<DOCNO> APW19991005.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-05 17:00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Length of Baseball Games Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- So much for commissioner Bud Selig's desire to  
quicken major league games. 
</P>
<P>
	The average time of a nine-inning game increased six minutes  
this year to 2:53, according to the Elias Sports Bureau, baseball's 
statistician. That's one minute short of the record length set in 
1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Selig became angry about the length of games during the 1997  
World Series between Florida and Cleveland. The average time was 
3:31 and Game 3 lasted 4:12. 
</P>
<P>
	``The `Unfinished Symphony' had a better chance of finishing  
before that game,'' Selig said at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, one of his consultants, Hall of Famer Frank  
Robinson, was assigned to monitor the length of games. 
</P>
<P>
	In February 1998, a memo was sent to teams outlining a series of  
steps to speed up games. The commissioner's office hoped it would 
shave 15 minutes off the average game time, which was 2:52 during 
the 1997 season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Umpires should not grant time for batters to step out of the  
box unless, in the umpire's judgment, it is absolutely necessary,'' 
the memo said. ``When given permission to leave the batter's box 
... batters may not step more than 3 feet from the batter's box.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The average dropped five minutes last year to 2:47, but  
enforcement seems to have slackened this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Length of games has mostly increased over the years. In 1981,  
the average was 2:33. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
