<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-05 12:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Agassi Wins at Swiss Indoors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BASEL, Switzerland (AP) -- World No. 1 Andre Agassi, the French  
and U.S. Open champion, began his bid for another title Tuesday, 
beating Jan Siemerink of the Netherlands 6-3, 6-4 at the Swiss 
Indoors. 
</P>
<P>
	Agassi, seeking his fifth title of the year, dominated from the  
start, his scintillating serve largely responsible for the victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Agassi opened the match with a love service game before serving  
three successive aces, then breaking to take a 4-3 lead. 
</P>
<P>
	In the second set, Agassi waited until 5-4 before breaking the  
Dutchman, still winless this season. The struggling Siemerink has 
slipped from 19th to 94th over the past nine months. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jan is a tough opponent. It's very deceiving,'' said Agassi,  
the losing finalist to Tim Henman last year. ``He makes you take 
tough shots, good shots early in the point. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's left-handed and I haven't played a lefty in quite a  
while. It's not always easy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In other first-round matches, Ukraine's Andrei Medvedev, who  
lost to Agassi in the French Open final, rallied to beat Russia's 
Marat Safin 2-6, 6-4, 7-6 (7-2). Medvedev, ranked 34th, is seeking 
his first title of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	American qualifier Chris Woodruff upset Austria's Stefan Koubek  
3-6, 6-2, 6-2 and Slovakia's Karol Kucera defeated Sweden's Thomas 
Johansson 7-5, 6-3. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
