<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Car Drives Into Lake Mich., 3 Die </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- By the time officers arrived, it was too late:  
The car with a mother and two of her children inside had sunk in 
about 17 feet of water after plunging into Lake Michigan. 
</P>
<P>
	``All we saw was bubbles coming up,'' Officer Frank Guerrero  
said, recounting the scene he and other officers encountered Monday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	Witnesses said the car veered off Lake Shore Drive, went slowly  
down some steps and paused before suddenly accelerating and diving 
into Monroe Harbor. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, police were investigating whether Shirley Combest  
intentionally drove her car into the dark, 59-degree water, killing 
herself, 8-year-old Shaniqua and 6-year-old John. 
</P>
<P>
	Police suspect it was a murder-suicide, in part because family  
members say the 33-year-old mother had a history of depression. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Combest had been under a doctor's care for depression a few  
months ago, said her mother, Ruthie Mae Combest. She said her 
daughter also was grieving over the death of an older sister in a 
car accident last month. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was taking it awful hard,'' the mother said.  
</P>
<P>
	But all Guerrero and Officer Edward Tribe knew Monday night was  
that people in the car were dying. With little time to think, they 
pulled off their boots and blue police sweaters, took off their 
guns and dove in. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got children, much older; they're the most precious thing  
I have.... That was about the first thing I thought of,'' Tribe 
said. ``I thought maybe there was a chance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both officers, overcome by the cold, had to be pulled out by  
other officers. Police divers got the victims out an hour later. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
