<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-05 07:31:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Indonesia Military Marks Army Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- The Indonesian military celebrated its  
54th anniversary today in the shadow of the East Timor crisis and 
ahead of the selection of a new president. 
</P>
<P>
	Children in the red and white of the Indonesian flag sang  
nationalist songs while performers in bright costumes interpreted 
Javanese mythology through dance. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of troops in fatigues, representing all branches of the  
military, marched and saluted President B.J. Habibie and Gen. 
Wiranto, the defense minister and leader of the military. Wiranto, 
like many Indonesians, uses only one name. 
</P>
<P>
	Habibie has been trying hard to keep his job, but his popularity  
has sunk as one crisis after another has hit since he took office 
in May 1998. A special assembly of legislators and government 
appointees will chose the next president on Oct. 20. 
</P>
<P>
	Habibie wants the assembly to adopt sweeping changes to  
Indonesia's 1945 constitution, including adoption of direct, 
popular election of the president. 
</P>
<P>
	At today's celebrations, he called on the army to maintain  
security and avoid excessive violence, but made no mention of East 
Timor. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesian troops have been widely blamed for participating in a  
violent purge in the territory after residents voted overwhelmingly 
on Aug. 30 to separate from Indonesia. 
</P>
<P>
	There has also been criticism at home for the way troops and  
police have handled demonstrations. Seven people died in two days 
of protests in Jakarta recently. 
</P>
<P>
	``Violence has become almost uncontrollable'' in Indonesia,  
Habibie said, calling on the army and police to use restraint. 
</P>
<P>
	The military and police hold 38 nonelected seats in the  
700-member People's Consultative Assembly. Because none of the 
three parties fielding candidates for president have enough seats 
to win a majority on their own, those seats could be enough to sway 
the vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Abdul Harris Nasution, a former general and the father of the  
``dual function'' doctrine that gives the army a place in politics, 
said the military's powers are excessive and the concept should be 
reviewed. 
</P>
<P>
	Wiranto and other generals said Monday that the army would  
remain neutral during the election process. 
</P>
<P>
	Wiranto issued a five-point decree to the military Monday  
calling for increased cooperation with the public. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
