<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Case Keeps Sprewell Away From Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) -- Latrell Sprewell stayed away from  
training camp for another day Tuesday, surprising the New York 
Knicks by waiting out the verdict in his civil suit in California. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprewell's agent had originally told the Knicks he would join  
the team following closing arguments in the trial, but the player 
then decided to wait for the jury to come back. 
</P>
<P>
	He was not present in court, however, when the verdict came in.  
There were no punitive damages, although Sprewell must pay $105,000 
to two people who were injured in a car accident that he admittedly 
caused. 
</P>
<P>
	``Well, we just hope he's here soon, and hopefully we'll hear  
soon what his plans are,'' general manager Scott Layden said 
following an evening practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprewell's agent, Robert Gist, did not return numerous phone  
calls. 
</P>
<P>
	The rest of the team went through a 3-hour, 40-minute practice  
Tuesday morning, followed by another long workout in the evening. 
</P>
<P>
	Two-a-day practices will continue through Friday, with the team  
flying back to New York following Saturday morning's practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Nobody with the Knicks knew exactly what to think Tuesday  
afternoon following the first practice. Sprewell failed to take a 
red-eye flight from the Bay area to the East Coast, which would 
have enabled him to be in Charleston by the morning, and Layden was 
only able to exchange phone messages with Sprewell's 
representatives. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want him here as soon as possible,'' coach Jeff Van Gundy  
said. ``Until I can talk to him, I don't know what the situation 
is. So I'm going to wait, talk to him and go from there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Late in the afternoon, Layden found out that Sprewell had  
decided to wait out the verdict. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, that's different from what we were told earlier,''  
he said. ``The attorney felt it was very important, almost 
critical, that he be there when it was with the jury.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sprewell was sued by Arnulfo Perlas, 55, and Irma Feliciano, 54,  
of Antioch, Calif., whose car overturned when Sprewell tried to 
drive his Mercedes-Benz back onto a freeway from an exit lane. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprewell pleaded no contest to reckless driving and was  
sentenced to 90 days in jail, which he served under electronic home 
detention in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The plaintiffs asked for $450,000 in actual damages, plus two  
months of his $9 million salary for the upcoming season in punitive 
damages. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprewell's attorney said the plaintiffs were trying to make  
minor injuries seem major and asked the jury to award $30,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Perlas was awarded about $75,000 for economic and non-economic  
damages. Feliciano was awarded $30,000, mostly in economic damages. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was just a matter of someone trying to get some money off a  
professional athete again,'' teammate Chris Childs said. ``I'm glad 
he got off and is able to go on with his life. to go through what 
he's been through the last couple of years, whenever he gets here 
it's understandable by his teammates.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
