<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former Sooners All-American Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPIRO, Okla. (AP) -- Rod Shoate, whose speed and strength helped  
make him a two-time All-American linebacker at Oklahoma during the 
1970s, has died after a long illness. He was 46. 
</P>
<P>
	Shoate died Monday at his home, where he farmed with his family.  
</P>
<P>
	Shoate earned All-American honors in 1973 and 1974. He later  
played with the New England Patriots and in the United States 
Football League. 
</P>
<P>
	During Shoate's playing days, Oklahoma coach Barry Switzer  
called him ``the best linebacker to don a Sooner uniform.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At Oklahoma, Shoate had 420 career tackles, ranking him third on  
the school's career list. He led the team in tackles in 1972, 1973 
and 1974. 
</P>
<P>
	He played for Sooners teams that went 29-4-1 and won the 1974  
national championship. Shoate finished seventh in the Heisman 
Trophy voting as a senior in 1974 and was one of four finalists for 
the Lombardi Award that year. 
</P>
<P>
	Shoate was drafted in the second round by the Patriots in 1975.  
He played in 76 games with the Patriots, starting 65. 
</P>
<P>
	Shoate was traded to the Chicago Bears in 1982 and released  
before the start of the season. He played in the USFL for New 
Jersey in 1983 and Memphis in 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	Services are scheduled Thursday at Mt. Triumph Baptist Church in  
nearby Fort Coffee. 
</P>
<P>
	Shoate is survived by his parents, Levester and Lula Shoate of  
Fort Coffee, five sisters and five brothers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
