<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Lighter Side of Business /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SHOP AROUND: That's the advice of Consumer Reports magazine for  
people with prescriptions to fill but whose health insurance 
doesn't cover medications. Consumer Reports compared the prices for 
commonly-prescribed drugs and found a big disparity among the 
amounts charged by drugstore chains, independent pharmacists, 
supermarkets, mass retailers like Wal-Mart and online or mail-order 
pharmacies. For example, a prescription for the anti-allergy drug 
Claritin averaged $60 at online and mail-order druggists and $84 at 
independent drugstores. The antibiotic Biaxin cost $46 online and 
through the mail, was $57 in drugstore chains and $59 at the 
independents. However, the magazine noted, while order through the 
Internet or mail generally will give you the best deal, if you're 
looking for extra service and face-to-face contact with the 
pharmacist, an independent store may be the place for you to shop. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	HALLOWEEN BUDGETS: With each year, Halloween is becoming a  
bigger holiday for American families and their Halloween budgets 
are growing accordingly. A survey by American Express found 
consumers will spend an average of $98 on Halloween candy, 
decorations and costumes for themselves and their children, up from 
$81 last year. Of that amount, $30 will be spent on candy, $22 on 
costumes, $16 on pumpkins, $11 on other decorations, $11 to attend 
parties or other functions and $8 on home entertaining. The survey 
found Snickers is the candy most likely to be handed out to 
trick-or-treaters, followed by candy corn, Reese's Peanut Butter 
Cups and Tootsie Rolls, Hershey's and M&AMP;Ms. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	A MARKETER'S DREAM: For years, the common wisdom was that people  
ages 18-34 made up the primary group for marketers to target. Some 
marketers aimed for a larger and somewhat older group, ages 18-49. 
But there is growing evidence that people age 50 and over with time 
and disposable income represent a great marketing opportunity, 
particularly when it comes to the leisure and sporting industries. 
The Sporting Goods Manufacturers Association reports that sales of 
exercise equipment to people between the ages of 45 and 64 rose 53 
percent in 1998. The trade association also notes a proliferation 
of clubs and groups for older people interested in fitness, and 
reports that people over 50 spend more time at health clubs than 
younger people do. The most popular fitness or athletic activities 
for older Americans are aquatic exercise, followed by fitness 
walking, golf, stationary cycling and cross-country skiing. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
