<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Teachers' Union Endorses Gore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore won endorsement Tuesday  
by the nation's second-largest teachers' union for his steadfast 
opposition to private-school vouchers. But the AFL-CIO's bigger 
prize remained an agonizingly open question for Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	With the AFL-CIO biennial convention looming next week, the  
Teamsters union stood ready to resist Gore's once-certain early nod 
from the federation. But labor and political operatives close to 
the wrangling said they believed Gore would overcome such 
resistance. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have taken a position that it's too early,'' said Teamsters  
political director Mike Mathis. ``This is not an anti-Al Gore 
thing. But there's still so much gray area out there on worker 
issues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at the United Auto Workers, Machinists, Food and  
Commercial Workers, and International Brotherhood of Electrical 
Workers also have signaled some reservations to backing Gore this 
early in a tightening Democratic nomination race with Bill Bradley. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, several leaders who have questioned an early endorsement  
of Gore have indicated to AFL-CIO President John Sweeney that they 
would be willing to support the vice president at the convention if 
Sweeney pushed for a vote, according to the officials who spoke on 
condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	``This all boils down to John Sweeney and whether he will push  
it through,'' said Mathis. 
</P>
<P>
	Sweeney did not tip his hand, telling The Washington Post: ``We  
are going through a process. ... There are some people who think we 
should take a little longer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A final decision wasn't expected until after the union  
presidents who comprise the federation's executive council meet 
Friday in advance of the convention, which convenes in Los Angeles 
on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore and Bradley continue to fight intensively for the  
endorsement. Neither was scheduled to address the convention, but 
both were planning to be in California with open space on their 
schedules. 
</P>
<P>
	The executive council of the American Federation of Teachers,  
which represents nearly a million teachers, mostly in the nation's 
largest school districts, overwhelmingly endorsed Gore on Tuesday. 
There was one abstention among the 38 members, said spokesman 
Gregory King. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a very positive endorsement of Al Gore on the record,  
not an endorsement against anyone,'' said Sandra Feldman, president 
of the AFT, who said the endorsement has support from the larger 
membership, which was polled earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore, like the teachers unions, opposes voucher programs.  
Bradley has voted for school voucher experiments but has said he 
doesn't believe they are the solution to fundamental problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Feldman said the endorsement is more about supporting Gore and  
less about punishing Bradley: ``We're not using that (the voucher 
issue) as a single-issue litmus test at all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the Republican presidential candidates favor voucher  
programs. Front-runner George W. Bush has steadily touted vouchers, 
which in some parts of the country are providing public money for 
private education. In a speech Tuesday, he suggested money from the 
nation's largest federal education program could be used to fund 
state voucher programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush campaign spokesman Scott McClellan said, ``We expect  
(Texas) Governor Bush to receive many endorsements from individual 
teachers but we are not surprised that an entrenched organization 
that has defended the status quo would endorse Al Gore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The National Education Association, the nation's largest  
teachers' union with 2.4 million members, may issue an endorsement 
as early as Friday, said spokeswoman Kathleen Lyons. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore and Bradley have fought for the favor of the traditional  
Democrat stronghold of organized labor, with Bradley waging a 
tougher-than-expected challenge to Gore's institutional support. 
Gore allies have been pushing for the AFL-CIO endorsement since 
February, and the Bradley camp claims a small victory in 
forestalling them. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're certainly making a case to labor and have throughout the  
campaign, said Bradley campaign spokesman Eric Hauser. ``They 
haven't made an endorsement yet; we'll keep making a case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The AFT nod, some observers say, may have come early in an  
attempt to prod its parent organization, the AFL-CIO, and other 
labor organizations into issuing endorsements. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we'll be playing a strong role in trying to make that  
happen,'' said Feldman. 
</P>
<P>
	Late Tuesday, Gore's campaign said he had won endorsement by the  
International Association of Washington State Machinists. A 
campaign news release noted that ``the organization is the largest 
machinists union in the country, with more than 50,000 members 
statewide.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
