<DOCNO> APW19991005.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-05 16:30:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Red Sox Play Down Games Vs. Indians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Who are these Cleveland Indians who went 4-8  
with a .236 batting average against the Boston Red Sox?. 
</P>
<P>
	Certainly not the fearsome Indians who are one of only seven  
teams in major league history to score more than 1,000 runs in a 
season. And definitely not the determined Indians the Red Sox 
expect to see in the division series starting Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know what? Those games are already played, those days are  
gone,'' Boston Game 1 starter Pedro Martinez said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Those were the days when Cleveland's Manny Ramirez managed just  
three RBIs in eight games against Boston. He had 162 RBIs in his 
other 139 games. 
</P>
<P>
	Those were the days when Boston's Nomar Garciaparra hit. 451  
with five homers in 12 games against Cleveland. He hit 22 homers in 
his other 123 games and led the AL with a .357 average. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just happens,'' Garciaparra said of his success against  
Cleveland. ``I don't even know what I've done statistically.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Statistics show just how meaningless regular season performances  
can be. The Red Sox were 8-3 against the Indians last season then 
lost the division series to them 3-1. 
</P>
<P>
	End of discussion.  
</P>
<P>
	``It would probably make a difference if you were 0-12,'' said  
Mike Stanley, who hit .281 this season but .344 against Cleveland. 
``But we know they're a tough team. They scored 1,000 runs this 
year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``They have a lot of talent and there are games that they lose  
during the regular season you wonder why they lose them,'' John 
Valentin said, ``but I think in the playoffs they're going to be 
ready.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The nicked up left side of Boston's infield, Valentin and  
Garciaparra, should be ready. Valentin was on the disabled list 
from Aug. 31 to Sept. 23 with tendinitis in his left knee. 
Garciaparra missed the last five games with a bruised right wrist 
after he was hit by a pitch. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, after his first workout since he played in the  
wild-card clincher last Wednesday in Chicago, he was as eager to 
talk about his condition as he is to strike out. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel fine,'' Garciaparra said repeatedly, his eyes looking  
past his questioners and his wrist wrapped in ice. 
</P>
<P>
	``He took batting practice today and he stayed out there for the  
complete round,'' manager Jimy Williams said. ``He's going to play. 
But is he 100 percent? No. But I don't think anybody in either 
dugout is 100 percent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams is taking precautions in case the wrist gets worse. In  
fact, Valentin's knee and the health of starters Bret Saberhagen, 
Ramon Martinez and Kent Mercker influenced Williams' roster 
decisions. 
</P>
<P>
	Saberhagen has been pitching with a cranky shoulder, Ramon  
Martinez missed more than a year following shoulder surgery and 
Mercker spent 16 days on the disabled list last month with a 
strained rib cage. 
</P>
<P>
	So Williams kept 11 pitchers instead of the 10 he went with a  
year ago and is carrying two spare infielders, Donnie Sadler and 
Lou Merloni. 
</P>
<P>
	But they're quite a dropoff from Garciaparra, who has a .392  
career average against the Indians. He's not the only Boston hitter 
who enjoys facing Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	Troy O'Leary hit .280 this season but .353 against the Indians.  
Jose Offerman, a .294 hitter, hit .347 against them. As a team, 
Boston hit .278 this season, but .300 against Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	The dominance extended to the pitching staff. The Indians are  
just 6-for-84, an .071 batting average, against relievers Derek 
Lowe, Rheal Cormier, Rich Garces, Rod Beck, John Wasdin and Tom 
Gordon. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indians averaged 6.2 runs per game but only 4.5 against the  
Red Sox. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this time of year, you have to delete all that stuff,''  
Boston's Darren Lewis said. ``You can break it down and analyze the 
numbers any way you want, but this time of year, anything can 
happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As the Red Sox found out at this time last year.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think we beat them quite a bit last year, too, during the  
regular season,'' Garciaparra said. ``Then we went home early. So 
it's irrelevant.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
