<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Oct. 5, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Annan Wants UN Force in E. Timor  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- With East Timor's government structures  
destroyed, the U.N. chief outlined a plan to take control and 
protect the territory with a 9,000-strong peacekeeping force. ``The 
situation in East Timor is critical,'' Secretary-General Kofi Annan 
said in a report outlining his proposals to send in U.N. 
peacekeepers until the territory becomes independent in about two 
to three years. U.N. troops would replace the Australian-led force 
sent last month to rein in rampaging pro-Indonesian militias after 
the vote for independence. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Co. To Pay for Nuke Damages  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- A Japanese company promised Tuesday to pay damages  
for the victims of the country's worst nuclear accident, which 
exposed dozens of people to radiation and forced hundreds of 
thousands of others to stay indoors. Government investigators again 
searched the offices of the plant's operator, JCO Co., and the 
plant site 70 miles northeast of Tokyo to look for evidence of 
wrongdoing behind Thursday's disaster, which sent three workers to 
the hospital. The authorities reportedly suspect negligence and 
violation of rules. 

</P>
<P>
	House Approves Foreign Aid Bill  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House narrowly passed a $12.6 billion  
fiscal 2000 foreign aid bill today that the White House has 
threatened to veto on grounds that it shortchanges vital 
international programs. The bill was approved 214-211, all but 
ensuring that a veto would be sustained. The Senate has yet to take 
up the bill. 

</P>
<P>
	Annan Says UN Needs Reform  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Secretary-General Kofi Annan said today  
the U.N. still has too many administrators and rules, and too 
little money. Member countries, primarily the United States, owed 
the United Nations more than $2 billion, he said. Unpaid dues and 
bureaucratic delays have made it virtually impossible for the U.N. 
to respond quickly to crises like those in Kosovo and East Timor, 
he said. 

</P>
<P>
	UAW Sets Deadline for Ford Talks  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The United Auto Workers today in effect set a  
strike deadline of 3:30 p.m. Friday against Ford Motor Co., saying 
it would not extend its contract beyond then -- a sign talks could 
be intensifying. A spokesman for Ford said the union made the 
decision and talks recessed for the day. Negotiations on a new 
contract to cover about 100,000 employees were scheduled to resume 
tomorrow. 

</P>
<P>
	Money Laundering Charges Filed  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Federal prosecutors say $7 billion from Russia  
was illegally funneled through accounts at the Bank of New York in 
one of the largest money laundering cases in U.S. history. Three 
individuals and three companies were charged with channelling the 
money -- believed to have ties to the Russian mafia -- in the first 
criminal charges to be brought in the case. The Bank of New York, 
the nation's 15th-largest bank, was not named in the indictments. 

</P>
<P>
	London Trains Crash, Killing 26  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Two London commuter trains collided Tuesday during  
rush hour, killing 26 passengers and injuring 160. It was Britain's 
worst train accident in more than a decade. The accident took place 
in the Ladbroke Grove residential area in west London. 

</P>
<P>
	Floods Kill 19 in Mexico  
</P>
<P>
	VILLAHERMOSA, Mexico (AP) -- The Mexican government declared a  
state of emergency Tuesday in four states where the worst flooding 
in 40 years has killed at least 19 people and forced the evacuation 
of more than 100,000 others. Officials declared a state of 
emergency in the Pacific states of Michoacan and Jalisco, the 
central state of Puebla and the Gulf coast state of Tabasco. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Climber Feared Dead in Tibet  
</P>
<P>
	BOZEMAN, Mont. (AP) -- Alex Lowe, described by Outside magazine  
as the best mountain climber in the world, was presumed dead 
Tuesday with another climber in a Himalayan avalanche, the 
expedition announced. Dispatch from the American Shishapangma Ski 
Expedition, posted on the Web site MountainZone.com, said the 
climbers were struck by an avalanche on 26,291-foot Shishapangma in 
Tibet. 

</P>
<P>
	Stock Prices Rise in Japan  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Stock prices opened higher on Wednesday in Japan.  
The Nikkei rose 65.36 points to 17,849.51 in early trading. In New 
York, the Dow ended 0.64 lower at 10,400.59 after the Federal 
Reserve decided against raising interest rates but left open the 
possibility of a third rate hike later this year. 

</P>
<P>
	Astros Top Braves in NL Playoffs  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The Houston Astros posted a 6-1 victory vs. the  
Atlanta Braves today in Game 1 of their NL playoff series. 
Houston's Daryle Ward hit a leadoff homer against Greg Maddux in 
the sixth inning to break a 1-1 tie. The Astros got four runs in 
the ninth, topped by Ken Caminiti's three-run homer. Houston 
starter Shane Reynolds and three Astros relievers held the Braves 
to seven hits. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
