<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Michigan Utility Cos. To Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Two major Michigan utilities are combining in a  
$2.6 billion deal that will create the state's largest electric and 
gas company. 
</P>
<P>
	DTE Energy Co., parent of Detroit Edison Co., will buy MCN  
Energy Group Inc., parent of Michigan Consolidated Gas Co., for 
$28.50 per share in cash and stock. DTE will also assume about $2 
billion in MCN debt in the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	The new company, DTE Energy, will remain based in Detroit and  
have more than 3 million customers. 
</P>
<P>
	``This really is a home run. It creates an energy powerhouse in  
the Midwest,'' said Anthony Earley Jr., DTE president and chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	Industry analyst Frederick Schultz of Raymond James &AMP; Associates  
said the combination was good for both companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``It makes DTE a big regional combination utility. Now they have  
the summer-peaking electric earnings and the winter-peaking gas 
earnings,'' he said Tuesday from his Houston office. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Heim, an analyst with A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons, Inc. in St.  
Louis, said the arrangement ``seems to make good strategic sense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Investors pushed shares of MCN up $5.87 1/2 to $23.56 1/4, while  
dropping shares of DTE $3.87 1/2 to $33.12 1/2 in trading on the New York 
Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The boards of both companies have already approved the deal,  
which is subject to approval from shareholders and regulators. The 
utilities together will have about 11,500 employees when the 
transaction is complete, expected in six to nine months. 
</P>
<P>
	DTE expects to trim its work force by about 500 jobs as it cuts  
$60 million in costs by eliminating overlap, Earley said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the job cuts are expected to come through attrition, early  
retirement, voluntary buyouts and decreased hiring, said MCN 
chairman Alfred Glancy III, who will retire when the deal is 
complete but join the DTE board. 
</P>
<P>
	Deregulation is fueling the deal, as well as others in the  
industry, by increasing competition, Earley said. 
</P>
<P>
	In other recent utility mergers, Illinois-based Commonwealth  
Edison's parent is seeking a combination with Philadelphia-based 
PECO Energy Co. to create a company with 5 million customers in two 
states. 
</P>
<P>
	Carolina Power &AMP; Light Co. is buying Florida Progress Corp. for  
$5.3 billion, creating the nation's ninth-largest electric utility. 
</P>
<P>
	DTE will be able to market coal, gas and electricity in the  
region and to compete more effectively in the development of new 
power plants and distributed generation, Earley said. 
</P>
<P>
	And DTE will keep an eye out for more acquisitions.  
</P>
<P>
	``Now it's going to be much easier to expand,'' Earley said.  
``We will look for growth opportunities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When the transaction is complete, DTE will serve 2.1 million  
electric customers and 1.2 million natural gas customers in 
Michigan. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991005.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-05 07:54:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Braves, Astros Ready for series </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The Atlanta Braves relaxed in front on their  
television sets, wondering who they would play today. The Houston 
Astros sat on a runway, wondering if their plane would fly east or 
west? 
</P>
<P>
	About 10 o'clock Monday night, both teams finally got the  
answer. 
</P>
<P>
	The NL Central champion Astros, their travel plans in shambles  
because of a wild-card playoff game in Cincinnati, didn't learn 
they would play the Braves in the best-of-5 division series until 
the Reds lost 5-0 to the New York Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	That sent the New Yorkers to Arizona, while the Astros turned  
their charter jet eastward and headed toward Atlanta to meet the 
team that has eight straight division titles and baseball's best 
record at 103-59. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know I wouldn't want to play a game after flying to Arizona  
or coming here,'' Braves MVP candidate Chipper Jones said. ``That 
takes a toll on your body. It usually takes a day or two to 
regroup.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The closest the Braves got to a plane was Javy Lopez's  
remote-control version. 
</P>
<P>
	When rain wiped out a scheduled workout at Turner Field, the  
injured Atlanta catcher broke out his model aircraft, the stadium's 
vast expanse giving him plenty of room for a series of twisting, 
spinning maneuvers. 
</P>
<P>
	Greg Maddux (19-9), who will start the opener for Atlanta  
against Shane Reynolds (16-14), spent the night watching videos 
from his recent performances against both Houston and Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	If Cincinnati had won the playoff, Atlanta would have met the  
Reds and Houston would have played Arizona in the other division 
series. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would prefer to know,'' Maddux said earlier Monday. ``But I  
would prefer there be no traffic when I come to the park, too. It's 
really not that big a deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not after what the Braves went through this year. They lost  
cleanup hitter Andres Galarraga and closer Kerry Ligtenberg before 
opening day, while Lopez and pitchers Odalis Perez and Rudy Seanez 
went down during the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a grittier, guttier team,'' Jones said. ``We're not  
going to pop anybody's eyes out. We don't have the firepower of 
some of our other teams. But we do the little things to score 
runs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Every year about this time, the Braves face questions about  
their lack of postseason success. Despite eight straight 
appearances -- three more than any team in baseball history -- they 
have won just one World Series title in the 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the dark cloud that always hangs over the Braves,''  
said Brian Jordan, who brought emotion to the clubhouse, not to 
mention a career-high 115 RBIs. ``Hopefully, this is the year we 
get the breaks and finally win another world championship. If not, 
we've still exceeded our expectations this season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Houston clinched its third straight NL Central title on the  
final day of the regular season, finishing one game ahead of 
Cincinnati. The Astros have been quickly eliminated in their last 
two playoff trips, a sweep by Atlanta in 1997 and a 3-1 loss to San 
Diego last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first year it was new and maybe a little overwhelming.  
Last year we weren't able to do a lot,'' manager Larry Dierker 
said. ``This year, all we're ready to do is go out and play the 
best baseball we can. If it's 3-0 again, well, we're going to give 
it our best.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Astros didn't seem concerned about their late-night travel  
plans. 
</P>
<P>
	``This won't bother them,'' general manager Gerry Hunsicker  
said. ``I don't think anything can happen to this club that hasn't 
already happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like the Braves, Houston survived a devastating medical report.  
Moises Alou missed the entire season, while Derek Bell and Ken 
Caminiti were plagued by injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're the underdogs and maybe that's good,'' Reynolds said.  
``Everyone expects them to win, so let them have all the 
pressure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Astros went 1-6 against the Braves during the regular  
season, including a three-game sweep at the Turner Field, site of 
Games 1 and 2. The series shifts to Astrodome on Friday for Game 3. 
</P>
<P>
	The first of Houston's 20-game winners, Jose Lima (21-10), faces  
Kevin Millwood (18-7, 2.68 ERA) in Wednesday's game. Cy Young 
contender Mike Hampton (22-4) follows for the Astros against last 
year's Cy Young winner, Tom Glavine (13-11). 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the credit for the Braves' success must go to manager  
Bobby Cox, who businesslike demeanor was criticized in the past, 
but served the team well when one player after another went down. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bobby didn't panic,'' Millwood said. ``We just went about our  
business the way we always have.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991005.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-05 18:30:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hungarian Baron's Relative Sues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARMONK, N.Y. (AP) -- The granddaughter of a Hungarian baron filed  
a lawsuit against that country's government Tuesday, demanding the 
return of family art treasures seized by invading Nazis a 
half-century ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit, filed in Budapest, follows three years of  
unproductive negotiations, said the plaintiff, Martha Nierenberg of 
Armonk. 
</P>
<P>
	``They kept stalling and stalling and stalling,'' she said in an  
interview. ``I'm 75 years old and as it is with these things, they 
were just waiting for me to give up, to go away, to die.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She called the paintings ``the last prisoners of World War II.''  
</P>
<P>
	Sandor Beer, the Hungarian consul in New York, said he had not  
seen the suit and had no comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Nierenberg is the granddaughter of Baron Maurice Herzog,  
who amassed a 2,500-item art collection between the world wars, 
including paintings attributed to El Greco, Velazquez and Courbet. 
The collection has been appraised at more than $20 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Nierenberg said she remembered many visits during her  
childhood to the baron's home in Budapest. 
</P>
<P>
	``His house was like a museum,'' she said. ``I was there often  
and I was always a little bit annoyed because I would want to sit 
down on a chair, and I would hear, `Oh, no, you can't sit down on 
that chair, that's 12th century.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The baron died in 1934, dividing his estate among his three  
children, including Mrs. Nierenberg's mother. But in 1944, under 
the direction of Adolf Eichmann, the best pieces were sent off to 
Germany as Mrs. Nierenberg's Jewish family fled Hungary, the court 
papers say. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the art was returned to Hungary after the war. But  
because Mrs. Nierenberg's mother was in the United States by then, 
the pieces that had been left to her were sent to the major 
government museums in Budapest under a ``safekeeping'' law. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Nierenberg's lawyer, Glen Young, said the Hungarian law was  
clear. 
</P>
<P>
	``She owns the paintings. They were never nationalized by the  
government, never taken or appropriated,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
