<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bengals and Browns Both 0-4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Playing the Cleveland Browns doesn't have  
quite the feel of years past for the Cincinnati Bengals. 
</P>
<P>
	But for the winless Bengals and a coach trying to keep his job,  
every game is big. The Bengals and Browns both have 0-4 records. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think every week is a big week, whether it's the Browns or  
anybody else,'' Bengals coach Bruce Coslet said. ``Consider the 
state of the Bengals. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you go back through the history of the rivalry, it isn't  
that. It may be some day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coslet should know. He was a tight end for Cincinnati during the  
1970s under coach Paul Brown, who started and built the Bengals 
after Art Modell, owner of the old Browns, had fired him. Brown 
died in 1991, Modell's team now is the Baltimore Ravens and the new 
Browns are an expansion team. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Bengals, coming off their fourth 3-13 season of the  
1990s, lack the luxury to take anything for granted. 
</P>
<P>
	``We mentally can't slack on anybody,'' offensive lineman Brian  
DeMarco said. 
</P>
<P>
	DeMarco is looking forward to the game at Cleveland, near his  
hometown of Lorain. He recalled having bought 125 tickets for 
family and friends one season when he played for the Jacksonville 
Jaguars in Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	``I won't do that again,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	DeMarco, signed for his ability to block for running plays,  
wants to see the Bengals run the ball more. But Cincinnati is 
coming off three consecutive big losses when it had to resort to 
passing in attempts to catch up. 
</P>
<P>
	Bengals players share the blame for the skid, DeMarco said. He  
had no simple answers for how to correct the slide, other than to 
suggest that each player needs to perform better. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody's got to pick it up,'' he said. ``We've got to look  
in the mirror.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bengals need a vocal leader, running back Corey Dillon said.  
</P>
<P>
	``The team's looking for leadership,'' said Dillon, who  
expressed frustration that he isn't being given more chances to run 
the ball. ``I try to lead by example. I'm doing all I can.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
