<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mattel Debt Rating May Be Downgraded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Standard &AMP; Poor's said Tuesday it is  
considering lowering the debt rating of Mattel Inc. following the 
toy company's surprise warning that its earnings will fall sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	If the rating is lowered by the major business information  
service, investors will view Mattel bonds as riskier and will 
demand higher interest rates for lending the company money, 
increasing Mattel's expenses. 
</P>
<P>
	Mattel, the world's largest toymaker, announced on Monday that  
it expects its software subsidiary, The Learning Company, to lose 
$50 million to $100 million. That would push Mattel earnings per 
share into the 30 cent to 40 cent range in the third quarter. Wall 
Street analysts had expected 67 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	Mattel blamed the loss on high product returns, the write-off of  
bad debt and other difficulties at the software business. 
</P>
<P>
	The Learning Company wasn't Mattel's only problem, S&AMP;P said in a  
news release. 
</P>
<P>
	``Additionally, Mattel's profitability has been lackluster in  
the first half of 1999, partly due to a 2 percent sales decline in 
Barbie products, the company's largest line,'' the release said. 
``... Standard &AMP; Poor's will evaluate Mattel's business strategies 
and operating outlook in reassessing the ratings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The rating agency placed Mattel on its ``Credit Watch'' with a  
negative assessment. 
</P>
<P>
	Mattel now has an A-minus rating on its longterm bonds. S&AMP;P's  
top rating is AAA, and a single-A rating is its third-highest 
letter grade. S&AMP;P uses plus and minus signs to denote standing 
within each grade. 
</P>
<P>
	The next lowest grade would be BBB-plus. The triple-B rating is  
the lowest ``investment grade.'' Anything at double-B or lower is 
considered speculative or ``junk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mattel stock rebounded on Tuesday after sinking on Monday to its  
lowest level since 1993. Mattel shares gained 87 1/2 cents to close at 
$12.75 a share on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Mattel acquired The Learning Company in May for $3.5 billion in  
stock as part of a campaign to expand into electronic and 
interactive toys. 





</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991005.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-05 15:10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ravens Coach Promises Not To Curse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- It's either wash out his own mouth with soap or  
fine himself. One way or another, Baltimore Ravens coach Brian 
Billick plans to stop using foul language on the sidelines. 
</P>
<P>
	Billick was scolded by his mother, wife and daughter following  
the Baltimore Ravens' 19-13 overtime victory over the Atlanta 
Falcons on Sunday. The television cameras showed Billick yelling at 
his players, and apparently it wasn't too difficult to read his 
lips. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a short-lived win for me. As soon as I got from the  
lockerroom to the bus, I called my mother as I normally do. I got a 
15-minute butt-chewing for my foul language on the sidelines,'' 
Billick said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I then go home to the refuge I go to and had my wife ream me  
for a good half-hour, followed by my 10-year-old daughter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So Billick, whose career as an NFL head coach is barely a month  
old, has installed a new code of conduct -- for himself. 
</P>
<P>
	``Henceforth, I'm counting on you guys to be the guardians of  
the faith here,'' he said to the media. He pledged to fine himself 
$100 if he's caught using a certain obscenity. 
</P>
<P>
	``So we'll see if I clean that up and find some other euphemisms  
to convey the same point,'' Billick said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said all money he fined himself would be given to charity.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
