<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Split on Contribution Limits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Twenty-three years after helping reshape the  
political landscape by approving limits on campaign contributions, 
the Supreme Court appeared deeply split Tuesday over the wisdom and 
constitutionality of continuing such restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	Through rapid-fire questions and comments to lawyers, the  
justices debated the virtues and vices of limiting political 
spending, a form of speech, to deter corruption. Congress will take 
up a similar debate next week. 
</P>
<P>
	While one justice said he assumed big contributors ``get  
something extraordinary in return,'' another extolled a wealthy 
person's right ``to participate in the democratic process as fully 
as he is able.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With members of Congress among the courtroom crowd, the court  
probed the constitutionality of Missouri's contribution limits in 
state races. The justices' eventual decision, expected by late 
June, likely will affect limits imposed for federal elections and 
races in two-thirds of the states. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote could be very close. Justices David H. Souter, Ruth  
Bader Ginsburg, Stephen G. Breyer and John Paul Stevens seemed most 
sympathetic to allowing limits. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justice Antonin Scalia  
seemed least sympathetic. In previous writings, Justice Clarence 
Thomas supported overturning the court's 1976 decision to uphold 
contribution limits. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision, as in many of the court's most divisive cases,  
could hinge on the votes of Justices Sandra Day O'Connor and 
Anthony M. Kennedy. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Connor voiced some doubts about Missouri's purpose -- fighting  
corruption or the perception of corruption. If someone makes a 
donation in the hope a candidate, if elected, ``will pay attention 
to me, does that give rise to enough of a negative picture to 
justify state regulation?'' she asked. 
</P>
<P>
	Missouri Attorney General Jay Nixon answered no, but Souter  
suggested that large contributions always raise the possibility of 
corruption. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most people assume -- I do, certainly -- that someone making an  
extraordinarily large contribution is going to get something 
extraordinary in return,'' Souter said. 
</P>
<P>
	Breyer said that if a rich man contributed $15 million, ``the  
public might think he owns that candidate.'' But Scalia countered 
by suggesting a wealthy person has a right to contribute ``as fully 
as he is able.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stevens asked whether it was ``reasonable for the people of  
Missouri to think everyone should have the same access (to public 
officials) and seek to avoid ``an appearance of unequal treatment 
that borders on corruption.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nixon was joined by Solicitor General Seth Waxman, arguing for  
the Clinton administration, in urging the justices to reinstate 
Missouri's limits. The limits were struck down as violations of the 
free-speech rights of candidates and contributors alike. 
</P>
<P>
	``If a contribution is speech, it's hard to say speech is a  
subversion of the political process,'' Kennedy told Waxman. But the 
government lawyer responded, ``The potential for corruption comes 
from the nonspeech element of the large contribution.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In its 1976 decision, called Buckley vs. Valeo, the Supreme  
Court said free-speech rights trump any attempt to limit an 
individual candidate's spending. But that ruling drew a distinction 
between spending, which cannot be capped, and contributions, for 
which it upheld a $1,000 limit on individual contributions in 
federal elections. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1976 ruling focused on a federal law enacted after the  
Watergate scandal of the early 1970s. The Missouri limits -- also 
$1,000 before being adjusted to $1,075 -- were not imposed until 
1994. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal appeals court ruled that inflation had eroded the  
limits' fairness, and Missouri had not proved that larger donations 
corrupt elections. 
</P>
<P>
	St. Louis lawyer D. Bruce La Pierre argued that the appeals  
court was right. ``The government should not limit the voices of 
some to amplify the voices of others,'' he said. ``We can try 
trusting the American public'' to decide when political candidates 
are taking too much money from any one contributor. 
</P>
<P>
	But Nixon warned the court that ending contribution limits would  
lead most Americans ``to believe that their government is literally 
for sale.'' He added: ``The system has been vibrant and alive 
across the country with these limits in place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among members of Congress on hand to listen to the debate were  
Russell Feingold, D-Wis., and Jack Reed, D-R.I., supporters of 
federal campaign-finance changes. Also present was Sen. Mitch 
McConnell, R-Ky., who supports increasing federal contribution 
limits to $3,000 when campaign-finance legislation is considered 
next week. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
