<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Chides GOP on Social Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican presidential candidate George W.  
Bush today criticized his own party's record on social issues, as 
he proposed mandatory state testing of students to ensure that 
schools are performing up to standard. 
</P>
<P>
	Expanding on his education agenda, Bush tied federal education  
money to student testing. He proposed requiring all states to 
develop and administer annual tests for students in grades three to 
eight. He also would require the states to participate in the 
National Assessment of Educational Progress, a federal program that 
tests a random sampling of students every two to four years. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans have long been critical of any expanded federal role  
in education, particularly mandatory testing. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking to the Manhattan Institute, a conservative thinktank,  
Bush noted that ``education reform is gaining a critical mass of 
results. In the process, conservatism has become the creed of hope, 
the creed of aggressive, persistent reform, the creed of social 
progress.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said that was a change for the GOP.  
</P>
<P>
	``Too often on social issues my party has painted an image of  
America slouching toward Gomorrah. ... Too often my party has 
focused on the national economy to the exclusion of all else. ... 
Too often my party has confused the need for limited government 
with the disdain for government itself,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second time in two weeks that Bush has stung his own  
party with criticism. The Texas governor drew the ire of 
congressional Republicans last week when he criticized their plans 
to squeeze money from a program for the working poor to meet budget 
targets. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said the nation needs to rebuild its approach to education  
with ``pressure from above and competition from below.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Toward that end, he proposed a tenfold increase in the size of  
tax-free savings accounts that parents can establish for 
educational expenses. The current maximum annual contribution would 
rise from $500 to $5,000. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Bush called for a $500 million Achievement and  
Education Fund to reward improving school systems, and a $3 billion 
Charter School Homestead Fund to provide loan guarantees to help 
start or improve charter schools. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush singled out the Elementary and Secondary Education Act of  
1965 as a program that needs revisions. The $13.9 billion program, 
which is up for reauthorization in Congress, provides grants for 
elementary and secondary programs under 60 categories. 
</P>
<P>
	He would streamline them into five general categories so states  
can tailor programs to their unique needs. Under the plan, money 
could be spent to improve the achievement of disadvantaged 
children; promote fluency in English; train and recruit teachers; 
encourage student character and school safety; and promote 
innovation and informed parental choice. 
</P>
<P>
	Under his plan, federal money could be used to fund state  
voucher programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Voucher programs are strongly opposed by teacher unions and  
Democratic candidates such as Vice President Al Gore. Bill Bradley, 
Gore's rival for the Democratic presidential nomination, has voted 
for voucher experiments but doesn't believe they are the solution 
to fundamental educational problems. Most of the GOP candidates 
favor voucher systems. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore was endorsed today by the American Federation of Teachers,  
the nation's second largest teachers' union. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton has proposed national student testing, but  
Republicans in Congress used their majority to block the 
legislation. Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said the governor views 
the NAEP test merely as an ``audit'' that would verify the state 
test results. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said states whose schools show no improvement after five  
years, as measured by the tests, would lose 5 percent of the 
administrative portion of their ESEA grants. States that improve 
would be eligible for money from the Achievement and Education 
Fund, which would be bolstered with $500 million over five years. 
</P>
<P>
	Test results would be distributed over the Internet.  
</P>
<P>
	``Without testing, reform is a journey without a compass,'' Bush  
said in the second three planned education speeches. ``Without 
testing, teachers and administrators cannot adjust their methods to 
meet high goals. ...Without testing, parents are left in the 
dark.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush also wants to increase the number of charter schools --  
privately run schools that receive public money -- to give parents 
another education option. His $3 billion Homestead program would 
provide seed money for up to 2,000 such schools. 
</P>
<P>
	``As president, I want to fan the spark of charter schools into  
a flame,'' Bush said. ``If charters are done properly -- free to 
hire their own teachers, adopt their own curriculum, set their own 
operating rules and high standards -- they will change the face of 
American education.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush also proposed increasing the federal allowance for  
education savings from $500 per year to $5,000. Under a 1997 law, 
parents can make contributions to the accounts as if they were 
paying into an IRA. The money can be withdrawn tax-free for college 
expenses. Eligibility for the program starts to phase out for 
single taxpayers earning $95,000 and couples earning $150,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush would let parents spend the money for kindergarten through  
college. His campaign projects that the expansion would cost the 
Treasury $92 million in revenue in the first year and more than $1 
billion by 2008. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
