<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NBC Acquires Triple Crown Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- For years, NBC television has programmed NBA  
playoff games opposite thoroughbred racing's Triple Crown series. 
Now those games will serve as a lead-in for the Kentucky Derby, 
Preakness and Belmont Stakes. 
</P>
<P>
	The network reached a five-year agreement to televise the races  
beginning in 2001. Dick Ebersol, chairman of NBC Sports, said the 
NBA lead-in would increase ratings for the races by 15 to 20 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly, the NBA has posed a problem for thoroughbred  
racing,'' said Thomas Meeker, president of Triple Crown 
Productions. ``Not having that competition will enhance our ability 
to attract new viewers to our sport.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ebersol said a second-round NBA playoff game would precede  
coverage of the Derby, and it's likely there would be games shown 
before both the Preakness and Belmont. 
</P>
<P>
	Negotiations for the Triple Crown package, which cost NBC a  
reported $51.5 million, were completed in less than eight days. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal adds the spring 3-year-old series to the Breeders' Cup,  
which has been an NBC property since its inception. ``It offers all 
kinds of packaging possibilities,'' Ebersol said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ebersol said NBC also was committed to coverage of the prep  
races that lead up to the Derby, either on its cable channels or 
other cable systems. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are thrilled to be joining the NBC Sports family,'' Meeker  
said. ``We have always been extremely impressed by the passion with 
which NBC approaches all of its properties and how it has telecast 
the Olympics, the NBA and the Ryder Cup.'' 
</P>
<P>
	ABC, which has televised the Derby since 1975 and covered all  
three races since 1987, has one more year remaining on its contract 
for the series. It reportedly bid $35 million to retain the 
contract. CBS, which provided the first national telecast of the 
Derby in 1952 and added the Preakness and Belmont in 1960, offered 
a reported $28 million. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
