<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mitchell: N. Ireland Talks In Peril </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) -- Northern Ireland's peace process is under  
great stress because of stubborn disagreements between two key 
parties, and may collapse, American mediator George Mitchell said 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The review I am engaged upon will be concluded in the near  
future. I have not set a specific time, but I do not intend this to 
be an open-ended process,'' Mitchell said in a speech to a banking 
conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitchell, a former U.S. senator, chaired the negotiations that  
produced the Good Friday 1998 agreement on forming a new 
Protestant-Catholic government for Northern Ireland. 
</P>
<P>
	That government has not been formed because the Ulster  
Unionists, the province's major Protestant party, are demanding 
that the Irish Republican Army begin to disarm before its allied 
Sinn Fein party can take part in the government. The IRA has 
refused to start surrendering its weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	The British and Irish governments asked Mitchell to return to  
Northern Ireland to seek a way out of the impasse. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it is beyond dispute that the peace process is under  
stress,'' Mitchell said in his speech. ``The outcome is not 
assured. I hope that there will be full implementation of the 
agreement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He added: ``There is no credible alternative to the Good Friday  
Agreement. If it is not implemented, I think the people in Northern 
Ireland face a highly uncertain future.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
