<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Antismoking Group Sues Tobacco Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- An antismoking group sued three tobacco  
companies on Tuesday, asking that the federal court require them to 
establish a $330 million fund to help prevent smoking-related 
illness. 
</P>
<P>
	Tobacco Control Coalition Inc. accused Philip Morris, Rothmans  
and WD&AMP;HO Wills, Australia's three largest tobacco companies, in 
the suit of misleading or deceptive conduct. 
</P>
<P>
	The coalition also wants health and medical groups to be  
reimbursed for money spent on tobacco control. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies already face a separate class action by  
Australians who have contracted smoking-related diseases over the 
past three years. 
</P>
<P>
	The new case, a brief outline of which was filed Tuesday,  
relates to people who may suffer loss or damage in the future even 
if they do not yet smoke. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Court judge Justice Murray Wilcox ordered the coalition  
to prepare a statement detailing its case by Dec. 3. 
</P>
<P>
	Brendan Brady, corporate and regulatory affairs director of  
British American Tobacco Australasia, the trading company which 
owns both Wills and Rothmans in Australia, said he believed the 
judge would throw out the case. 
</P>
<P>
	``We would expect it to fall down at the first hurdle,'' Brady  
said. ``Our initial reaction is one of surprise really at the 
bizarre nature of the suit. It really is a quite unique and novel 
approach to try to have a fund set up for people who do not yet 
smoke and for people who smoke who may or may not get ill.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
