<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ala. Gov Aide Got Help From Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) -- Records show that a court official fixed  
a speeding ticket for the governor's top aide -- another revelation 
in a scandal that has led to the resignation of Alabama's state 
police director and the suspension of three aides. 
</P>
<P>
	The governor's press secretary, Carrie Kurlander, played it down  
Tuesday, saying ``judges dismiss tickets all the time after hearing 
circumstances of the case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But records show the speeding ticket that a trooper gave Paul  
Hamrick, Gov. Don Siegelman's chief of staff, never made it to a 
judge. The ticket would have cost Hamrick $128, but Fred Posey, the 
circuit court clerk in Autauga County for more than 50 years, 
agreed to drop it. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is nothing you can do about it,'' Posey said. ``That's  
the system and that's the way it has always been.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Siegelman suspended three other aides in his office and forced  
the public safety director to resign after The Associated Press 
last week reported a pattern of ticket-fixing in Alabama. The 
governor has ordered several agencies to investigate and has asked 
legislative leaders and court officials to do the same. 
</P>
<P>
	Records show Hamrick was stopped in his BMW in 1998 and charged  
with traveling 78 mph in a 55 mph zone. Hamrick had been 
Siegelman's chief of staff when Siegelman was lieutenant governor 
and at the time was involved in Siegleman's successful campaign for 
governor. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Kurlander said Hamrick's ticket would be reviewed by the  
governor's chief legal adviser, along with the other cases. 
</P>
<P>
	``This ticket is not evidence of anything improper,'' she said.  
``It doesn't mean there was any wrongdoing.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
