<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gordon on Boston Postseason Roster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Boston closer Tom Gordon's sidetracked season  
took a positive turn when he was put on the postseason roster 
despite missing 3 1/2 months with an injured elbow. 
</P>
<P>
	Red Sox manager Jimy Williams confirmed it Tuesday although the  
official announcement of rosters for the best-of-5 division series 
against the Cleveland Indians was expected Wednesday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams also indicated that infielders Lou Merloni and Donnie  
Sadler, who both spent most of the season in the minors, were on 
the roster which includes 11 pitchers. 
</P>
<P>
	The series begins Wednesday night.  
</P>
<P>
	Gordon's major league record streak of 54 successful  
regular-season save opportunities ended June 5 in a 6-5 loss to 
Atlanta. He also blew a save opportunity in his next appearance, 
June 11 against the New York Mets. After the game, he returned to 
Boston for an MRI and three days later was placed on the disabled 
list with a right elbow strain. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams sidestepped a question about what role Gordon would  
play, then discussed it when he heard Gordon told reporters he was 
on the roster. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is on our roster,'' Williams said. ``I didn't think he'd  
make it back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gordon made three minor league rehabilitation appearances and  
returned to action with Boston last Wednesday when he gave up two 
runs in one inning as the Chicago White Sox handed him a 4-2 loss. 
</P>
<P>
	He pitched twice more -- allowing two runs in 1 2-3 innings  
against Baltimore last Friday and pitching a perfect inning against 
the Orioles last Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He threw good on that road trip those last few games,''  
Williams said. ``We'll use him in any part of the game that we 
think is the right spot to use him to help us win that game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it would be smart to bring him in in the middle  
of an inning,'' he added. ``He has thrown the ball very well, 
especially the last couple of times out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, his first full season as Boston's closer, Gordon was  
7-4 with a 2.72 ERA and an AL-best 46 saves. He blew just one 
opportunity. 
</P>
<P>
	This season, he had 11 saves, an 0-2 record and a 5.60 ERA in 21  
appearances. In 1998 and 1999, he was 2-0 against the Indians with 
six saves and a 1.17 ERA in 7 2-3 innings during the regular 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	But in last year's division series against Cleveland, he blew a  
save opportunity as Boston lost the decisive fourth game 2-1. 
</P>
<P>
	In his absence, Tim Wakefield, Derek Lowe and Rod Beck took  
turns in the closer's role. Wakefield and Lowe each had 15 saves 
and Beck had three in 12 appearances after being obtained from the 
Chicago Cubs on Aug. 31. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
