<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Wants UN Force in E. Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- With East Timor's government structures  
destroyed, the U.N. chief outlined a plan on Tuesday for the United 
Nations to take control and protect the territory with a 
9,000-strong peacekeeping force. 
</P>
<P>
	U.N. troops would replace the Australian-led force sent to East  
Timor last month to rein in pro-Indonesian militias who went on a 
looting, burning and killing campaign after the territory's vote 
for independence. 
</P>
<P>
	``The situation in East Timor is critical,'' Secretary-General  
Kofi Annan said in a report outlining his proposals to place U.N. 
peacekeepers in East Timor until it becomes independent in about 
two to three years. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Council for Timorese Resistance, a pro-independence  
umbrella organization, will be ``a key player'' in the U.N. 
administration, said Bernard Miyet, head of U.N. peackeeping. The 
council is headed by Jose Alexandre ``Xanana'' Gusmao, likely to be 
East Timor's first president. 
</P>
<P>
	The United Nations is to assume civilian and military control of  
East Timor after Indonesia's parliament ratified the results of the 
independence referendum in late October or early November, 
according to the May 5 agreement between Indonesia and Portugal 
that paved the way for the referendum. 
</P>
<P>
	But because of the precarious humanitarian situation in the  
province, Annan said, the U.N. civilian authority must immediately 
take charge of infrastructure, including water, electricity, 
hospitals, courts and some public offices. 
</P>
<P>
	He recommended the urgent deployment of 460 U.N. civilian  
police, and asked the Security Council to deploy a total of 1,640 
U.N. police, 8,950 peacekeepers and 200 military observers. The 
council is expected to consider the report on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In many ways, Annan's proposal for East Timor is similar to his  
plan for Kosovo after NATO ended its bombing campaign and Yugoslav 
forces withdrew from the province. 
</P>
<P>
	Like Kosovo, the United Nations will take over East Timor's  
defunct court and law enforcement systems, a chief administrator 
will have authority to make and change laws, and deputy 
administrators will govern the territory -- resettling refugees and 
rebuilding their torched homes. 
</P>
<P>
	But unlike Kosovo, there will be more need for international  
experts to run those public sectors, Miyet said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Kosovo, ethnic Albanians ran a parallel administration to  
that of the Serbs in education, health and other areas, and were 
able to resurrect it under U.N. control. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was not the case in East Timor,'' Miyet said.  
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, the U.N. Transitional Administration in East  
Timor, known as UNTAET, will need to involve as many East Timorese 
as possible so as to prepare them eventually to run the territory 
independently, Miyet said. 
</P>
<P>
	The cost of the U.N. effort could cost hundreds of millions of  
dollars, the bulk of which would go toward the peacekeeping 
operation, said Joseph Connor, the undersecretary-general for 
management. But no firm figures were available yet. 
</P>
<P>
	Miyet said he was optimistic that member states would contribute  
troops, and that the council would approve the size of the force. 
He didn't rule out that some members of the Australian-led force -- 
mainly Asian countries -- could remain in East Timor under U.N. 
control. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
