<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Data Show Smoke Reduces Rainfall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Satellite data have provided the first  
evidence that smoke from forest fires reduces rainfall. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've seen evidence of decreased precipitation in clouds  
contaminated by smoke, but it wasn't until now that we had direct 
evidence showing that smoke actually suppresses precipitation 
completely from certain clouds,'' said Daniel Rosenfeld, who 
reports the finding in a paper scheduled for the Oct. 15 edition of 
Geophysical Research Letters. 
</P>
<P>
	Rosenfeld studied the area of Kalimantan, Indonesia, during a  
satellite overpass on March 1, 1998. The southeastern portion of 
the island was engulfed in smoke, while the northwestern portion 
was relatively smoke-free. 
</P>
<P>
	The spacecraft's radar detected precipitation in smoke-free  
clouds, but almost none in the smoke-plagued clouds, showing the 
impact of smoke from fires on precipitation over the rainforest. 
</P>
<P>
	Rosenfeld, a satellite scientist at the Institute of Earth  
Sciences, Hebrew University of Jerusalem, did the research as part 
of NASA's Tropical Rainfall Measuring Mission project. 
</P>
<P>
	Rain is formed in one of two processes, a cold form in which  
moisture condenses on ice crystals, and a warm form -- common in the 
tropics -- in which raindrops grow by colliding and combining with 
each other. 
</P>
<P>
	The study shows that the ``warm rain'' processes are practically  
shut off when the clouds are polluted with heavy smoke from forest 
fires. 
</P>
<P>
	In these clouds, scientists found, the cloud tops must grow  
considerably above the freezing level of 16,000 feet in order for 
them to start producing rain by the alternative mechanism. 
</P>
<P>
	Scientists study how changes in global precipitation affect  
human activities, such as crop production, and the global rainfall 
weather pattern. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's important to note that this is not a unique case,''  
Rosenfeld said in a statement. ``We observed and documented several 
other cases that showed similar behavior. In some instances, even 
less severe smoke concentration was found to have comparable 
impacts on clouds.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier studies of urban air pollution have shown that pollution  
in Manila, Philippines, has an effect similar to forest fires, 
according to Rosenfeld. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
