<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gold Rallies; Cocoa Falls  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Gold futures prices surged higher in trading Tuesday on the New  
York Commodity Exchange, at one point hitting a two-year high of 
$339 a troy ounce before falling back on profit-taking. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, cocoa futures prices fell, coffee futures  
prices gained and crude oil futures slipped. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold prices surged at the start of trading on the COMEX as the  
market reacted to reports of a large gold transaction during 
overnight trading, according to analysts. 
</P>
<P>
	Also influencing the market were reports a number of hedge  
funds, which have been trading gold on ideas prices will remain 
low, were trying to limit their losses now that gold prices are 
rising, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday's huge early gains were already being trimmed when the  
Federal Reserve Bank announced it was leaving interest rates 
unchanged, which added to the price retreat. There was some belief 
in the market that the Fed would hike rates, causing the stock 
market to tumble and send investors fleeing to gold, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	The gold market continues to react to last week's announcement  
by the central banks of several European countries that they will 
limit their gold sales to 2,000 metric tons over the next five 
years and freeze their gold lending levels during the same period, 
according to analyst Bernard Savaiko of PaineWebber Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement by the European banks created the perception in  
the market that gold supplies have tightened, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, the Australian National Bank announced it has no  
plans to sell gold for the foreseeable future. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold for December delivery settled $8 higher at $326 a troy  
ounce. 
</P>
<P>
	Cocoa futures prices tumbled on the New York Coffee, Sugar and  
Cocoa Exchange as the market reacted to indications cocoa 
production will outpace demand. 
</P>
<P>
	Growers in the Ivory Coast and Ghana, the world's top two  
producing nations, are harvesting their main crops, which are 
reported to be large, according to analysts. Indonesia, the third 
largest producer, also is reported to have a large cocoa crop. This 
is coming at a time when European processors are reporting 
lackluster demand from major importing nations. 
</P>
<P>
	December cocoa was $36 lower at $975 per metric ton.  
</P>
<P>
	Coffee futures rose on concern about the condition of Brazil's  
2000-2001 coffee crop. 
</P>
<P>
	Several coffee cooperatives in Brazil are reporting crop losses  
of up to 25 percent. Local experts are reporting there has not been 
enough rain to keep the coffee trees in shape to produce an 
expected 40 million bag crop, according to analysts. 
</P>
<P>
	An agronomist with one Brazilian coffee cooperative, Pocos de  
Caldas, is estimating Brazilian coffee output will total 30 million 
to 36 million bags, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	December coffee was 2.20 cents higher at 85.05 cents a pound.  
</P>
<P>
	Crude oil futures prices were lower for the third consecutive  
trading session on the New York Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The move lower was in reaction to concerns that an American  
Petroleum Institute inventory report will show steady or increased 
crude oil stockpiles. 
</P>
<P>
	API data released after the close of trading show crude stocks  
increased 1 million barrels last week. 
</P>
<P>
	There also was concern in the market about a planned November  
meeting of the oil ministers of Mexico, Venezuela and Saudi Arabia, 
analysts said. They are expected to discuss whether to maintain 
current production levels past March. 
</P>
<P>
	November light sweet crude was 31 cents lower at $23.45 a  
barrel; November heating oil was .95 cent lower at 59.61 cents a 
gallon; November unleaded gasoline was .36 cent lower at 66.69 a 
gallon; November natural gas was .039 cent lower at $2.586 per 
1,000 cubic feet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
