<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jim Brown Sentenced to Probation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- NFL great Jim Brown was sentenced Tuesday to  
three years of probation and ordered to take domestic violence 
counseling for smashing his wife's car with a shovel during an 
argument that led her to call 911. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown also must pay $1,500 to a battered women's shelter and  
another $200 to a domestic violence fund. 
</P>
<P>
	The 63-year-old Hall of Famer, who was not in court, was told to  
appear Oct. 20 with proof that he had joined a counseling program. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown's lawyer told Municipal Court Judge Dale Fischer that his  
client opposed any sentencing that included domestic violence 
conditions. He noted that a jury found Brown guilty only of 
misdemeanor vandalism on Sept. 10, acquitting him of a charge that 
he made a terrorist threat against his wife, Monique. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's unfair to put any conditions of domestic violence on a  
man who's been actually found not guilty of domestic violence,'' 
lawyer William Graysen said outside court. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if he believed the court was making an example of Brown,  
Graysen said, ``It would appear so.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The prosecutor disputed that view.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're simply trying to hold him, like any other ordinary  
citizen, accountable,'' Deputy City Attorney Grace Lee said. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown was not in Hollywood Municipal Court because he had been  
visiting a daughter in Atlanta and missed the plane home, his 
lawyer said. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge placed Brown on 36 months' probation, ordering him to  
enroll in and complete a ``batterer's counseling program'' and to 
complete either 40 days of work with the Hollywood Beautification 
Team, or 400 hours of other court-approved community service. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown also must pay a $100 fine, $1,500 to a battered women's  
shelter and $200 to a domestic violence fund. His driver's license 
was suspended for a year. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the judge imposed a three-year protective order,  
similar to one that was in place for the trial. It bars Brown from 
annoying, harassing, threatening or committing violence against 
anyone. 
</P>
<P>
	If she wishes, Mrs. Brown may request further conditions for the  
protective order to keep Brown away and bar him from possessing 
weapons, the judge said. 
</P>
<P>
	The former Cleveland Browns running back has a long history of  
arrests for alleged attacks on women but never has been convicted. 
He was prosecuted for making a terrorist threat against his 
25-year-old wife even though she recanted her accusations to police 
that he had threatened to snap her neck. 
</P>
<P>
	She testified that she made her initial remarks following a June  
15 fight at the couple's Hollywood Hills home to get attention, 
because she believed her husband was having an affair. 
</P>
<P>
	In court, the prosecutor argued that under California law a  
crime is domestic violence if it is committed against someone 
defined as being in a domestic relationship with the defendant, 
such as a wife. 
</P>
<P>
	Graysen countered that the law is not intended to include crimes  
of property damage that did not involve violence or threats against 
an individual. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Brown testified that she was not frightened or threatened,  
Graysen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee disagreed, contending Mrs. Brown was so frightened ``she had  
to run as far away as she could, to a complete stranger, to call 
911 for help.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In asking for leniency, Graysen said Brown admitted he smashed  
the car windows with a shovel, and he quickly had the damage 
repaired. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would say that that was a very, very moderate offense and  
should receive a very moderate sentence,'' Graysen said. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge, however, called it ``an extremely serious form of  
vandalism'' and noted that Brown struck the car three times with 
``tremendous force.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems obvious to me that Mr. Brown needs counseling'' to  
control his anger, she said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
