<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> WWII Laborers Seek Remuneration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After months of negotiations, German companies  
are coming to the table with an offer on how much compensation 
they're willing to pay Nazi-era slave laborers. 
</P>
<P>
	And in advance of the two-day talks starting today, survivors  
launched a newspaper ad campaign and held a news conference to push 
for what they call a quick and just compensation settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	Sponsors said the ad campaign will continue through the talks.  
</P>
<P>
	``The corporations who exploited us and who, in genocidal  
partnership with the SS, murdered our friends and relatives have 
grown rich. ... They are worth countless billions,'' Rudy Kennedy, 
a Holocaust survivor from London, said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy spoke at a news conference in advance of today's  
reopening of negotiations in Washington to determine compensation 
for as many as 2.4 million people forced into labor to aid 
Germany's Nazi war machine. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were treated like animals,'' said an ad about Ford Motor  
Co. and its wartime German subsidiary, Ford Werke AG, displayed at 
the news conference. It had not yet run in newspapers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bayer (haggled) over the purchase price of 150 female  
prisoners on whom to test a sleeping medication,'' said an ad on 
the pharmaceutical company that ran in Tuesday's New York Times. 
``Bayer found $80 per woman too high a price. They ultimately 
bought them for less.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The charges are not new, but their presentation in full-page ads  
came as survivors and their attorneys attacked a reported 
compensation offer from 16 German companies as ``a disgrace,'' ``an 
insult'' and ``peanuts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An attorney in the negotiations threatened to walk out of the  
talks if industry's offer today is too low. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they don't step up to the plate and start negotiating ...  
with real money that is representative of their ability to pay, we 
are going to walk away from these meetings,'' said attorney Mel 
Weiss. 
</P>
<P>
	Weiss said that in months of negotiations, the German companies  
have never given a specific figure of how much they would pay. 
Instead, he said, survivors have relied on newspaper reports and 
rumors for an idea of what might be offered. 
</P>
<P>
	Weiss quoted such a report Tuesday in The Washington Post that  
said compensation of $3.8 billion, or $200 per forced labor 
survivor, is being contemplated. He called that offer a ``paltry 
amount.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reached by phone in Boston, Wolfgang Gibowski, spokesman for the  
German business initiative, said the $3.8 billion figure was wrong 
but would not divulge the amount. 
</P>
<P>
	Likewise, at the Washington new conference, Weiss also declined  
to say how much survivors are demanding but said it was ``far in 
excess'' of the $20 billion reported elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Tuesday, leading politicians in Germany pressured German  
businesses to reach an agreement quickly. The German government's 
envoy to the talks, Otto Lambsdorff, pointing to the ad campaign, 
also warned that failure of the talks could damage relations with 
the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Lambsdorff said this week that he would be bringing a final  
offer to the table during the talks starting today at the State 
Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas Reinert, a spokesman at Bayer headquarters in Leverkusen,  
Germany, said Bayer was absorbed during the Nazi era into the IG 
Farben pharmaceutical and chemical conglomerate. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bayer rejects legal responsibility for whatever may have  
happened under the Nazi dictatorship and at IG Farben,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``However, Bayer is aware of a humanitarian responsibility and  
therefore is taking part in negotiations aimed at creating a 
foundation for the victims.'' 
</P>
<P>
	From Dearborn, Mich., a Ford spokesman said the company is doing  
research to learn what happened at Ford operations after they were 
placed under government control during the war. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ford is part of the global community and is dedicated to  
supporting humanitarian initiatives because it's the right thing to 
do,'' said Jim Vella, Ford global news director. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991005.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-05 20:30:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DaimlerChrysler, CAW Reach Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The Canadian Auto Workers said it reached a  
tentative contract agreement with DaimlerChrysler AG late Tuesday, 
less than two hours before 13,800 union workers were set to strike. 
</P>
<P>
	CAW President Buzz Hargrove said at a news conference in Toronto  
that the deal was modeled on an agreement the CAW rank-and-file 
ratified last week with Ford Motor Co. of Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an excellent deal,'' Hargrove said. ``I have absolutely  
no disappointment at all. After bargaining a long while, I know you 
don't get everything you want.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A message left for DaimlerChrysler spokesmen at the Toronto  
hotel where negotiations were held were not immediately returned. 
</P>
<P>
	The two sides had appeared to be at a standstill hours earlier  
over four disputes involving union organizing and future work. The 
union had set a strike deadline of 11:59 p.m. Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hargrove said the union did not make any progress in its effort  
to force DaimlerChrysler to pressure a supplier, Magna 
International Inc., to recognize the union in Magna's Integram 
plant near Windsor, Ontario, which makes minivan seats for 
DaimlerChrysler. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're walking away empty handed on the Magna issue,'' Hargrove  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We settled the issues of DaimlerChrysler. We didn't feel at  
that point we could justify taking down the DaimlerChrysler 
operation,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hargrove also had said that the union could strike over disputes  
at DaimlerChrysler plants in Windsor and Ajax, Ontario, where work 
has not been assigned. He said the CAW had reached agreements 
there, including saving more than 70 jobs at the Ajax plant. 
</P>
<P>
	Hargrove said DaimlerChrysler is committed to new investment  
worth $400 million at the truck plant in Windsor, which has 2,000 
workers. He said he expects more workers to be hired there. 
</P>
<P>
	``This plant is now positioned for the new products of the  
future. The jobs of the workers are now secure,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler also agreed to take a neutral stand in CAW  
organizing efforts at the company's Freightliner heavy truck plant 
in St. Thomas, Ontario, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the agreement between CAW and Ford, workers received a 3  
percent wage increase in each year of a three-year package, a 
$1,000 (Canadian) signing bonus, a lucrative retirement package and 
other benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	Hargrove said the agreement with DaimlerChrysler also includes a  
$1,200 (Canadian) Christmas bonus and $800 tuition fees for 
dependents. He said that under the agreement 2,300 workers are 
eligible to retire immediately. 
</P>
<P>
	The CAW will now move on to negotiations with General Motors of  
Canada Ltd. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
