<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Principal Items in Defense Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Principal items in the $288.8 billion defense authorization bill  
signed Tuesday by President Clinton: 

</P>
<P>
	--Provides 4.8 percent across-the-board basic military pay raises  
in January, rather than 4.4 percent as Clinton requested; and 
future pay raises each year through 2006 that would be 0.5 
percentage points higher than private-sector wages. It is the 
largest military pay raise in nearly two decades. 
</P>
<P>
	--Gives additional targeted salary increases of up to 5.5 percent  
for mid-career officers. The 150 highest-ranking generals and 
admirals would get even higher pay raises, up to $125,900 a year 
from the current top pay of $110,700. 
</P>
<P>
	--Revamps military pension plans, allowing service members to  
retire after 20 years of basic service at 50 percent of basic pay, 
up from the current 40 percent. Or the retiree could stay with the 
40 percent -- and get a $30,000 cash bonus. 
</P>
<P>
	--Consolidates the Energy Department's nuclear weapons program  
into a National Nuclear Security Administration and tightens 
security at government nuclear weapons laboratories. The 
reorganization follows reports of Chinese espionage at the labs. 
</P>
<P>
	--Authorizes $8.3 billion more than requested by the president on  
defense programs in fiscal year 2000, mostly to increase military 
readiness. 
</P>
<P>
	--Provides $4.2 billion for anti-missile programs. That includes  
$867 million for the national missile defense program, $31 million 
more than Clinton requested. 
</P>
<P>
	--Requires the Pentagon to remove the remaining U.S. forces from  
Haiti by May 31, 2000. The administration announced last month that 
it would withdraw 450 full-time U.S. troops from Haiti by early 
next year, replacing them with rotating units made up largely of 
reservists. 
</P>
<P>
	--Requires the president to notify Congress of any potential  
violations of export control laws by U.S. companies that launch 
satellites from China; requires annual reports to Congress on the 
transfer of any U.S. military technology to China, Russia or 
terrorist regimes. 
</P>
<P>
	--Expands the size of Arlington National Cemetery by 44 acres by  
2025. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
