<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Americans' Use of MSAs Growing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- More Americans are trying the experimental  
tax-free medical savings accounts that Republican lawmakers are 
pushing to make more widely available, but the growth in popularity 
is slow. 
</P>
<P>
	The Internal Revenue Service says 11,727 of the accounts -- known  
as MSAs -- were opened between Jan. 1 and June 30, based on a tally 
of forms that new account holders must complete. The IRS also says 
809 more taxpayers reported contributions to MSAs on their 1998 tax 
returns than on 1997 returns. 
</P>
<P>
	The MSA count for 1998 included tax returns received by April  
15, and those expected to come in late. In total, the IRS projected 
that 42,477 taxpayers would report MSA contributions on their 1998 
returns. That compares with 41,668 in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	MSAs let people set aside money, tax free, to pay routine  
medical bills and the premium for a high-deductible insurance 
policy -- cheaper than a regular health plan -- to protect them in 
the event of expensive illness. 
</P>
<P>
	This week, Republican leaders are planning to bring legislation  
to the House floor that would open MSAs to all Americans, as part 
of a package of health care tax breaks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Thousands of Americans who previously had no health insurance  
at all are now covered because of MSAs and that is our top 
priority,'' House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill Archer, 
R-Texas, said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the taxpayers reporting MSA contributions on 1998 returns,  
the IRS said 24 percent, or 10,106, did not have health insurance 
before opening the accounts. Among the new 1999 account holders, 38 
percent, or 4,468, were previously uninsured. 
</P>
<P>
	Currently, MSAs are available only to the self-employed or  
companies with fewer than 50 workers that want to offer them as an 
employee benefit, under a congressional pilot project that began in 
1997 and runs through 2000. Lawmakers limited that project to 
750,000 people, but participation has not come close to that. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRS must report each October on the MSA experiment's  
progress. 
</P>
<P>
	Although a separate Medicare test of MSAs for senior citizens  
was supposed to start this year, no insurance company has yet 
offered the companion coverage necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	That has led critics to call MSAs a bust. Among them,  
congressional Democrats and Clinton administration officials say 
the accounts provide less financial protection than traditional 
health insurance when people get sick, even as employers pay 
unnecessary contributions to the MSAs of the healthy. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a lousy deal. It's like Edsels and Humvees,'' said Rep.  
Pete Stark, D-Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Republicans say easing restrictions on access to MSAs  
and the amount of tax-free contributions allowed will help them 
catch on with insurance companies and consumers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991005.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-05 13:00:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ryder Cup Stomps on Presidents Cup  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	On his flight home from the Ryder Cup, Davis Love III read every  
word in every story in the Boston newspapers about the great 
American comeback. He flew to Florida the next morning and read 
them all over again. 
</P>
<P>
	Not a day passed at the Buick Challenge that Love didn't have  
occasion to talk about the Ryder Cup, whether he was on the range 
or inside the ropes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't get enough of it,'' he gushed.  
</P>
<P>
	But all it takes is one question for that boyish glee to be  
replaced with a furrowed brow. A guy who could spin yarns about the 
thrill of winning the Ryder Cup suddenly hit a snag as he 
contemplated what lies ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	What does this do to the Presidents Cup?  
</P>
<P>
	Love stared at the ground, puffed his cheeks and let the air out  
slowly. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whew,'' he finally said. ``I have to be careful here.''  
</P>
<P>
	Love walks a fine line because he is a member of the PGA Tour  
policy board, and the Presidents Cup is a PGA Tour creation. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, there was no denying what took place at The Country Club.  
The excitement, the passion and the pressure -- yes, even the 
boorish behavior by the Boston gallery -- exposed the Ryder Cup as 
the greatest spectacle in golf, one of the greatest events in all 
sports. 
</P>
<P>
	And it may have exposed the Presidents Cup as, well, an  
exhibition. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a great event,'' Love said. ``But it's not as exciting as  
the Ryder Cup. You can see that in the players, and you can see 
that in the fans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some might argue you can see it in the results, too. Just 10  
months ago, an uninspired American team trudged down to Australia 
and got hammered like never before. 
</P>
<P>
	``Being in December, there were some guys on the team -- and I'm  
on that list, too -- that maybe weren't there 100 percent,'' said 
Justin Leonard, who was 0-3-1 at Royal Melbourne and didn't make 
any 45-foot putts. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wanted to play well and we wanted to win,'' he said. ``But  
there wasn't the excitement as a team that we had for the Ryder Cup 
this year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So, did the Ryder Cup hurt the Presidents Cup?  
</P>
<P>
	``In a way, yes,'' Leonard replied.  
</P>
<P>
	To what degree remains to be seen. The Presidents Cup will never  
become a real clash as long as it pits Team USA against Team 
Florida (nine International players have homes in Florida). Of 
course, that could actually be to its credit if the Ryder Cup turns 
into the Retaliation Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Presidents Cup is a happier contest. That's undeniable,''  
said Peter Thomson, who returns as the International captain next 
year. ``There are no threats, no ugliness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, the gallery was exemplary at Royal Melbourne. They were  
knowledgeable and respectful. They cheered long and loud for the 
home team, but also applauded the few great shots produced by the 
Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	``Part of it was they were beating us so badly,'' Leonard said.  
``There was probably some pity in their applause.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There are compelling issues involving the 2000 Presidents Cup at  
the Robert Trent Jones Club in Virginia. Can the Americans remain 
undefeated on home soil? Can they win back the one professional cup 
they no longer have? 
</P>
<P>
	Can they keep Greg Norman, Nick Price, Ernie Els &AMP; Co. from  
worldwide bragging rights? 
</P>
<P>
	``I have a view that the International team could be the equal  
of the U.S. team -- and much, much better than the European team,'' 
Thomson said. ``I know everyone in the International lineup is very 
keen to make a point that we've been overlooked as a third force in 
the world of golf. This team may lay claim to being top dog.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What happens after next year is the real dilemma.  
</P>
<P>
	That's when the Presidents Cup moves to South Africa, another  
long trip after another long season. And for what? As Lanny Wadkins 
noted about the previous Presidents Cup, the Americans flew halfway 
around the world to play a bunch of guys from Orlando. 
</P>
<P>
	Tiger Woods and David Duval will be playing on their sixth team.  
It could be the 11th straight team for Love. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are guys on our team who don't want to go to South  
Africa in 2002,'' Love said. ``Before they announce another 
captain, we need to say, 'Look. We need to expand this to get 
another team involved.' 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to figure out something that makes everybody excited  
about it,'' he said. ``Because there are five or six guys who 
didn't want to go last time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There may be twice as many who don't want to go in 2002 because  
they are emotionally exhausted. If not, it's only because they 
aren't wasting any emotion on one of the cups. 
</P>
<P>
	Care to guess which one?  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
