<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mets Face Big Unit in Series Opener </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- The Arizona Diamondbacks and New York opened  
their division series Tuesday night at an unusually late hour -- 
11:10 p.m. EDT -- with the Mets trying to regroup less than 24 hours 
after their emotional wild-card playoff victory in Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	Randy Johnson (17-9) was on the mound for Arizona, trying to end  
his five-game losing streak in the playoffs. The slump was tied 
with Joe Bush (1914-23) and Doyle Alexander (1973-87) as the 
longest postseason skid in baseball history. 
</P>
<P>
	His lackluster 2-5 postseason record did not reflect how well he  
has pitched. His ERA in the postseason was a respectable 3.10. 
</P>
<P>
	At age 36, Johnson is coming off what he has called his best  
season, when he struck out 364, fourth-most in baseball history, 
and led the National League in ERA at 2.48. 
</P>
<P>
	Masato Yoshii, New York's best pitcher in the two months, got  
the start. Yoshii (12-8) was 5-0 in his last eight starts with a 
1.61 earned run average over that span. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets-Diamondbacks matchup was the third playoff game of the  
day in the majors. The start time at Bank One Ballpark was about an 
hour later than normal for night games, and was designed to let all 
postseason games be televised without conflicts. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson and Yoshii had faced each other once before. On May 30  
in New York, the Diamondbacks shelled Yoshii for seven runs in 2 
2-3 innings. Johnson, meanwhile, struck out 10 in eight innings in 
Arizona's 10-1 victory. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets didn't arrive in Phoenix until nearly 2 a.m. after  
their 5-0 victory in Cincinnati. They advanced to the playoffs for 
the first time since 1988 despite a seven-game losing streak that 
left them on the brink of elimination with just five games to play. 
New York won four of five to force the playoff with the Reds. 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona spent $118.9 million on free agents, including Johnson,  
in the off-season and won the NL West title to become the first 
team to reach the playoffs in just its second season. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
