<HEADLINE> Bush Declines N.H. Debate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HANOVER, N.H. (AP) -- George W. Bush has turned down an  
invitation to participate in a nationally televised Republican 
presidential forum later this month, citing a conflict with an 
event in Texas honoring his wife. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope the organizers understand that while the debate may be  
important, it's not nearly as important as me being with my wife on 
that day,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's wife, Laura, is being honored at Southern Methodist  
University on Oct. 28, the same day as the Republican presidential 
forum at Dartmouth College. 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign said Bush does not plan to participate in any  
debates before January. Bush has agreed to two debates in the new 
year -- a forum in Iowa sponsored by the Des Moines Register and one 
Jan. 26 in Manchester sponsored by CNN and WMUR-TV, according to 
the campaign and WMUR. 
</P>
<P>
	CNN and WMUR are the sponsors of the Oct. 28 forum and one the  
night before for Democratic candidates Al Gore and Bill Bradley. 
</P>
<P>
	WMUR spokeswoman Julie Campasano said Tuesday that the Oct. 28  
GOP forum will go on without Bush. She said all the other 
Republican candidates have accepted invitations except Pat 
Buchanan, who is considering leaving the GOP and has not replied. 
</P>
<P>
	Two earlier debates were torpedoed after Bush declined to  
participate and the rest of the field saw no point in debating 
without the front-runner. One was in conjunction with the Ames, 
Iowa, straw poll in August. Another was originally planned for this 
weekend at the Florida Republican convention. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sunshine State GOP, under reported pressure from Bush and  
his brother, Florida Gov. Jeb Bush, dropped the straw vote and 
decided instead on a debate Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the Texas governor said he would not participate in  
that debate either, ending the proposed joint appearance. 
</P>
<P>
	``We intend to debate next year when people are beginning to pay  
attention to the presidential race,'' said Bush campaign 
spokeswoman Karen Hughes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're still in the process of establishing Governor Bush as a  
presidential contender, laying out his ideas, his proposals and his 
vision of the future of America,'' she said. ``We have a game plan 
for this campaign and we are in the process of executing it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
