<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Tobacco Lawyer S1/8reads essage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- Some 35 million pages of documents gathered during  
a legal battle against tobacco companies in the United States could 
help similar cases across the world, an attorney who fought the 
tobacco industry and is now working for the World Health 
Organization said today. day. 
</P>
<P>
	Roberta Walburn helped the state of Minnesota reach a $6.6  
billion settlement with the tobacco industry last year. 
</P>
<P>
	She is now advising groups in a number of countries on the  
content of the documents and suggesting how they could make use of 
them in their own litigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have been struck by how similar the tobacco industry  
arrangements are in a number of countries and the level of interest 
in the documents and in litigation,'' said Walburn, who is taking a 
year's leave from her law firm to work with the health 
organization. 
</P>
<P>
	The legal team in the Minnesota case forced tobacco companies to  
release the documents. The settlement included a clause making them 
available to the public, and many are now on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the documents, the attorneys claim they found evidence  
that tobacco companies had known for decades that nicotine was 
addictive. 
</P>
<P>
	Cases against tobacco companies are currently going through the  
courts in about a dozen countries, including Australia, Canada, 
India, Britain, Ireland, France and Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	The World Health Organization is working with governments to  
create an international treaty on tobacco control. 
</P>
<P>
	Walburn said litigation is still an important part of the fight  
against the tobacco industry, even though it is slow and costly and 
many cases fail. 
</P>
<P>
	``The goal is to hold the tobacco industry accountable for its  
actions and make this information available around the world for 
people in the public health community to use these documents and 
understand the public better,'' she said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
