<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-05 15:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Exhumed Body of Sheppard Tested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- The body of Marilyn Sheppard was exhumed  
Tuesday and prosecutors performed tests to try to prove the guilt 
of her husband in the murder case that inspired the ``The 
Fugitive'' film and TV series. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we want to do is get to the truth,'' said Cuyahoga County  
Prosecutor William Mason said. ``I don't think today's tests are 
definitively going to give us the killer but it's going to give us 
some answers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors had Mrs. Sheppard's body exhumed from a crypt in a  
suburban Cleveland cemetery to obtain new DNA samples as they 
defend the state in a wrongful imprisonment suit brought by the 
couple's son, Sam Reese Sheppard. The fetus she was carrying when 
she died also was exhumed. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheppard claims his father, Dr. Sam Sheppard, was unfairly  
convicted of killing his mother, who was beaten to death in 1954 in 
the bedroom of the family home on Lake Erie. 
</P>
<P>
	An investigator said Tuesday's tests showed Mrs. Shepard did not  
bite her attacker 45 years ago. The possibility of bite marks on 
the killer was part of the defense testimony in the retrial 
Sheppard, who spent 10 years in prison for the slaying before being 
acquitted in 1966. Sheppard had no bite wounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Lowell Levine, forensic dentist with the New York State Police,  
would not go into detail about the evidence about the biting, but 
said, ``It just didn't happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sheppard attorney Terry Gilbert said it was premature to discuss  
the findings on the teeth. 
</P>
<P>
	The testing also showed that the injuries to Mrs. Sheppard's  
face were much more extensive than expected, Mason said. The bones 
below her eye and around the mouth were detached from her face. 
</P>
<P>
	Forensic scientists for prosecutors and the Sheppard legal team  
were conducting tests of Mrs. Sheppard's mummified remains. 
</P>
<P>
	Reports on the scientists' findings will take two months.  
</P>
<P>
	The younger Sheppard was present when his mother's casket was  
opened at Knollwood Cemetery. 
</P>
<P>
	More than a dozen people, wearing masks, protective headgear and  
slippers to avoid contaminating the remains, also were in the room 
but Sheppard was then allowed a few moments with only an undertaker 
present. 
</P>
<P>
	``The viewing was difficult,'' he said. ``I needed to witness  
that because I learned long ago that in terms of her murder my 
imagination is worse than the real thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Sheppard's remains are to be reinterred on Wednesday.  
</P>
<P>
	The fetus had been removed from Mrs. Sheppard's body shortly  
after her death and contained in a preservative solution in a glass 
jar. 
</P>
<P>
	Forensic scientists learned for the first time Tuesday that the  
fetus had been autopsied, which Gilbert said raised questions about 
whether the coroner's office around the time of the slaying had 
concealed evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheppard said he doesn't believe any evidence will be gained  
that will implicate his father. ``This is an exercise in 
futility,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The younger Sheppard and his lawyers contend DNA and other  
evidence point to a family window-washer, Richard Eberling, as the 
killer. Eberling died last year in prison, where he was serving a 
life sentence for an unrelated murder. 
</P>
<P>
	But Mason believes the doctor was the killer and the DNA  
evidence collected by the Sheppard team is contaminated. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Sheppard, who died in 1970, always claimed a bushy-haired  
intruder killed his wife and then knocked him unconscious when he 
ran to her aid. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
