<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Oct. 5, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Stocks End Lower; Dow Down 0.64  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell today in volatile trading after the  
Federal Reserve decided against raising interest rates again but 
left open the possibility of a third rate hike later this year. The 
Dow Jones industrial average closed 0.64 lower at 10,400.59, having 
swung from a 106-point gain to a 124-point loss over the final two 
hours. Most broader stock indexes also turned lower in the 
afternoon, cresting just as the Fed was set to announce the outcome 
of its latest meeting on inflation and interest rate strategy. The 
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 3.25 to 1,301.35, but the Nasdaq 
composite index rose 3.70 to 2,800.16 thanks to a strong showing by 
certain technology stocks. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at the close:  
Dow Industrials:        10,400.59    - 0.64
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1,226  Declines 1,789  Unchgd  515
NYSE Volume:         934,184,350
Most Active NYSE issue:        America Online113 7/8   + 4 3/4
S&AMP;P 500:         1300.32  - 4.28
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          784.65  - 5.18
Nasdaq Composite Index        2,800.16   + 3.70
Gold(final) -    $324.40    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Tue.
Silver(final) -   $5.500  troy oz., NY Comex spot month Tue.

</P>
<P>
	Fed Leaves Interest Rates Unchanged  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Reserve, faced with a booming  
economy but no signs of inflation, decided today not to raise 
interest rates but left open the possibility of a third rate 
increase later this year. The Fed policy-makers moved their policy 
directive, which signals the future course of interest rates, from 
neutral to one tilting toward a rate increase. By leaving interest 
rates unchanged, the federal funds rate, the interest that banks 
charge each other on overnight loans, continues to stand at 5.25 
percent. 

</P>
<P>
	Ferguson Sworn In As Fed Vice Chairman  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Roger W. Ferguson, a Harvard-trained economist  
and lawyer, was sworn in today as vice chairman of the Federal 
Reserve. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan administered the 
oath to Ferguson, 47, who was nominated by President Clinton to 
fill a vacancy created by the departure of Alice Rivlin in July. In 
making that announcement this summer, Clinton said Ferguson would 
be the first African American to hold the post of vice chairman. 

</P>
<P>
	Charges Filed in Bank of NY Probe  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Federal criminal charges were unveiled today in  
the Bank of New York investigation against three individuals and 
three companies alleging the illegal transmission of $7 billion 
through accounts at the bank. The charges were contained in a 
three-count indictment filed under seal in U.S. District Court in 
Manhattan on Sept. 16. The indictment unsealed today named as 
defendants Peter Berlin, Lucy Edwards and Aleksey Volkov as well as 
Benex International Co. Inc., Becs International L.L.C. and 
Torfinex Corp. The charges were the first to result from an 
investigation by federal prosecutors in Manhattan into what has 
been described as potentially one of the largest cases of 
money-laundering ever uncovered in the United States. 

</P>
<P>
	Leading Economic Indicators Fall  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A key gauge of future economic activity declined  
in August following three straight monthly gains, a sign that 
rising interest rates are starting to have an effect on the 
economy, the Conference Board reported today. The Index of Leading 
Economic Indicators fell 0.1 percent in August, but the drop was 
slightly less than the 0.2 percent decline economic analysts had 
forecast. The index, designed to forecast economic activity three 
to six months in the future, had risen 0.3 percent in each of 
previous three months after falling 0.1 percent in April. It has 
increased nine times in the past 11 months. 

</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom Wins Sprint Bid War  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- MCI WorldCom Inc. has forged the largest  
corporate takeover in history, announcing today a $115 billion 
acquisition of Sprint Corp., the nation's third-largest 
long-distance company. The nation's top telephone regulator 
immediately warned the companies that they ``bear a heavy burden to 
show how consumers would be better off'' as a result of the merger. 
The combined company will be called WorldCom, and will control 30 
percent of the U.S. long-distance market, offer wireless phone and 
paging services and an Internet network. WorldCom also will be a 
stronger competitor to AT&AMP;T Corp., the nation's largest 
long-distance and cable TV company. William E. Kennard, chairman of 
the Federal Communications Commission, said MCI WorldCom and Sprint 
will have to make a strong case for approval of the deal. MCI 
WorldCom shares were at 67 15/16, down 3 11/16. Sprint was at 58 7/8, 
down 2. 

</P>
<P>
	BellSouth Seen Facing Challenges  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- After losing the bidding war for Sprint,  
BellSouth Corp. -- the only regional Baby Bell phone company yet to 
be involved in a major merger -- needs to make a deal soon or risk 
being dominated by the giant firms taking over the 
telecommunications industry, analysts said today. Still, the 
Atlanta-based company's entry into the fight for Sprint -- won by 
MCI WorldCom -- indicates that BellSouth is no longer content to sit 
back watch other telecom companies grow. ``BellSouth making an 
offer shows a difference in direction,'' said analyst David Burks 
of J.J.B. Hilliard, W.L. Lyons. BellSouth officials would not 
speculate on any other potential merger targets. BellSouth shares 
were at 41 13/16, down 7/8. 

</P>
<P>
	CBS Plans Majority Web Co. Stake  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- CBS Corp. is teaming with a small Internet  
company to create a Web site that will lure users with daily cash 
prizes and also combine the TV network's varied Web offerings, from 
business and investing news, to sports and entertainment. CBS said 
it will pay $30 million in cash for a majority of CTC Bulldog Inc., 
an Irvington, N.Y. venture formed earlier this year. The deal 
represents CBS's first majority stake in a Web site. The companies' 
new site, iWon.com, was launched today. Its most prominent feature 
is an ongoing cash sweepstakes that will give away $10,000 a day, 
$1 million every month and $10 million on tax day, April 15. 

</P>
<P>
	America Online Launches Version 5.0  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- America Online Inc. introduced its latest  
software today, eyeing a future where wireless phones and hand-held 
organizers are as popular as computers for reaching the Internet. 
The AOL 5.0 software will let users adapt such features as a new 
interactive calendar to portable devices, which are starting to hit 
the market for Net use. Steve Case, chairman and chief executive 
officer of AOL, said he wants to move away from tying AOL to any 
one device such as the computer. ``You stop thinking about AOL as a 
screen-based, PC-based, telephone-based service and start thinking 
of it as a set of capabilities imbedded throughout your life,'' he 
said in an interview. 

</P>
<P>
	Impact of State Farm Case Weighed  
</P>
<P>
	MARION, Ill. (AP) -- The $456 million jury verdict in a lawsuit  
accusing State Farm of using second-rate parts for automobile 
repairs could lead to higher premiums if the ruling stands on 
appeal, industry experts warn. Steve Goldstein, a spokesman for the 
Insurance Information Institute, a nonprofit industry 
communications group, said premiums and repair bills could soar if 
insurers are forced to use factory-authorized parts. Consumers save 
about $800 million a year in reduced premiums through the use of 
less-expensive repair parts, according to industry estimates 
presented at trial. 

</P>
