<HEADLINE> Pele's Son Is Convicted of Murder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- The son of Brazilian soccer legend Pele  
was convicted of murder early Wednesday for taking part in a street 
car race which resulted in the death of a passing motorcyclist. 
</P>
<P>
	Edson Cholbi do Nascimento, 29, was sentenced to six years in  
``semi-open'' prison, which means he must sleep in the prison but 
may leave during the day to go to work. 
</P>
<P>
	Nascimento and Marcilio Marcilio Jose Marinho de Melo, 25, -- who  
was also convicted and sentenced to 6 years in semi-open prison -- 
were accused of racing their cars in Santos, a port town 48 miles 
southeast of Sao Paulo, when they struck and killed 50-year-old 
retiree Pedro Simoes Neto. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Melo's car was the one that hit Neto, Nascimento was  
found guilty for taking part in the race which occurred in Oct. 
1992. 
</P>
<P>
	The pair will be free while they appeal the decision.  
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Octavio Borba de Vasconcellos began to present his  
case before a jury at 8 a.m. Tuesday and, expect for breaks for 
lunch and dinner ran straight through to 1:00 a.m. Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Most Brazilian trials last around 24 hours, usually running  
through the night. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
