<HEADLINE> Report: DaimlerChrysler Mulls Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- DaimlerChrysler is considering whether to relocate  
its headquarters from Germany to the United States, a magazine 
reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	A DaimlerChrysler spokesman called the report ``speculation''  
and refused comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares in the automaker climbed on the Frankfurt stock exchange  
on news of the report in Stern weekly. 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler chairman Juergen Schrempp is under pressure  
because the company's share price has weakened since Daimler-Benz's 
merger with Chrysler Corp. last year, the article said. 
</P>
<P>
	It said U.S. investors are less interested in DaimlerChrysler  
shares because -- unlike the former Chrysler shares -- they are not 
included in the major U.S. stock indexes. 
</P>
<P>
	Schrempp is having the company study plans to move its  
headquarters to the United States and create a holding company in 
Zurich, Switzerland, as its European base, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, the company announced the early retirement of  
Chrysler division president Thomas Stallkamp in a board shakeup 
seen as a move by Schrempp to consolidate his control. 
</P>
<P>
	Stallkamp, a 19-year Chrysler veteran, was credited with helping  
Chrysler shed billions in costs and was expected to help the German 
side do the same. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
