<HEADLINE> NFL Near Expansion Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The NFL decision on where its 32nd team is going  
to play appeared closer Tuesday night after Houston's Robert McNair 
and Los Angeles' Michael Ovitz spoke to the expansion committee 
members. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think there will be a recommendation tomorrow by the  
committee,'' NFL spokesman Joe Browne said after that group, with 
12 of its 14 members present, met for three hours. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no straw vote and no recommendation was formed, Browne  
said. But he added that the committee was to meet again Wednesday 
morning and would be expected to make its recommendation afterward 
to the full ownership, which has a session beginning at 9 a.m. EDT. 
</P>
<P>
	``What happens after that as far as the 17 clubs, I'm not  
sure,'' Brown said, referring to the 17 teams that aren't 
represented on the expansion committee. ``Anything can happen right 
up until the meeting starts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The committee's recommendation would have to be approved by 24  
of the 31 owners. 
</P>
<P>
	McNair would pay a reported $700 million for the expansion  
franchise in a deal that would be the largest ever for a sports 
team in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he was cautiously optimistic.  
</P>
<P>
	``I feel very good about our chances,'' McNair said in a lobby  
outside the meeting room. ``Of course, I've felt good about our 
chances all along. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've made an outstanding business proposal, and these are  
good business people who know a good proposal. From what I know 
about the other proposals, I don't think they compare to ours. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the main issue is that Houston's ready to go.''  
</P>
<P>
	Unlike McNair, Ovitz did not make himself available to answer  
questions after addressing the committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hollywood deal maker and his backers hold an option on a  
parcel of land at Hollywood Park and have proposed building a 
stadium there, an idea that has been raised by other businessmen in 
the past. 
</P>
<P>
	Any plans Ovitz has at Hollywood Park almost certainly would be  
in the very early stages. He only received the option on the race 
track property last week after Marvin Davis, who held the option, 
dropped out of the bidding for an NFL team. 
</P>
<P>
	Ed Roski, who represents the group trying to bring an NFL team  
to the Los Angeles Coliseum, also came to Atlanta. He was not asked 
to address the expansion committee, however, although he did speak 
at length with NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
