<HEADLINE> Japan Stocks Edge Higher / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The U.S. dollar was marginally lower against the  
yen Wednesday morning after the U.S. Federal Reserve warned of 
further interest rate increases. Prices on Tokyo's benchmark stock 
index rose. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 106.59 yen, down 0.01 yen from its level of  
106.60 yen late Tuesday in Tokyo but above its level of 106.41 yen 
late Tuesday in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark Nikkei-225 Stock Average rose 56.35 points, or  
0.32 percent, to 17,840.50 at the end of the morning session. The 
average closed up 20.44 points, or 0.12 percent, the previous day. 
</P>
<P>
	While keeping rates unchanged Tuesday, the U.S. central bank  
switched its policy directive from neutral to one leaning toward 
increased rates. It warned that it would remain ``especially 
alert'' to any inflation threats coming from tight labor markets. 
</P>
<P>
	``The U.S. Fed's unexpected decision to adopt a tightening bias  
is putting some downward pressure on the dollar,'' said Takeo 
Suzuki, assistant foreign exchange manager at Nomura Trust and 
Banking. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro bought 114.84 yen in midday  
trading, up 0.94 yen from its level of 113.90 yen late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo share prices were mixed at midday after the market trimmed  
early gains made on hopes for further economic stimulus measures by 
Japan's new Cabinet. 
</P>
<P>
	Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi reshuffled his Cabinet on Tuesday  
and kicked off a three-party coalition government, retaining 
economic ministers who have played a key role in bringing the 
economy to the verge of a recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	Shizuka Kamei, the policy chief of the ruling party, said he  
expects the government's new economic stimulus package to include 
around 13 trillion yen (dlrs 123 billion) in total spending. 
</P>
<P>
	Overnight on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average  
closed 0.64 point lower at 10,400.59 Tuesday, having swung from a 
106-point gain to a 124-point loss over the final two hours. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section fell 1.80 points, or 0.12 percent, to 1,508.26. The 
TOPIX closed up 0.90 point, or 0.06 percent, on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose  
to 1.6400 percent from Tuesday's finish of 1.6100 percent. Its 
price fell 0.26 point to 100.52. 
</P>
<P>
 *(kgo-ep-dj) 
  	   	
</P>
