<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> State Farm Verdict Angers Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MARION, Ill. (AP) -- The insurance industry fears a swarm of  
lawsuits in the wake of an Illinois jury's $456 million verdict 
over State Farm's use of questionable auto parts -- and industry 
leaders are looking for help. 
</P>
<P>
	Insurance groups called Tuesday for support of a bill under  
consideration in the U.S. Senate that would force plaintiffs to 
file most national class-action lawsuits in federal court. 
Proponents say such a law would help limit the influence -- which 
some find excessive -- of state juries in the affairs of regulators 
and legislatures nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	In the State Farm case, they say, the jury's finding that State  
Farm breached its contract with policyholders by using auto-body 
repair parts of questionable quality intrudes on the policy 
decisions of regulators and legislators who approve of the parts' 
use. 
</P>
<P>
	``Here we have a judge and jury in Illinois essentially making  
policy for the entire United States. This is the kind of case that 
belongs in the federal court,'' said J.V. Schwan, counsel for the 
Civil Justice Reform Campaign of Citizens for a Sound Economy, 
which seeks less government involvement in business. 
</P>
<P>
	``What's particularly objectionable in this case is that this is  
a practice that state insurance regulators have examined time and 
again and have permitted to be followed,'' said Ann Spragens, 
general counsel and senior vice president for the Alliance of 
American Insurers, a trade group. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the U.S. Supreme Court rejected State Farm's argument  
that certification of the national class violated the company's 
due-process rights by allowing Illinois law to be used to judge 
claims from states whose laws allow use of aftermarket parts. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress is considering a bill that would grant federal courts  
jurisdiction in cases where any member of a proposed class resides 
in a different state than any defendant. The House approved the 
bill Sept. 23. It is currently awaiting action in the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	If approved, the legislation would require that large cases such  
as State Farm's be filed in federal court, preventing trial lawyers 
from filing in courts they believe likely to approve large awards. 
</P>
<P>
	Sherman Joyce, president of the American Tort Reform  
Association, said allowing juries from one state to reach into 
another is unfair. 
</P>
<P>
	``It sends a very, very troubling message to businesses, to  
anybody who is involved in commercial activities throughout the 
country, that they could be adhering to the letter of the law in a 
particular state and then find that they are subject to a 
class-action lawsuit,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Trish Littleton, a plaintiffs' attorney in the State Farm  
lawsuit, said there is nothing wrong with filing a class-action 
lawsuit in a state court. 
</P>
<P>
	In the State Farm case, she said, Illinois was an appropriate  
forum because the contracts the company was alleged to have 
breached originated at the company's Bloomington headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
	She said the insurance industry's claim that the jury is making  
national policy is ``blarney,'' but conceded that insurance 
regulators will have to revisit their approval of aftermarket parts 
now that a jury has found consumers were bilked by their use. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury's award designated $456 million to compensate the 4.7  
million current and former State Farm policyholders who had 
aftermarket parts included on repair orders since July 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	Williamson County Circuit Judge John Speroni is considering a  
separate consumer fraud complaint in which the plaintiffs have 
asked for damages totaling nearly $4 billion. That count accuses 
the company of deliberately deceiving customers about the quality 
of aftermarket parts -- sheet-metal and plastic trim parts that are 
modeled on the originals but made without access to factory 
specifications. 
</P>
<P>
	A decision is expected by Friday. At least 13 other lawsuits  
naming seven insurance companies are pending in state courts from 
Arizona to Florida. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
