<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate OK's FAA Flight Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Flights out of some of the nation's busiest  
airports would be increased as part of a major Federal Aviation 
Administration bill passed Tuesday by the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	In a move aimed at improving service to smaller markets and  
making it easier for new entrants to compete, the Senate bill, 
approved by voice, would increase flights out of Chicago's O'Hare, 
New York's LaGuardia and Kennedy and Washington's Reagan National. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a remarkable win for consumers,'' said Sen. John  
McCain, R-Ariz., who has been a strong advocate of increasing 
flights as a means of helping smaller communities hurt by 
deregulation. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA legislation in general would authorize $45 billion over  
four years to fund aviation safety, modernization and competition 
programs. 
</P>
<P>
	It provides more than $2 billion a year for the Airport  
Improvement Program, which has been prohibited from making new 
project grants since the new fiscal year began last Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In a step welcomed by the administration, the bill would seek to  
overhaul the air traffic control system by appointing a chief 
operating officer and creating an oversight committee. The 
administration has been pressing to make the system, swamped by 
rapidly expanding numbers of flights, operate more like a private 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the critical challenge facing the FAA,'' said  
Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress in 1969 imposed flight ceilings on the Chicago, New  
York and Washington airports to counter congestion and noise 
pollution. A 1,250-mile ``perimeter rule'' was also established for 
Reagan National in 1986 to assure the economic viability of the 
region's two long-haul airports, Dulles and Washington-Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA bill would eliminate the ``high density rule'' for the  
New York airports. The two Illinois senators, Republican Peter 
Fitzgerald and Democrat Richard Durbin, blocked an effort to do 
away with the rule for O'Hare, instead settling for a 30-slot 
increase. One slot is a takeoff or a landing. 
</P>
<P>
	Flights out of Washington are to increase by 24 slots, with 12  
going beyond the 1,250-mile limit. An amendment by Sen. Charles 
Robb, D-Va., to keep flights at current numbers was defeated, 
61-37. 
</P>
<P>
	In each case new entrants or flights to underserved markets get  
priority for any new flights. 
</P>
<P>
	The House passed its version of the bill by a 316-110 margin  
last June. While similar in many respects, it differs on the level 
of flight increases and includes a provision, opposed by the 
administration, that would wall off the Aviation Trust Fund, 
revenues coming in from airport taxes, so that it could be used 
only for airport projects. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year Congress was unable to pass an FAA bill because the  
House and Senate couldn't agree on slot allocations. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also would set up a pilot program to help small  
communities improve air service, authorize $30 million a year to 
purchase precision instrument landing systems, require that cargo 
aircraft be equipped with instruments that warn of impending 
collisions in the air and provide funds to address the problems of 
bird strikes. 
</P>
<P>
	Durbin of Illinois inserted language to ban smoking on all  
international flights landing or taking off from the United States, 
and Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., won approval of language requiring the 
Transportation Department to make sure airlines put their promises 
to improve service into their legal contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would additionally give the FAA authority to fine  
unruly passengers and put new regulations on national park air tour 
overflights. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is S. 82.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
