<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> High School Coach Lied About Past </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROCHESTER, Mass. (AP) -- Football players and coaches at Old  
Colony Regional High School always took for granted that their 
assistant football coach was Nick Eddy, an All-American halfback at 
Notre Dame in the mid-1960s. 
</P>
<P>
	But then the real Nick Eddy called the man who was impersonating  
him, and a ruse that began 20 years ago suddenly fell apart. 
William Nicholas Eddy-McMullen was forced to resign from the 
coaching staff, and he had to own up to living a lie. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't deny it. I didn't embellish it,'' a weary McMullen  
said of his claims. By coincidence he shares two of the real Nick 
Eddy's names. ``In fact, people were amazed at how modest ... how I 
didn't talk about my past and my exploits and what I'd done, 
etcetera.'' 
</P>
<P>
	School officials, tipped off by Eddy's call and a report by The  
Standard-Times of New Bedford, said they were surprised at why he 
lied. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact is he didn't need to because he was successful just  
on his ability as a coach,'' said David Ferreira, Old Colony's 
superintendent. 
</P>
<P>
	The real Nick Eddy, now an insurance executive in Modesto,  
Calif., heard of McMullen's scam through a rumor that he had 
divorced his wife and had a new family in Massachusetts. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought, `My gosh, that's where this all came from,''' said  
Eddy, who called and confirmed the story in a telephone 
conversation with McMullen. 
</P>
<P>
	But Eddy, who played seven seasons with the Detroit Lions, said  
he doesn't have any ill will towards McMullen. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only real harm, I think that has come out of it, is the  
impression that I was divorced,'' said Eddy, 55, who will soon 
celebrate his 34th wedding anniversary. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview Tuesday, McMullen said his deception started  
about 20 years ago. While broke and looking for a job, the Iowa 
native interviewed at a New Bedford clothing plant. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he had played football at Notre Dame under his  
stepfather's last name, Eddy. He added that he had also used his 
middle name, Nick. 
</P>
<P>
	Noticing Notre Dame paraphernalia at the plant manager's office,  
he decided to try to boost his chances of getting hired. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a last minute tidbit, I threw in that I went to Notre  
Dame,'' said McMullen, whose highest degree was actually from high 
school. 
</P>
<P>
	The lie worked, and McMullen kept up the facade until he moved  
to California in 1979 and temporarily dropped the act. 
</P>
<P>
	He resumed it, however, when he returned to Massachusetts in  
1989, and an old acquaintance introduced him to others as the 
football great. 
</P>
<P>
	``It kind of snowballed,'' McMullen said.  
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, McMullen was hired at Old Colony as one of several  
assistant football coaches after a chance meeting with head coach 
Kevin Gonsalves. Gonsalves had been impressed by McMullen's 
knowledge of the game -- even without McMullen bringing up his 
fictitious past. 
</P>
<P>
	School officials said they first learned of McMullen's claims  
when he sent in his resume. Because he used his own social security 
number and passed the state's criminal records check, his past was 
never questioned. 
</P>
<P>
	Ferreira said McMullen was a popular coach and a good motivator.  
</P>
<P>
	But that didn't excuse his lies, he said.  
</P>
<P>
	``In our eyes there's something wrong in that he misrepresented  
himself when he's working with young men, trying to teach them 
honesty and proper values,'' Ferreira said. ``That's 
inappropriate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McMullen said he is embarrassed and sorry about his lies. He  
apologized to the real Nick Eddy over the phone, he said, and plans 
to apologize to Old Colony's players. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know it's going to change the nature of the relationships I  
have with just about everybody I have in this town,'' McMullen 
said. He said when the news broke, he had been working with a 
therapist to figure out how to come clean about the lie to the 
community -- and also his family. 
</P>
<P>
	``The truth is out and I've dealt with it,'' he said. ``I'm  
going to go forward and see what happens.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
