<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Targets Women's Vote in N.Y. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Seeking the women's vote, Vice President Al Gore  
proposed Tuesday to make life better for working families by 
providing preschool for every child and encouraging employers to 
provide on-site day-care and emergency baby-sitting. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you do not understand the fatigue of the American working  
woman, then you don't deserve to be president of the United 
States,'' Gore said to cheers from about 600 mostly female 
supporters at a Manhattan fund-raising luncheon. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you elect me president, I will honor your struggle by  
making it easier to be a good worker and a good parent at the same 
time,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore, fighting former Sen. Bill Bradley for the Democratic  
presidential nomination, also said he wanted to further women's 
rights by ensuring equal pay for equal work, keeping abortion legal 
and offering help to those juggling the demands of jobs and family. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you elect me president, I will make available high-quality  
preschool for every child in every family across the United 
States,'' he said. ``It's the single best investment we can make.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore said he wants to create tax incentives for employers who  
provide on-site day care or help to parents when child-care 
arrangements fall through. He also said he would encourage 
businesses to offer job shares, flexible schedules and 
telecommuting. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore also criticized Republican presidential front-runner George  
W. Bush's proposal to cut federal education funds to 
underperforming public schools and give their students $1,500 each 
to use for tuition at private schools or tutoring. 
</P>
<P>
	Long saddled with a reputation as a stiff speaker, Gore tried to  
connect with his audience by cracking jokes, telling personal 
stories and sharing the stage with his daughter, Karenna Gore 
Schiff, a Columbia University law student. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the day, he met upstate with more than 100  
supporters. 
</P>
<P>
	With polls showing him deadlocked with Bradley in New York, a  
crucial early primary state, he sought to rally them for the ``big 
challenge we're going to meet together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got a fight on our hands,'' Gore told the crowd huddled  
under a tent to ward off the chill and drizzle outside of a rented 
country house in Pine Plains. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore had met inside with key supporters, including state  
Attorney General Eliot Spitzer, state Comptroller H. Carl McCall 
and state Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver, for what Rockland County 
Democratic Chairman Paul Adler called ``a skull session.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got to listen to the guys in the trenches,'' Adler  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	A poll released Tuesday by Marist College's Institute for Public  
Opinion had Gore and Bradley each favored by 41 percent of 
Democratic voters. A similar poll in March had Gore leading 
Bradley, 47 percent to 30 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Without naming Bradley, a former New York Knicks star, McCall  
and Spitzer used basketball metaphors to promote Gore's candidacy. 
</P>
<P>
	``When things get tough on the court, you don't want somebody  
who will quit,'' McCall said, referring to Bradley's retirement 
from the Senate in 1996 after the Republican takeover of Congress 
in elections two years earlier. ``Al Gore was there when we needed 
him, when other people walked off the court.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
