<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-05 20:40:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stars 3, Red Wings 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Brett Hull's power-play goal midway through the  
third period gave the Dallas Stars a 3-2 win over the Detroit Red 
Wings Tuesday in an early matchup of Western Conference powers. 
</P>
<P>
	The defending Stanley Cup champion Stars had a two-man advantage  
when Hull fired a pass from Joe Nieuwendyk past Detroit goalie Ken 
Wregget 11:18 into the period to break a 2-2 tie. The goal was 
Hull's second of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Sergei Zubov had a goal and an assist and Blake Sloan scored his  
first career goal for Dallas, which improved to 3-0. 
</P>
<P>
	Larry Murphy and Steve Duchesne scored goals in the second  
period for the Red Wings. Detroit is 1-4-0 in its last five 
regular-season games against Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars played without Mike Modano, who is out indefinitely  
with a mild concussion and broken nose suffered when he was hit 
from behind by Anaheim's Ruslan Salei on Saturday. Salei was given 
a 10-game suspension by the NHL on Tuesday for the hit that caused 
Modano to collide headfirst with the boards before he was removed 
on a stretcher. 
</P>
<P>
	Darryl Sydor was also out of the Stars' lineup with a fractured  
eye socket he suffered when he was hit by Anaheim's Jim McKenzie, 
who drew a four-game suspension. Niewendyk played despite the elbow 
he took from the Mighty Ducks' Pascal Trepanier, who was given a 
five-game suspension. 
</P>
<P>
	Dallas goaltender Ed Belfour made 32 saves while Wregget, signed  
as a free agent in the offseason, stopped 11 shots in his first 
start for Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars were outshot 13-0 in the first period until Zubov's  
shot from center ice glanced off Wregget's glove and then trickled 
over the goal line, giving Dallas a 1-0 lead at 16:38. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars' chances were once again limited in the second period  
as Detroit outshot them, 15-6. Wregget made a glove save on Zubov's 
shot from the right point and Nieuwendyk hit the post. 
</P>
<P>
	Detroit finally broke through just eight seconds after Hull went  
off for interference. Murphy's shot from the top of the left circle 
got past Belfour at 13:48 as he was screened by Tomas Holmstrom. 
</P>
<P>
	Only 25 seconds later, Duchesne scored his first goal as a Red  
Wing by skating in from the left with a cross-ice pass from Igor 
Larionov and beating Belfour wide to his glove side. 
</P>
<P>
	Sloan flipped a loose puck past Wregget for his first career  
goal and a 2-2 tie 3:26 into the third period. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991005.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-05 21:10:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sabres Re-Sign Miroslav Satan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- The Buffalo Sabres and Miroslav Satan  
agreed to terms on a multiyear contract Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Satan led the Sabres last season with 40 goals and 66 points. He  
was Buffalo's first 40-goal scorer since Pat LaFontaine in 1996-97. 
</P>
<P>
	The signing leaves Buffalo with two holdouts, the defensive  
pairing of Jay McKee and Rhett Warrener, as the team prepared for 
Friday's home opener with Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres lost their season opener in Detroit 2-0 as goaltender  
Dominik Hasek faced 44 shots. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
