<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Filene's Fights To Stay on Nasdaq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WELLESLEY, Mass. (AP) -- Troubled discount retailer Filene's  
Basement Corp. said it will fight the Nasdaq Stock Market's plan to 
delist its stock because the bankrupt retailer fails to meet 
minimum requirements. 
</P>
<P>
	Filene's Basement has requested a hearing to appeal the  
decision, company spokesman Rich Tauberman said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Filene's Basement filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in  
federal court Aug. 23. Nasdaq suspended trading of the company's 
shares the same day, and at Nasdaq's request, the company on Sept. 
2 submitted documents detailing its financial health, Tauberman 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	If Filene's Basement's appeal is turned down, ``the company will  
seek alternative means of having the stock traded,'' Tauberman said 
without elaborating. 
</P>
<P>
	Nasdaq spokesman Wayne Lee said the exchange does not make  
public its dealings with listed companies. A company can still 
trade on the Nasdaq if it is bankrupt, Lee said, but it must 
continue to meet certain minimum standards. 
</P>
<P>
	Among them: the company's stock must meet a minimum bid price of  
at least $1 at the close of the market, and the company must have a 
minimum of 400 shareholders and $4 million in net tangible assets. 
</P>
<P>
	The company announced last week it will close a total of 19  
underperforming stores by year's end as part of its plan to emerge 
from bankruptcy, bringing the total number of closures to 19. After 
the closings, Filene's Basement will have 32 stores, which will 
continue to operate while the company reorganizes its debt. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991005.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-05 07:30:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Move Higher; Dow Up 23.74 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks edged higher this morning as investors  
remained confident that today's Federal Reserve strategy meeting 
would not produce another boost in interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones  
industrial average was up 23.74 at 10,424.97, building on Monday's 
128-point rally. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mostly positive, although  
declining issues outnumbered advancers by a slender margin on the 
New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	In Nasdaq trading, however, gainers led by a 6-to-5 ratio, and  
the Nasdaq composite index was up 10.46 at 2,806.43. The Standard &AMP; 
Poor's 500 index was up 1.64 at 1,306.24. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading was expected to remain somewhat restrained until the  
afternoon, when Fed officials were expected to conclude one of 
their periodic meetings on inflation and interest rate policy. 
</P>
<P>
	Signs of inflationary growth in the economy have prompted the  
Fed to boost lending rates twice in recent months, but analysts 
expected the central bank to take a wait-and-see approach going 
forward. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecommunications stocks led the early advance amid news that  
MCI WorldCom had sealed an agreement to acquire long-distance rival 
Sprint for $115 billion in what would be the largest corporate 
takeover in history. 
</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom, slipped 1 to 70 5/8 as the most active Nasdaq issue,  
while Sprint was up 1 3/8 at 62 1/4 on the NYSE. Among other leading 
telecom names, AT&AMP;T was up 1 at 44 3/4 on the NYSE and Qwest 
Communications was up 1 1/2 at 34 3/16. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading today, the Russell 2000 index of smaller  
companies was up 0.18 at 426.79. 
</P>
<P>
	NYSE volume totaled 114.41 million shares, up from 93.38 million  
at the same point on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.12 percent. In  
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 0.83 percent, 
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.06 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up 
0.63 percent. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991005.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-05 23:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Signs $289B Defense Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The fiscal 2000 defense bill signed into law  
by President Clinton includes a host of financial incentives -- 
including the biggest military pay raise in 18 years -- that the 
Pentagon is counting on to boost recruiting and persuade more 
troops to make a career of their service. 
</P>
<P>
	``The excellence of our military is the direct product of the  
excellence of our men and women in uniform,'' Clinton said Tuesday 
in a bill-signing ceremony at the Pentagon. ``This bill invests in 
that excellence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The pay package, including a 4.8 percent across-the-board raise  
effective Jan. 1 and a change in pay scales effective next July, 
represents the biggest increase in compensation in a generation, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense Secretary William Cohen, who joined Clinton on the  
Pentagon steps to thank Congress for forging the legislation, said 
service members deserve better pay and working conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to recruit and retain the best people and provide them  
with a sound quality of life if we're going to remain a dominant 
force for good for the future,'' Cohen said. 
</P>
<P>
	The $289 billion defense bill represents an $18 billion increase  
over fiscal 1999, which ended Sept. 30. Republicans in Congress 
were quick to point out it is also $8 billion more than Clinton had 
requested. 
</P>
<P>
	``While this bill does not fully address all of the Joint  
Chiefs' critical requirements, ... it does provide short-term fixes 
necessary to ensure an improved quality of military life for our 
service members and their families,'' said Rep. Floyd Spence, 
R-S.C., chairman of the House Armed Services Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The 4.8 percent pay raise is the highest since a 14.3 percent  
boost in 1981. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon announced Tuesday that the Air Force ended the 1999  
fiscal year with a manpower shortage of about 10,000 -- a 
combination of too few recruits and too many people leaving the 
service for commercial aviation jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Army, Navy and Marine Corps reached troop strength levels  
set by Congress, although only the Marines -- the smallest of the 
major services with 172,500 people -- met their goals in both 
recruiting and retention. 
</P>
<P>
	The Air Force, which for years didn't need to bother with TV  
advertising, fell short in both recruiting and retention, whereas 
the Army overcame a recruiting shortfall by exceeding its retention 
goal. The Navy, which was nearly 7,000 recruits short in 1998, met 
its goal this year. 
</P>
<P>
	In a related development Tuesday, the Parents Television  
Council, a private advocacy group, complained in a letter to Army 
Secretary Louis Caldera about the Army buying recruit advertising 
time on TV shows that the council considers excessively violent and 
offensive. 
</P>
<P>
	The group's Steven Schweim said the objectionable shows include  
``WWF Smackdown,'' a wrestling program. He said the Army helped 
sponsor five episodes, and the Navy and Air Force sponsored one 
each. Schweim said his group planned to complain to Navy and Air 
Force leaders later. 
</P>
<P>
	``The programs the Army is currently sponsoring, which glorify  
wanton and cruel violence, obscenity and the mockery of America's 
great presidents and military heroes, undermine the Army's own core 
values,'' Brent Bozell, the chairman of the Parents Television 
Council, wrote to Caldera. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about such objections, a senior Pentagon official who  
spoke on condition of anonymity said the services are mainly 
interested in reaching the largest possible audience of potential 
recruits. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
