<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> North Dakotans Suing Over Insurance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) -- As Howard and Adeline Snortland approached  
their 80s, they decided to insure themselves against future steep 
nursing care costs. Nearly a decade later, they have dropped their 
coverage, after paying almost $12,000 for it. 
</P>
<P>
	``We thought it was a good idea to protect our children in case  
we were not in a condition to take care of ourselves,'' said Howard 
Snortland, now 87. ``We're discouraged.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Snortlands, of Bismarck, are among hundreds of North  
Dakotans who are suing two insurance companies that, they say, 
lured them to buy long-term care insurance policies with prices 
that were too low, then dramatically raised their rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Their first annual premium was $889 in 1987. By 1995, when the  
Snortlands dropped their policies, the rate had more than tripled, 
to $2,947, after premium increases of 25 percent, 25 percent and 40 
percent, Howard Snortland said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought this was ridiculous,'' he said. ``There was nothing  
to prevent them from going to 50 percent next time. I just didn't 
trust them anymore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A jury is being selected this week to hear the case, which  
focuses on whether the premium increases were justified. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court in Bismarck, seeks  
unspecified damages. It alleges that Acceleration Life Insurance 
Co. of Dublin, Ohio, and Commonwealth Life Insurance Co. of 
Louisville, Ky., sold fraudulently underpriced long-term care 
policies in North Dakota. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies later raised their rates exorbitantly, to force  
policyholders into dropping their coverage and lose the premiums 
they had paid, the lawsuit says. 
</P>
<P>
	Acceleration and Commonwealth have denied the claims in court  
filings, saying the coverage was priced properly, and that the 
policies did not violate North Dakota insurance law. Their 
attorneys declined to comment further. 
</P>
<P>
	Similar lawsuits have been filed in Wyoming and Florida by Allan  
Kanner, a New Orleans lawyer who is one of the lead attorneys in 
the North Dakota case. 
</P>
<P>
	Long-term care insurance covers a certain amount of custodial  
care for the elderly or sick in their own homes, or in nursing 
homes. The policies are a popular way for older people to protect 
their estates from being depleted by high nursing care costs, said 
Trent Heinemeyer, North Dakota's deputy insurance commissioner. 
</P>
<P>
	Insurers that sell policies in North Dakota must have Insurance  
Department approval of their rates. 
</P>
<P>
	``If a company has issued policies after we approved a rate and  
three years down the road says they need a 50 percent rate 
increase, we require they prove it's necessary,'' Heinemeyer said. 
If that requirement is met, he said, ``our hands are somewhat tied 
in denying that increase.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit says Acceleration Life and Commonwealth Life raised  
their premiums annually from 1989 to 1996. In some cases, the total 
increase during that time was as much as 700 percent, forcing most 
policyholders to dump their coverage, the lawsuit contends. 
</P>
<P>
	Fewer than 300 North Dakotans out of more than 2,000 who bought  
nursing home policies from the two companies still have them, and 
those who still do are paying astronomical premiums, the lawsuit 
says. 
</P>
<P>
	The insurance policies themselves told buyers that premiums  
could rise. The lawsuit acknowledges that, but says the policies 
gave no hint of the steep premium increases to come. 
</P>
<P>
	Big rate increases on some long-term care policies during the  
late 1980s and early 1990s could be tied to rising health care 
costs, said Shelly Peterson, president of the North Dakota Long 
Term Care Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Long-term care insurance ``has been a developing field,''  
Peterson said. ``Maybe some companies didn't have as much 
information to price the product as they should.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Acceleration Life and Commonwealth Life were pioneers in the  
field of long-term care insurance and were likely caught unaware of 
the cost, said Pamela Schmidt, vice president of SIA Marketing in 
Bismarck. SIA Marketing, which sells long-term care policies 
nationwide, did some business with Acceleration Life several years 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think anybody knew enough about long-term care to  
deliberately'' defraud, Schmidt said. ``No one had any statistics 
on usage ... and what happened with Acceleration was they didn't 
charge enough and then they started paying out high benefits.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Acceleration and Commonwealth assert in court documents that the  
Insurance Department considered their premium increases reasonable. 
Even with them, they collected about $26.4 million in premiums and 
paid $40.2 million in benefits, the companies said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were some really tough increases that were requested,  
that we had no choice but to approve because the company was paying 
out way more in benefits than they were receiving in premiums,'' 
Insurance Commissioner Glenn Pomeroy said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Snortlands' experience with long-term care insurance has  
turned them off on the concept, and they plan to pay for future 
nursing care out of their pensions and Social Security benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	They also plan to lobby for better consumer protection. Howard  
Snortland, who is a former state superintendent of public 
instruction, was an unsuccessful Democratic candidate for the North 
Dakota Senate last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just hoping that either through the Legislature or the  
courts, we can protect people,'' he said. ``It's unscrupulous 
insurance companies taking advantage of old people.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
