<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Activist Proposes Liquor Store </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) -- Unable to persuade the government to shut  
down white-owned liquor stores near the Pine Ridge Indian 
Reservation, American Indian activist Russell Means said he wants 
to open a liquor store and use the profits to treat alcoholism. 
</P>
<P>
	Alcohol is banned on the South Dakota reservation, a  
5,000-square-mile expanse that is home to 15,000 Oglala Sioux and 
has one of the nation's highest alcoholism-related mortality rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Four stores in Whiteclay -- just two miles from the reservation --  
sell millions of dollars worth of beer each year, most of it to 
Oglala Sioux. 
</P>
<P>
	Means said he wants to form a nonprofit corporation to open a  
liquor store in the tiny town and use the proceeds to build an 
alcohol rehabilitation center. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a win-win situation for the governor, state of Nebraska  
and for the taxpayers,'' Means said Monday. ``We don't want to run 
anybody out of business, contrary to the American way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Mike Johanns, who has met with tribal leaders in the past  
to discuss concerns, said the state would treat Means' liquor 
license application ``like any other application that comes 
forward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Means, co-founder of the American Indian Movement, was among  
several Indians who were arrested July 3 in Whiteclay while 
protesting the alcohol sales and the unsolved murders of two Oglala 
Sioux men found earlier this year just outside the town. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he would like to have the store open by spring.  
</P>
<P>
	Fellow activist Frank LaMere said he supports Means' idea.  
</P>
<P>
	``It will empower the Oglala people and give them some control --  
which is something that don't have now,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
