<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Moderate Quake Shakes Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MARMARIS, Turkey (AP) -- Another earthquake hit Turkey on  
Tuesday, jolting this resort town and sending tourists and 
residents into the streets or jumping from balconies in panic. 
</P>
<P>
	Hospital officials said 32 people were treated for broken legs  
or arms and 70 others suffered from shock. One person had a broken 
back. 
</P>
<P>
	Istanbul's Kandilli Observatory said the epicenter of the quake  
was at Marmaris, 470 miles south of Istanbul. Most people in the 
resort were asleep when the magnitude 5.2 quake hit at 3:53 a.m. At 
least six aftershocks followed. 
</P>
<P>
	There were no reports of any tourists being injured.  
</P>
<P>
	A magnitude 7.4 quake devastated Istanbul and other areas of  
northwest Turkey on Aug. 17, killing some 16,000 people. Those who 
threw themselves out of windows and off balconies Tuesday 
apparently feared they could be trapped if their houses collapsed, 
reports said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some tourists set out for home after the quake. Others who had  
come to enjoy the sun, sand and deep-blue bays around Marmaris took 
to sleeping on beach mattresses or napping at outdoor cafes after 
the quake. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although there is no intense panic, they want to go back  
home,'' said Ibrahim Gurkan, an official from the Marmaris Elegance 
Hotel. ``We are trying to help them to fly back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Local officials decided to close the schools to assess damage  
and let children -- some of whom had spent the night outside -- 
recover and rest. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
