<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Leading Economic Indicators Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A key gauge of future economic activity declined  
in August following three straight monthly gains. But the nation's 
economy still seems robust enough to keep growing through February 
and into the record books as the longest expansion ever in U.S. 
history, the Conference Board reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Index of Leading Economic Indicators, designed to forecast  
economic activity three to six months in the future, fell 0.1 
percent in August. It had risen nine times in the last 11 months, 
including an increase of 0.3 percent in each of previous three 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	The first decline in the index since a 0.1 percent dip in April  
signals that rising interest rates are starting to slow the 
economy, said an economist at the Conference Board, a 
business-sponsored research organization. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Reserve has raised short-term interest rates twice  
since June in an attempt to keep the economy from overheating to 
the point that it revives higher inflation. Fed policy-makers met 
again Tuesday, leaving rates unchanged for the time being. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Fed warned that its policy bias now leans toward raising  
interest rates and said it will be especially watchful for signs of 
inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with the slight decline in the leading index, which was not  
as steep as analysts' expected, the economy continues to grow, the 
Conference Board said. 
</P>
<P>
	The figures suggest the nation's longest peacetime economic  
expansion, which began in March 1991, has enough strength to become 
the longest on record, said Ken Goldstein, an economist for the 
group. 
</P>
<P>
	The longest economic expansion in U.S. history lasted for 106  
months, from February 1961 until December 1969. The current 
expansion will pass that record if it runs through February 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Rising interest rates have affected some sectors of the economy,  
leading to a dip in new housing construction and a slight drop in 
the average workweek, Goldstein said. 
</P>
<P>
	The most significant drags on the index in August were slower  
deliveries from vendors, lower stock prices, reduced consumer 
expectations and a decline in building permits. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, five of the 10 indicators that make up the leading index  
rose in August, including orders for nondefense capital goods and 
manufacturers' new orders for consumer goods. 
</P>
<P>
	One economist said the tiny drop in August did not yet signal a  
trend. 
</P>
<P>
	``Following three months of solid gains this seems like a mere  
wiggle,'' said Michael Moran, chief economist at Daiwa Securities 
America. ``We need to see a lot more movement before we see any 
real signal of weakness in the economy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The coincident index, which measure current expansion, rose 0.2  
percent in August, the fourth consecutive monthly rise of at least 
0.2 percent. The lagging index, which measures recent past 
performance, rose 0.2 percent after a gain of 0.5 percent in July 
and a 0.4 percent decline in June. 
</P>
<P>
	The leading indicators are calculated from a base of 100, set in  
1992. First calculated in the late 1960s, it is periodically 
fine-tuned and figures from past years are revised. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
