<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Florida Coach Concerned With Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Soon, No. 8 Florida will find out if  
two Steve Spurriers are better than one. 
</P>
<P>
	Frustrated with a young defense ranked last in the Southeastern  
Conference, Spurrier, the longtime mastermind on offense, has 
decided to expand his responsibilities and start helping coach the 
defense. 
</P>
<P>
	This week, he began sitting in on defensive meetings, a place  
where he was a stranger in recent seasons. He wants to offer 
suggestions and make himself more accountable for a unit that has 
struggled under first-year coordinator Jon Hoke. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if it will do any good,'' Spurrier said. ``But  
you know me. We're not going to do the same stuff we've been doing, 
that's for sure. We're going to try something different. I can't 
watch that and I know our fans don't want to watch what we 
attempted last week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The defense languished on the field for more than 42 minutes  
last week in a 40-39 loss to Alabama, mainly because it couldn't 
stop the Crimson Tide on third down. Alabama converted 11 of 20 
third downs, including four on third-and-8 or longer. 
</P>
<P>
	Defensive backs were continually out of position. Defensive  
linemen produced only one sack. Linebackers seemed lost through 
most of the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Enter Spurrier, who has taken a larger role in the defense  
before, but not since at least 1995, the year before Bob Stoops 
become coordinator. Stoops departed, as did most of last year's 
players, leaving this year's defense inexperienced and, at many 
times, looking clueless. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to try to find out the ones that will accept  
coaching instead of the ones who do their own stuff out there,'' 
Spurrier said. ``That's called coaching. When you're struggling, 
you've got to try to coach better. You've got to try to put players 
out there who you think at least will try to do what you're asking 
them to do. 
</P>
<P>
	Two players, safety Lester Norwood and linebacker Keith Kelsey,  
are candidates to lose their starting positions this week, although 
there is no more experience behind them on the depth chart. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoke, who coached defensive backs at Missouri last year, says he  
is not threatened by Spurrier's decision to step in. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not a big deal, it's not a big problem,'' Hoke said. ``He  
doesn't come in there and demand you do this or demand you do that. 
He just says, `Well, this is kind of what people are doing to us 
now. If it fits, great. You might want to take a look at it.' 
That's his approach to it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Spurrier says the Gators will do different things Saturday at  
LSU. He has mentioned trying more blitzing. He's also considering 
dropping eight players into coverage so Florida will ``have someone 
back there trying to cover somebody, trying to back up one of those 
linebackers who gets out of position.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After allowing 865 yards in the first two games of the season,  
Florida looked like it was getting better, giving up just 287 
against Tennessee and 317 to Kentucky. 
</P>
<P>
	The breakdowns returned against Alabama, which gained 447 yards  
and stayed on the field for a strength-sapping 81 plays. 
</P>
<P>
	Safety Marquand Manuel says the situation has become  
frustrating, but the Gators defenders aren't giving up. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't get off the field, we didn't create turnovers,''  
Manuel said. ``But it's not all going downhill. We played hard. We 
know storms will come, but we've just got to prevail.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
