<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kaiser Talks To Resume Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) -- Kaiser Aluminum &AMP; Chemical Corp. and the  
United Steelworkers will resume negotiations next week in hopes of 
ending a yearlong labor dispute affecting 2,900 union members in 
three states. 
</P>
<P>
	The sides said Monday their top negotiators will meet Oct. 14-15  
in Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kaiser dispute affects about 2,100 Steelworkers at two  
plants in the Spokane, Wash., area, along with smaller numbers of 
workers in Tacoma, Wash., Gramercy, La., and Newark, Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	The Steelworkers struck Sept. 30, 1998, over wages, proposed  
workforce reductions, reduced retirement benefits and contracting 
work to outside sources. 
</P>
<P>
	All five plants have continued to operate with temporary  
workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The last round of talks ended Aug. 26 over the company's demand  
that 239 jobs be removed from Steelworkers jurisdiction. 
</P>
<P>
	Kaiser, the nation's fifth largest aluminum producer, is seeking  
to contract out the jobs of carpenters, machinists, janitors, truck 
drivers, security guards and other employees. 
</P>
<P>
	In its latest offer, Kaiser proposed pay increases of $3.13 per  
hour over the length of a five-year contract, plus some benefits 
improvements. The company said base wages for its workers are more 
than $40,000 a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Kaiser is also demanding that 700 jobs be eliminated at the five  
plants -- a move it says can be accomplished mostly by attrition. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
