<DOCNO> APW19991005.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-05 14:50:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Bulls Try To Learn New Plays </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DEERFIELD, Ill. (AP) -- When the Chicago Bulls signed Hersey  
Hawkins, they figured the veteran would be the perfect player to 
help tutor the team's seven rookies. 
</P>
<P>
	That's fine. Now if only someone would explain to Hawkins what  
the Bulls are doing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know any of this stuff, either,'' he said, laughing,  
after the Bulls opened training camp Tuesday. ``That's the unique 
thing about it. Being a veteran, I'm still learning the system and 
all the plays just like the younger guys are. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the first time in my 12 years that I've gone into  
training camp and have really had to learn things that are totally 
new and totally foreign to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Welcome to life with the Bulls.  
</P>
<P>
	Chicago is almost an entirely different team from the group that  
won the NBA title in 1998, which means coach Tim Floyd has a lot of 
explaining to do during training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	The offense, the defense -- it's new to just about everyone.  
</P>
<P>
	``We have to gain a lot of ground in a short period of time,  
given the complexities of the offense,'' Floyd said. ``But we do 
have a full camp to do that, and we'll take it stage by stage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though Michael Jordan, Phil Jackson and Tex Winter are gone,  
Floyd still plans to use the triangle offense that was a hallmark 
of Chicago's six championship teams. It can be very successful -- 
know any other teams that won six titles in eight years recently? -- 
but everyone has to understand it and be able to run it smoothly. 
</P>
<P>
	That's the tricky part. Ask anyone who's ever run the triangle  
how tough it was to learn, and he'll probably just shake his head. 
It takes weeks, sometimes months, to pick it up. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not the type of offense you learn overnight,'' said  
Will Perdue, a member of Chicago's first three championship teams 
who rejoined the Bulls after spending his last four seasons in San 
Antonio. 
</P>
<P>
	Perdue and B.J. Armstrong, who also played on the first three  
title teams, know the triangle, as does Toni Kukoc. Randy Brown and 
Dickey Simpkins learned it under Jackson, too, though they didn't 
get much playing time until last year. Kornel David, Cory Carr and 
Corey Benjamin also got some exposure to the triangle last season. 
</P>
<P>
	Now it's time to show it to the new guys.  
</P>
<P>
	``We don't feel like our offense will be comfortable with our  
guys until probably the second or third month,'' Floyd said. 
``That's just because, once again, we have seven or eight new 
players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After a year off, defense will be a priority again this season.  
Chicago's championship teams were so tenacious on defense they were 
stifling. Jackson used to call his players the ``Dobermans.'' 
Jordan made a record nine appearances on the NBA's All-Defensive 
team, and he and teammate Scottie Pippen led that list of honorees 
in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	But with a lockout-shortened training camp and an almost  
entirely new team, something had to give with the Bulls last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was really ridiculous to try to teach eight new guys the  
triangle. We knew it going in,'' Floyd said. ``We knew that if we 
spent time in that area, that we wouldn't have enough time to be 
spent on the defensive end with the restricted number of practices 
we had. 
</P>
<P>
	``But it was all about carryover. It was all about trying to  
establish some type of foundation about how we were going to play 
in hopes those guys would garner some experience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So Floyd, a defensive coach at heart, endured a team that could  
barely get back to the other end of the court. Forced turnovers? 
Baskets off defense? What were those? 
</P>
<P>
	But that won't happen this year if Floyd has his way. The Bulls  
are going to play defense and they're going to play it hard. And 
just so everyone was clear on just how important it is, Floyd made 
defense, not offense, the focus of the first practice. 
</P>
<P>
	``A year ago, without being able to emphasize the defense like  
we wanted to, I don't know that you could ever get that 
established, or get any base to your team in terms of a belief 
system,'' Floyd said. ``This year, we have an opportunity to create 
some type of atmosphere.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now all he needs to do is explain it to the new guys.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
