<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Nixon Tapes Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Never suspecting that his secret taping system  
would eventually led to his resignation, President Nixon was 
cheerful and inquisitive the first morning the recording system was 
up and running in the Oval Office, a newly released tape shows. 
</P>
<P>
	``How does it work in here?'' Nixon asks his aide, Alexander  
Butterfield about 8 a.m. on Feb. 16, 1971. 
</P>
<P>
	It didn't work very well, judging from the poor quality of the  
recording, which was among 445 hours of tape recordings released 
today by the National Archives. Buzzing and humming noises from the 
recording machine drown out many words, but snippets of the 
conversation -- the first of 3,700 hours that Nixon would secretly 
record -- can be deciphered. 
</P>
<P>
	``The purpose of this is to have the whole thing in the file for  
a potential leak,'' Nixon says. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes, sir,'' replies Butterfield, who then goes on to school  
Nixon on the technical aspects of the voice-activated system and 
answer his queries about who was aware of its existence. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are only five people that know about it outside of (Bob)  
Haldeman (Nixon's chief of staff) and you and me,'' says 
Butterfield, who two years later would disclose to the Senate 
Watergate Committee the existence of the taping system. The tapes 
provided the evidence that ended Nixon's presidency and landed a 
few of his associates in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Since Nixon resigned in 1974, only 420 hours have been released  
of the estimated 3,700 hours of his presidential recordings. Most 
of those that have been made public deal with the break-in at the 
Democratic National Committee headquarters in the Watergate 
riverfront office building and the subsequent White House cover-up. 
</P>
<P>
	After Nixon resigned to avoid impeachment, the government seized  
his tapes. The former president, and later his estate, went to 
court to get them back. Years of legal wrangling and archival 
processing work stalled the release of the tapes. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's release, covering events between February and August  
1971, is the first in a series of chronological tape openings 
planned at the archives' complex in College Park, Md. 
</P>
<P>
	On the tapes that were released today, Nixon talks with White  
House staff members, his foreign policy advisers, congressmen, 
Cabinet secretaries and reporters. He discusses a vast array of 
foreign and domestic issues, including Vietnam, China, the Soviet 
Union, the environment, busing, unemployment and anti-war 
demonstrations. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an amazingly rich resource. Scholars are going to be  
chewing on this stuff for 50 years,'' said John Taylor, executive 
director of the Nixon Library &AMP; Birthplace Foundation in Yorba 
Linda, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the tapes were released with transcripts that the  
archives supplied over the years in response to court cases. Some 
excerpts from transcripts: 
</P>
<P>
	--On April 19, 1971, Nixon makes disparaging comments about  
federal workers. ``We have no discipline in this bureaucracy. We 
never fire anybody. We never reprimand anybody. We never demote 
anybody. We always promote the sons-of-bitches that kick us in the 
ass,'' Nixon tells John Ehrlichman, counsel to the president. 
``That's true in the State Department. It's true in HEW. It's true 
in OMB, and true for ourselves, and it's got to stop.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--On April 27, 1971, Nixon tells secretary Rose Mary Woods that  
the administration must stand firm in the face of protesters 
opposing U.S. Involvement in the Vietnam War. ``They're all a funny 
bunch, but, uh, well, I tell ya, we're going to stand firm against 
'em; I got (national security adviser) Henry (Kissinger) in here. I 
said, `Now look, just, they're not going to rattle us one bit. 
We're gonna stay on our course. This country's not gonna be run by 
a bunch of goddamned rabble. Don't you agree?'' 
</P>
<P>
	--On May 7, 1971, Nixon underscores his belief that the anti-war  
demonstrations represent only a tiny slice of American public 
opinion. ``I thought, uh, that guy standin' up there naked in front 
of everybody, that must've just turned off the heartland by the 
millions.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
