<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Braves, Astros Ready for Series  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The Atlanta Braves relaxed in front on their  
television sets, wondering who they would play today. The Houston 
Astros sat on a runway, wondering if their plane would fly east or 
west? 
</P>
<P>
	About 10 o'clock Monday night, both teams finally got the  
answer. 
</P>
<P>
	The NL Central champion Astros, their travel plans in shambles  
because of a wild-card playoff game in Cincinnati, didn't learn 
they would play the Braves in the best-of-5 division series until 
the Reds lost 5-0 to the New York Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	That sent the New Yorkers to Arizona, while the Astros turned  
their charter jet eastward and headed toward Atlanta to meet the 
team that has eight straight division titles and baseball's best 
record at 103-59. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know I wouldn't want to play a game after flying to Arizona  
or coming here,'' Braves MVP candidate Chipper Jones said. ``That 
takes a toll on your body. It usually takes a day or two to 
regroup.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The closest the Braves got to a plane was Javy Lopez's  
remote-control version. 
</P>
<P>
	When rain wiped out a scheduled workout at Turner Field, the  
injured Atlanta catcher broke out his model aircraft, the stadium's 
vast expanse giving him plenty of room for a series of twisting, 
spinning maneuvers. 
</P>
<P>
	Greg Maddux (19-9), who will start the opener for Atlanta  
against Shane Reynolds (16-14), spent the night watching videos 
from his recent performances against both Houston and Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	If Cincinnati had won the playoff, Atlanta would have met the  
Reds and Houston would have played Arizona in the other division 
series. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would prefer to know,'' Maddux said earlier Monday. ``But I  
would prefer there be no traffic when I come to the park, too. It's 
really not that big a deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not after what the Braves went through this year. They lost  
cleanup hitter Andres Galarraga and closer Kerry Ligtenberg before 
opening day, while Lopez and pitchers Odalis Perez and Rudy Seanez 
went down during the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a grittier, guttier team,'' Jones said. ``We're not  
going to pop anybody's eyes out. We don't have the firepower of 
some of our other teams. But we do the little things to score 
runs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Every year about this time, the Braves face questions about  
their lack of postseason success. Despite eight straight 
appearances -- three more than any team in baseball history -- they 
have won just one World Series title in the 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the dark cloud that always hangs over the Braves,''  
said Brian Jordan, who brought emotion to the clubhouse, not to 
mention a career-high 115 RBIs. ``Hopefully, this is the year we 
get the breaks and finally win another world championship. If not, 
we've still exceeded our expectations this season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Houston clinched its third straight NL Central title on the  
final day of the regular season, finishing one game ahead of 
Cincinnati. The Astros have been quickly eliminated in their last 
two playoff trips, a sweep by Atlanta in 1997 and a 3-1 loss to San 
Diego last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first year it was new and maybe a little overwhelming.  
Last year we weren't able to do a lot,'' manager Larry Dierker 
said. ``This year, all we're ready to do is go out and play the 
best baseball we can. If it's 3-0 again, well, we're going to give 
it our best.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Astros didn't seem concerned about their late-night travel  
plans. 
</P>
<P>
	``This won't bother them,'' general manager Gerry Hunsicker  
said. ``I don't think anything can happen to this club that hasn't 
already happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like the Braves, Houston survived a devastating medical report.  
Moises Alou missed the entire season, while Derek Bell and Ken 
Caminiti were plagued by injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're the underdogs and maybe that's good,'' Reynolds said.  
``Everyone expects them to win, so let them have all the 
pressure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Astros went 1-6 against the Braves during the regular  
season, including a three-game sweep at the Turner Field, site of 
Games 1 and 2. The series shifts to Astrodome on Friday for Game 3. 
</P>
<P>
	The first of Houston's 20-game winners, Jose Lima (21-10), faces  
Kevin Millwood (18-7, 2.68 ERA) in Wednesday's game. Cy Young 
contender Mike Hampton (22-4) follows for the Astros against last 
year's Cy Young winner, Tom Glavine (13-11). 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the credit for the Braves' success must go to manager  
Bobby Cox, who businesslike demeanor was criticized in the past, 
but served the team well when one player after another went down. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bobby didn't panic,'' Millwood said. ``We just went about our  
business the way we always have.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
