<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 7 Big 10 Teams in AP Football Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The Big Ten is boss in the Top 25, at least until Saturday.  
</P>
<P>
	A record seven schools from the 11-team Big Ten appear in this  
week's Associated Press college football poll, the first time a 
conference has placed so many teams in the rankings. 
</P>
<P>
	The record probably will last all of one week, since three Big  
Ten games on Saturday feature six of its seven Top 25 teams: No. 3 
Michigan (5-0) at No. 11 Michigan State (5-0); No. 17 Purdue (4-1) 
at No. 21 Ohio State (3-2); and No. 20 Wisconsin (3-2) at No. 25 
Minnesota (4-0). 
</P>
<P>
	Penn State (5-0), the highest ranked team in the league at No.  
2, is at Iowa, which along with Illinois, Indiana and Northwestern 
comprise the rest of the Big Ten. The Nittany Lions became the 
league's 11th team in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	The AP media poll began in 1936 as a Top 20 until 1960. It was a  
Top 10 from 1961-67 before it returned to a Top 20 from 1968-88. In 
'89, the poll became the Top 25. 
</P>
<P>
	Several conferences previously have placed six teams in the AP's  
Top 25, including the Big Ten, Big 12, Pac-10 and SEC. The SEC was 
the first with six -- in 1985 when it was a 10-team league and the 
poll consisted of 20 teams. 
</P>
<P>
	The combination of bigger conferences and the AP poll's  
expansion from a Top 20 to Top 25, has given leagues more chances 
to have more teams ranked. Also, league teams usually open the 
season against weak nonconference opponents before Big Ten play 
begins. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SENIOR CLASS:* College football's three grand ol' coaches --  
73-year-old Joe Paterno, 69-year-old Bobby Bowden and 68-year-old 
LaVell Edwards -- aren't going anywhere soon. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida State's Bowden re-upped for five more years through 2004  
-- at $1.5 million per -- on Monday, a few weeks after Brigham 
Young's Edwards signed a new deal that will keep him around Provo 
through 2004. 
</P>
<P>
	Paterno, whose contract is not public, won't commit to his usual  
``four more years'' preseason proclamation, but made it clear he'll 
be strolling the sideline awhile longer. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to say I'm going to wait four more years  
anymore. It may be two, three, six, eight, or 10,'' JoePa said 
before the season started. ``My problem is there's nothing else I 
really want to do. I really don't want to wait around until 
cocktail hour at 5 p.m.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bowden, who turns 70 next month, has 297 career wins, and can  
get No. 300 on Oct. 23 when his top-ranked Seminoles play Clemson, 
coached by his son, Tommy. Paterno became the fourth major college 
coach to win 300 games last season. Edwards has 246 career wins. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *PIRATES RETURN:* East Carolina, 5-0 for the first time since  
1976, plays its first home game at Dowdy-Ficklen Stadium since 
Hurricane Floyd struck on Sept. 16. 
</P>
<P>
	The 16th-ranked Pirates play host to Southern Mississippi in a  
Conference USA game that could be the final hurdle to a perfect 
season for one of the early surprise teams of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Southern Mississippi (2-2), off last week, is coming off tough  
losses to No. 4 Nebraska and No. 13 Texas A&AMP;M, and has proved to be 
a problem for East Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	The Golden Eagles have won all three games against the Pirates  
since C-USA play began in 1996, and holds an 18-6 series lead. The 
Eagles won 41-7 last year in Hattiesburg. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there's any game I don't want to lose, it's Southern  
Miss,'' Pirates QB David Garrard said. ``We've had tough times 
against them, and I really want to go out there and play well. 
Everything has to go right for, because they're going to be 
ready.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After Southern Miss, the Pirates play Tulane at home, Houston  
and Alabama-Birmingham on the road and finish at home against 
Cincinnati and North Carolina State. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *Around the conferences:    	
</P>
<P>
                              	 *ACC    	
</P>
<P>
	Georgia Tech, which plays North Carolina on Saturday, leads the  
nation in scoring (43.5) and total offense (517.3), while the Tar 
Heels are 93rd in total defense (408.8). ... Clemson QB Brandon 
Streeter (broken collarbone) is out four to six weeks, perhaps 
bringing an early end to his five-year career. If the Tigers 
qualify for a bowl game, Streeter could be ready. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *Big East    	
</P>
<P>
	West Virginia, off on Saturday, is 1-4 for the first time since  
1994. Rutgers and Temple are next on the schedule, but the future 
doesn't look good with games against Virginia Tech, Miami, Boston 
College and Pittsburgh. Says senior LB Barrett Green: ``We can say 
the hell with it, or we can finish this and try to get better on 
the things we need to improve on.'' After WVU's 31-28 loss to Navy 
on Saturday, an airplane flying above Mountaineer Field had this 
message: ``Nehlen must go.'' ... Miami, at No. 1 Florida State on 
Saturday, is 10-5 against the Seminoles at Tallahassee, but the 
'Noles have won the last three, including 47-0 in '97. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *Big Ten    	
</P>
<P>
	For the first time since 1961, No. 3 Michigan at No. 11 Michigan  
State is a battle of unbeatens. Tickets for the game at East 
Lansing are long sold out, but hit the Internet if you're still 
looking. Earlier this week, tickets went for more than $450 on 
eBay, an Internet auction site. ... After a 42-17 loss to 
Wisconsin, Ohio State coach John Cooper said: ``Guys, it's been a 
long time since we've been physically whipped like that in a 
game.'' It's been 32 years. The loss was the Buckeyes' worst at 
Ohio Stadium since a 41-6 defeat against Purdue on Oct. 14, 1967. 
... Not only is Minnesota -- a 33-14 winner over Northwestern on 
Saturday -- in the Top 25 for the first time since 1985, but the 
Golden Gophers also snagged their first Big Ten road win since Oct. 
22, 1994. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *Pac-10    	
</P>
<P>
	Since its school-record 20-game winning streak ended late last  
season, UCLA is 2-5. The Bruins are 2-3 this season entering 
Saturday's game against Oregon, the first of five straight home 
games. The wins were against Boise State and Fresno State; the 
losses were against Miami and Wisconsin in '98, and Ohio State, 
Stanford and Arizona State in '99. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
                              	 *SEC    	
</P>
<P>
	Florida freshman RB Earnest Graham had surgery this week to  
remove a blood clot from his left thigh. The injury occurred two 
games ago against Kentucky, and his playing status will be updated 
next week. Other injured Gators include WR Travis Taylor (ankle) 
and center Zac Zedalis (knee). ... Mississippi FB Charles 
Stackhouse had torn cartilage repaired in his left knee but could 
return by Oct. 16, against Alabama. Also, SS Kenny Woods 
(hamstring) is out for the season. ... Tennessee may have beaten 
Auburn 24-0, but five times the Vols reached the Tigers' 23 or 
better without scoring a point. Tee Martin threw interceptions; 
there was a poor center snap and the game ended on the fifth 
chance. ... Florida and LSU, which hook up on Saturday are both 
coming off tough losses -- the Gators lost 40-39 to Alabama in OT on 
a second-chance extra point; the Tigers lost 23-22 to Georgia on a 
failed 2-point conversion with 18 seconds left. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *Elsewhere:    	
</P>
<P>
	Grove City's R.J. Bowers, with 270 yards on 28 carries, tied a  
Division III record with his 11th 200-yard game in a 56-0 victory 
over Thiel. ... Lehigh has I-AA's longest winning streak at 16 
games. ... Hofstra RB Vaughn Sanders ended his career 7 yards shy 
of the school career rushing record after breaking his left leg in 
the Flying Dutchmen's 27-14 win over Massachusetts. Sanders has 
2,497 yards; Bill Sanford had 2,503 from 1951-54. 
  	   	
</P>
