<HEADLINE> Mint Where Euros Mad Goes on Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLERMONT-FERRAND, France (AP) -- A strike by workers disrupted  
production Tuesday at a French government mint that is scheduled to 
begin printing Europe's new currency, the euro. 
</P>
<P>
	About 20 percent of the 280 employees at the plant located in  
Chamalieres, 260 miles south of Paris, followed a call by two trade 
unions, the CGT and CFDT, for a 24-hour walkout. 
</P>
<P>
	The strikers are opposed to a plan to keep the presses working  
around the clock, five days a week, for the massive job of printing 
the euro, which goes into circulation in 2002. 
  	   	
</P>
