<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded  
heavily Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange, Nasdaq Stock 
Market, and American Stock Exchange. 

</P>
<P>
                               *NYSE    	
</P>
<P>
	Sprint, down 2 at 58 7/8  
</P>
<P>
	Sprint PCS, down 4 11/16 at 74  
</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom (Nasdaq), down 3 11/16 at 67 15/16  
</P>
<P>
	Forging the largest corporate takeover in history, MCI WorldCom  
agreed to pay $76 per share in stock, or about $115 billion 
overall, to acquire long-distance rival Sprint. Each share of the 
Sprint PCS wireless business will be swapped for one share of the 
new WorldCom PCS and 0.1547 of an MCI WorldCom share. 

</P>
<P>
	American Express, up 3 1/8 at 140 11/16  
</P>
<P>
	The New York-based company announced plans to launch a new  
brokerage unit with online trading and access to financial advisers 
and planners. 

</P>
<P>
	Halliburton, down 5 1/4 at 34 1/2  
</P>
<P>
	The Dallas-based provider of oil field services agreed to sell  
its stake in two joint ventures to Ingersoll-Rand for $1.1 billion 
in cash. Halliburton said the ventures are causing a drag on 
earnings and warned it will post disappointing third-quarter 
results. 

</P>
<P>
	MCN Energy Group, up 5 7/8 at 23 9/16  
</P>
<P>
	DTE Energy agreed to acquire MCN, the parent of Michigan  
Consolidated Gas, for cash and stock worth $28.50 a share, or $2.6 
billion. DTE, parent of electricity provider Detroit Edison, will 
also assume about $2 billion of MCN debt. 

</P>
<P>
                              *NASDAQ   	
</P>
<P>
	Concur Technologies, down 20 1/16 at 12 13/16  
</P>
<P>
	The provider of electronic commerce services warned it will post  
disappointing revenues for its fourth quarter ended Sept. 30. 
Concur, based in Redmond, Wash., blamed a delay in closing certain 
business by the quarter's end. 

</P>
<P>
	Gemstar International Group, down 6 13/16 at 69 3/8  
</P>
<P>
	The pioneer in onscreen TV program schedules agreed to acquire  
TV Guide for $8.6 billion in stock. The deal will end 
patent-infringement lawsuits between the companies over some of 
their interactive TV listings technology. Gemstar is based in 
Pasadena, Calif., while TV Guide is based in Tulsa, Okla. 

</P>
<P>
	Vivid Technologies, up 1 7/8 at 5 7/16  
</P>
<P>
	EG&AMP;G Inc. is buying the supplier of explosive detection systems  
in a $62.5 million deal. EG&AMP;G will swap one of its shares for every 
6.2 shares of Vivid, which is based in Woburn, Mass. 

</P>
<P>
	ShowCase, down 5 1/2 at 4  
</P>
<P>
	The maker of business computer systems for IBM AS/400 customers  
warned late Monday it will post an unexpected loss for its second 
quarter ended Sept. 30. ShowCase, based in Rochester, Minn., blamed 
disappointing revenue from Asia, low volume from IBM, and deferral 
of purchase decisions. 




  	   	
</P>
