<HEADLINE> Firefighters Surround Calif. Blazes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMPO, Calif. (AP) -- Firefighters were close to containing two  
southern California wildfires today, but huge fires elsewhere in 
the state remained out of control. 
</P>
<P>
	A 3,300-acre blaze near Campo, east of San Diego, was about 70  
percent surrounded by fire lines and expected to be completely 
surrounded tonight, said Chris Hess, a fire captain with the U.S. 
Forest Service. 
</P>
<P>
	Northeast of San Diego, airplanes and helicopters were used to  
fight a 6,000-acre fire that started on the La Jolla Indian 
Reservation and spread into Cleveland National Forest. Crews 
expected to have it fully contained by Wednesday evening, Hess 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Near California's central coast, firefighters had reopened a  
stretch of Highway 1 that was closed by two fires totaling 76,000 
acres near Big Sur. Both fires, started by lightning on Sept. 8, 
were 50 percent contained. About $44 million has been spent 
fighting them. 
</P>
<P>
	Farther north, fires in the Trinity Alps Wilderness had covered  
96,000 acres but were 42 percent contained. A 51,000-acre blaze in 
Tehama County, near Red Bluff, was 70 percent contained. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
