<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Leak Reported at S.Korea Nuke Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Radioactive water leaked inside a  
South Korean nuclear power plant, exposing at least 22 people to 
radiation, the government said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident occurred at 7 p.m. Monday during repair work on a  
cooling water pump at Wolsung nuclear power plant, the science and 
technology ministry said in a statement. About 12 gallons of 
so-called ``heavy water'' leaked, the ministry said. 
</P>
<P>
	It said the radioactive water was contained inside the plant.  
</P>
<P>
	``It did not leak outside of the building. It did not affect the  
environment,'' the ministry said in the statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Those who were exposed to the radiation included employees of  
Korea Electric Power Corp., which runs one of the three nuclear 
power plants in Wolsung. The one where the accident happened 
started commercial operations on July 1, 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first reported leak of radioactive material at a  
plant in South Korea, where the first nuclear plant was built in 
1978. The northeast Asian nation has 14 nuclear power plants which 
provide about 40 percent of its electricity. 
</P>
<P>
	The incident followed Japan's worst nuclear accident last week  
at a uranium-processing plant in Tokaimura, a town 70 miles 
northeast of Tokyo. The accident Thursday was caused when two 
workers skipped key security steps while mixing nuclear fuel. 
</P>
<P>
	The reaction that followed exposed at least 49 people to  
radiation, closed down Tokaimura and heightened fears about the 
safety of Japan's nuclear plants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
