<DOCNO> APW19991005.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-05 06:20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Two Former ADM Execs Sent to Jail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DECATUR, Ill. (AP) -- With the rejection of their latest appeals,  
two former executives of Archer Daniels Midland Co. have been 
ordered to report to federal prisons. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael D. Andreas, 50, and Terrance S. Wilson, 61, were  
convicted last year of fixing prices and were scheduled to report 
to their respective prisons today to begin serving their two-year 
sentences. 
</P>
<P>
	Andreas was originally directed to report to Greenville, Ill.,  
less than 100 miles southeast of Decatur, while Wilson was assigned 
to a prison in Oxford, Wis. 
</P>
<P>
	Those locations were recommended by a federal judge, but the  
men's final destinations will not be made public by the Federal 
Bureau of Prisons until each man has reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott Wilson, a spokesman for the Bureau of Prisons in  
Washington, D.C., said the odds are that Greenville and Oxford are 
the final locations. 
</P>
<P>
	``A judge's recommendation may or may not be followed. It  
usually is, but I can count thousands of cases where there has been 
a change,'' Wilson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for both men had filed numerous motions and appeals  
that delayed the eventual prison time since their convictions by a 
federal jury in August 1998. Their last effort, filed jointly, was 
denied by the U.S. Court of Appeals Seventh Circuit on Sept. 23. 
</P>
<P>
	Andreas is on leave as ADM's executive vice president. Wilson,  
who is retired, was the head of ADM's corn division. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Blanche M. Manning sentenced Andreas and  
Wilson, along with FBI informer Mark E. Whitacre, on July 9. 
Whitacre, the former head of ADM's BioProducts Division, is already 
in prison on a previous conviction of embezzling $9 million from 
the company. 
</P>
<P>
	Andreas, Wilson and Whitacre were convicted in one of the  
nation's biggest federal antitrust cases ever. The government said 
they had led ADM into a global conspiracy to set prices and divide 
up competition in sales of citric acid and lysine, which is a 
protein component of hog and chicken feed. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991005.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-05 00:00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Suggests His Own Death Sentence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VISTA, Calif. (AP) -- In a calm, deliberate voice, Brandon Wilson  
said he felt no remorse for fatally slashing the throat of a 
third-grade boy in a beach restroom last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would do it again in a second if I had the chance,'' Wilson  
told jurors Monday as the boy's mother, Sharon Cecchi, gasped from 
her courtroom seat. 
</P>
<P>
	``Execute me,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The 21-year old drifter spoke against the advice of his lawyer  
as jurors began hearing evidence to help decide between 
recommending a sentence of life in prison without parole or 
execution. Testimony was to resume today. 
</P>
<P>
	``My whole purpose in life is to help destroy your society,''  
Wilson told the panel. ``You people are here as representatives of 
that society and as such you should do everything in your power to 
rid the world of me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson admitted he smiled at 9-year-old Matthew Cecchi and  
followed him into the restroom at Oceanside, north of San Diego, in 
November. Then he came up behind the boy as he stood at the urinal. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson said he then pulled back the boy's head, slashed his  
throat and stabbed him five times in the back. Wilson fled the 
bathroom, leaving Matthew to bleed to death as his aunt waited 
outside. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson, from St. Croix Falls, Wis., claimed he was insane at the  
time, driven by voices from God to kill and hallucinogenic drugs. 
Jurors deliberated less than six hours last week before rejecting 
the claim. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury Monday heard more than two hours of prosecution  
testimony that included tearful recollections of Matthew by his 
mother, an uncle and the boy's third-grade teacher. 
</P>
<P>
	Two jurors wept as the teacher, Deborah Peck of Stanford Avenue  
School, described how she tried to explain the boy's murder to his 
classmates. 
</P>
<P>
	``Third-graders always ask why and that was a question I had no  
answer for,'' said Peck, who called Matthew a straight-A student 
and an extraordinary boy. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Cecchi recalled trying to comfort her son and to give him  
CPR as he lay bleeding. ``I put my hand on his hair and told him, 
`Hang in there baby. I love you,''' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	She said life has been difficult without her eldest son,  
especially holidays. Her 4-year-old son wears Matthew's shirts as a 
way to feel closer to his older brother. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was everything to us,'' she said. ``He was a very special  
boy.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
