<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CBS Plans Majority Web Co. Stake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- CBS Corp. is buying its first majority stake in  
a Web destination in a deal that intensifies the company's already 
aggressive foray into the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	The company agreed to pay an undisclosed amount of cash for CTC  
Bulldog Inc., an Irvington, N.Y. venture formed earlier this year 
that has yet to unveil its Internet site, a source familiar with 
the transaction said yesterday. CBS also will run ads promoting the 
site, said the source, speaking on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	An announcement was planned in New York today. Spokespeople from  
CBS and CTC Bulldog declined to comment on the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	CTC Bulldog's Web site is ready to be launched and will use  
promotions such as prizes to try to draw Internet viewers, the 
source said. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS has been greatly expanding its Web strategy and currently  
holds minority stakes in 11 Web sites, including SportsLine USA and 
financial news provider MarketWatch.com, which sold stock to the 
public this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	But CBS has yet to buy a majority stake. While some of its  
recent investments have paid off handsomely, CBS currently has no 
single Web destination to help guide Internet surfers to other 
holdings. In contrast, NBC has Web portal Snap.com and ABC created 
Go.com to organize links to its Web properties. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked whether CBS would use its latest Web holding to unify its  
disparate properties, the source would only say: ``This is the 
beginning of what they're doing. It's their entrance.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
