<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7:45 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Oct. 5, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	FCC Warns on MCI WorldCom-Sprint  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- MCI WorldCom's $115 billion deal to take over  
Sprint met with quick resistance today from federal regulators. 
Chairman William E. Kennard of the Federal Communications 
Commission said the nation's second- and third-largest 
long-distance telephone companies ``will bear a heavy burden to 
show how consumers would be better off'' after their merger. But 
MCI WorldCom and Sprint insisted the richest corporate buyout ever 
would strengthen competition. 

</P>
<P>
	Charges Filed in Bank of NY Probe  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) --Three individuals and three companies have been  
charged with illegally funneling $7 billion from Russia through 
accounts at the Bank of New York in what investigators 
investigators believe to be one of the largest cases of money 
laundering in the United States. Peter Berlin, Lucy Edwards -- a 
former vice president at the bank -- and Aleksey Volkov as well as 
Benex International Co. Inc., Becs International L.L.C. and 
Torfinex Corp. were named as defendents. 

</P>
<P>
	Nuke Test Ban Faces Opposition  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate's top Democrat on foreign affairs  
issues said he told President Clinton today the votes aren't there 
to ratify an international ban on nuclear testing. Sen. Joseph 
Biden, D-Del., said that, while all 45 Senate Democrats are 
prepared to support the treaty next Tuesday when a vote is 
scheduled, Republican support appears to be disappearing. The White 
House indicated that Clinton would continue to fight for the Senate 
to ratify the treaty. 

</P>
<P>
	London Trains Crash, Killing 26  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Two London commuter trains smashed into each other  
during rush hour today, killing 26 passengers and injuring 160 on 
the same rail line as another fatal crash two years ago. Ambulance 
and fire crews, police and rail workers swarmed around the 
overturned, mangled rail cars for hours, locating and freeing 
survivors in the smoldering wreckage near the Ladbroke Grove 
residential area in west London. It was Britain's worst train 
accident in more than a decade. 

</P>
<P>
	South Korea Nuclear Plant Leaks  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Radioactive water leaked inside a  
South Korean nuclear power plant during repair work, exposing 22 
workers to small amounts of radiation, the government said. It said 
the radioactive water was contained inside the plant and did not 
escape into the environment. About 12 gallons of so-called ``heavy 
water'' was leaked during the accident last night at a nuclear 
plant in Wolsung, 190 miles southeast of the capital Seoul, the 
Science and Technology Ministry said in a statement. 

</P>
<P>
	Annan Says UN Needs Reform  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Secretary-General Kofi Annan said today  
the U.N. still has too many administrators and rules, and too 
little money. Member countries, primarily the United States, owed 
the United Nations more than $2 billion, he said. Unpaid dues and 
bureaucratic delays have made it virtually impossible for the U.N. 
to respond quickly to crises like those in Kosovo and East Timor, 
he said. 

</P>
<P>
	Infant Deaths Hold Steady  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's infant death rate held steady in  
1998 after dropping for almost four decades. Researchers were at a 
loss for explanations and uncertain whether last year's figures 
represent a one-year glitch or an end to decades of progress. The 
portion of babies who died before their first birthday in 1997 was 
7.2 deaths for every 1,000 live births. It did not change in 1998. 
At least 24 other counties have lower rates than the United States. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends 0.64 Lower at 10,400.59  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell today in volatile trading after the  
Federal Reserve decided against raising interest rates again but 
left open the possibility of a third rate hike later this year. The 
Dow industrials closed 0.64 lower at 10,400.59. On the NYSE, losers 
led gainers 1,794-1,241. The Nasdaq rose 3.70 to 2,799.67. 

</P>
<P>
	Astros Pound Braves  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Daryle Ward's leadoff homer against Greg Maddux  
in the sixth inning broke a 1-1 tie and helped the Houston Astros 
to a 6-1 victory today vs. the Atlanta Braves in Game 1 of their NL 
division series. The Astros got four runs in the ninth, topped by 
Ken Caminiti's three-run homer. Houston starter Shane Reynolds, who 
went six innings, and three Astros relievers held the Braves to 
seven hits. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER  



  	   	
</P>
