<HEADLINE> WorldCom Boss a Modest Billionaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLINTON, Miss. (AP) -- In this town where roads are made of  
brick, cars are left unlocked and college kids dart in and out of 
coffee shops, Bernard J. Ebbers is everywhere. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-4 native of Edmonton, Alberta, came here in the late  
1960s to play basketball for Mississippi College, a private school 
with more than 3,600 students. Today, Clinton is the 58-year-old 
billionaire's home and the center of his life's work -- MCI WorldCom 
Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	To townspeople, he is Bernie Ebbers, not only the boss to 900  
MCI WorldCom employees, but also the vice chairman of the 
Mississippi College board of trustees. 
</P>
<P>
	``He comes to ball games,'' said Howell W. Todd, Mississippi  
College president. ``He's very loyal to this institution. He's very 
keen on our philosophy and mission, and in ensuring that we carry 
out that mission.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He is also quiet and faithful and once canceled a Saturday night  
business function with the Metro Jackson Chamber of Commerce so he 
could finish preparing the lesson for Sunday school the next 
morning. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know he is a deeply spiritual man; his faith is extremely  
important to him, and his values,'' said Todd. 
</P>
<P>
	It might be faith that helped prompt Ebbers, whose early jobs  
included that of basketball coach and small-chain motel owner, to 
invest in a tiny long-distance company called Long Distance 
Discount Services, even though he knew little about the phone 
business. That was in 1983, just before AT&AMP;T was dismembered. 
</P>
<P>
	He turned that company, an idea drawn up in a Hattiesburg coffee  
shop, into the nation's second-largest telecommunications company 
with net income last year of $2.6 billion and an overall value 
around $117.8 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	LDDS has been involved in 60 mergers since it was born. Before  
Tuesday, Ebbers' biggest deal was when his company, renamed 
WorldCom, bought MCI Communications. Now, he's maneuvered MCI 
Worldcom to take over Sprint Corp., in a $115 billion deal that is 
the largest corporate acquisition in history. 
</P>
<P>
	No one was surprised about the latest announcement; analysts had  
been saying MCI WorldCom needed Sprint for its wireless segment. 
</P>
<P>
	And Ebbers realized that, too, his friends say.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's safe to say that Bernie is always a step or two  
ahead of the rest of us,'' said Duane O'Neill, president of the 
Metro Jackson Chamber of Commerce. ``He's a true visionary in that 
he makes it happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ebbers, a former cowboy and soybean rancher, is credited with  
methodically making his company grow and remain profitable and 
competitive in an era of corporate mergers that has set the entire 
industry on its ear. 
</P>
<P>
	None of which surprises Todd, who has known Ebbers for five  
years. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is very unassuming; doesn't want to draw a lot of attention  
to himself,'' says Todd. ``But beware because underneath all that 
laid-back attitude is a steel-trap mind and one of the sharpest, 
shrewdest individuals I've ever known. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can look at the company and see that.''  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991005.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-05 15:00:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Broncos Hope Loville Can Replace TD </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Don't be misled by the silver stud piercing  
through Derek Loville's right nostril or the nipple ring under his 
shirt. He is not the anti-Terrell. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, the man who will replace MVP running back Terrell Davis  
does not crave attention and may be one of the most disciplined 
members of the Denver Broncos' backfield. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm in the weight room every day,'' Loville said. ``I've put  
in work just like the next man. I think I work harder than a lot of 
people. ... I'm looking forward to the opportunity to helping my 
team get a win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Davis out for the season with two torn ligaments and  
cartilage damage in his right knee, Loville will be called upon to 
handle the bulk of the rushing duties. 
</P>
<P>
	While no one can be expected to put up Terrellian numbers,  
Loville has spent the last three years as Davis' understudy, 
capably filling in when needed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Derek's going to get the job done,'' offensive lineman Tony  
Jones said. ``I'm glad he's had the reps he's had with us. We feel 
comfortable with him. We've just got to bear down more and block 
better and find a way to get a win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even with Davis healthy for the first three games, the Broncos  
(0-4) have struggled offensively averaging just 90.5 yards per game 
on the ground and 274 overall. Those numbers rank 20th and 26th, 
respectively, in the NFL. 
</P>
<P>
	There's no telling what the statistics will look like with  
Loville as the primary running back, but he carries a confidence 
borne from nine seasons in the NFL. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm always optimistic. That's me. That's my demeanor,''  
Loville said. ``This is my ninth year. I'm fortunate. Running backs 
are only supposed to play for, what, 3 1/2 years? I'm playing on 
borrowed time and I'm having fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Loville is no stranger to replacing a top-flight running back.  
In 1995, he waded into starting role with San Francisco after Ricky 
Watters left the 49ers to sign a lucrative free agent contract with 
Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	That season turned out to be Loville's best as he ran for  
career-high 723 yards and 10 touchdowns and caught 87 passes for 
662 yards and two scores. 
</P>
<P>
	``Derek is an experienced football player and he understands the  
game,'' Broncos coach Mike Shanahan said. ``He's a great special 
teams player. He's been a tremendous worker. He's been a starter in 
the NFL, so he does bring that experience and that drive that you 
look for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Loville won't be alone in trying to replace Davis, who refers to  
the Denver running backs as No Limit Soldiers. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to Loville, the corps will include rookie Olandis  
Gary and second-year player John Avery, who came to the Broncos in 
a trade that sent wide receiver Marcus Nash to Miami two weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're tight,'' Loville said. ``We're a tight group because we  
take pride in what we do and we pull for one another. There's no 
animosity. There's no jealousy. We want all of to do good, whether 
it's on special teams or offense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Whether being close-knit leads to success remains to be seen.  
</P>
<P>
	The Atlanta Falcons are 0-3 since losing star running back Jamal  
Anderson to a torn knee ligament. Anderson's replacement, Byron 
Hanspard, has run for 155 yards on 53 carries -- an average of less 
than 3 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe in our guys,'' Shanahan said. ``I really believe our  
guys will step up. It's not going to be easy. It's going to have to 
be a heck of a commitment by everybody.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
