<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thomas J. Bienemann    	
</P>
<P>
	KENOSHA, Wis. (AP) -- Thomas J. Bienemann, who played defensive  
end for the Chicago Cardinals of the National Football League from 
1951-56 and later headed up the underwear manufacturer Jockey 
International, died Tuesday of leukemia at the age of 71. 
</P>
<P>
	After his football career, Bienemann joined Jockey International  
in Kenosha as a sales trainee. In December 1960, he became vice 
president of sales for the eastern region, working out of the 
Empire State Building. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten years later, he joined Hanes Corp. and worked as vice  
president for sales and marketing until 1975, when he joined 
Warnaco Northwest, which makes Speedo and other sportswear 
products. 
</P>
<P>
	He retired but later returned to Jockey International in 1993 as  
managing director and chief operating officer, overseeing cuts of 
about 920 jobs from the 5,000-employee company. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Jerald C. Brauer    	
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Jerald C. Brauer, former dean of the University  
of Chicago's Divinity School, died Sept. 26 of leukemia at his 
home. He was 78. 
</P>
<P>
	Brauer was known for his efforts to diversify the predominantly  
Protestant school. 
</P>
<P>
	He has been credited with helping the university become one of  
the nation's leading theological centers, representing many faiths. 
</P>
<P>
	During his tenures as dean of the university's federated  
theological faculty from 1955 to 1960 and of the Divinity School 
from 1960 to 1970, Brauer was known for recruiting top theological 
scholars. 

</P>
<P>
 *Nigel Broakes    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Sir Nigel Broakes, a prominent property developer  
whose holdings included London's Ritz Hotel and the Cunard shipping 
line, has died. He was 65. 
</P>
<P>
	Broakes, who headed the property and construction conglomerate  
Trafalgar House died Sept. 28 after a short illness, news reports 
said Tuesday. He was known as the figurehead behind the successful 
redevelopment of the London Docklands area. 
</P>
<P>
	Born in Wakefield in the English Midlands, Broakes began his  
career as an insurance underwriter, but soon became interested in 
property development. He became a millionaire in his 20s. 
</P>
<P>
	He assumed the chairmanship of Trafalgar House at 35,  
accumulating some of the country's best-known assets over the next 
decade, among them Cunard and the Ritz. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1977, Broakes made a successful bid for the troubled  
Beaverbrook empire, which owned the Daily Express, the Sunday 
Express and the Evening Standard newspapers. 
</P>
<P>
	His development of the London Docklands led to a knighthood in  
1984. 
</P>
<P>
	Broakes is survived by two sons and a daughter. His wife, Joyce  
Horne, whom he married in 1956, died in 1993. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Martin S. Davis    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Martin S. Davis, who reshaped the sprawling Gulf  
&AMP; Western conglomerate into the publishing and entertainment 
powerhouse called Paramount Communications before presiding over 
its hotly contested sale to Viacom Inc., has died. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis died of a heart attack Monday evening, family spokesman  
Jerry Sherman said Tuesday. Davis was 72. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis, who had been a partner in recent years in a private  
investment firm whose holdings include the maker of Lionel trains, 
was known for a tough and aggressive style. But he described 
himself as an ``employee-captain'' whose job was to get the best 
return possible on shareholder's investments. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1983, Davis was selected as chief executive of G&AMP;W after its  
longtime boss Charles Bluhdorn died. The company at the time was a 
classic diversified conglomerate with assets ranging from cigars 
and agricultural products to financial services, industrial 
products, metals, chemicals and motion pictures. 
</P>
<P>
	But Davis felt conglomerates were no longer in vogue and that he  
could get better returns by selling assets. He began a sweeping 
corporate restructuring, selling about 150 busineses with revenues 
amounting to $6 billion between 1983 and 1989 and liquidating a 
$900 million investment portfolio. 
</P>
<P>
	The company focused on its publishing and entertainment  
operations which included Simon &AMP; Schuster, Prentice Hall, Madison 
Square Garden, TV stations and Paramount Pictures. It changed its 
name to Paramount Communications in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	In September 1993, Davis and Paramount agreed to sell Paramount  
to Sumner Redstone's Viacom, the owner of the MTV and the Showtime 
pay TV service, for about $8.2 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	But the deal provoked a bidding battle war led by former  
Paramount and Fox executive Barry Diller and involving many of the 
biggest names in the media and entertainment businesses. Davis was 
forced to abandon his deal with Viacom and conduct an auction. 
Viacom eventually prevailed, although the price was about $2 
billion more than the initial agreement. 

</P>
<P>
                         	 *Leonard Shoen    	
</P>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Leonard Shoen, founder of U-Haul International  
Inc., the nation's largest truck rental company, died in a traffic 
accident Monday. He was 83. 
</P>
<P>
	U-Haul spokeswoman Johna Burke confirmed the fatal accident, but  
Las Vegas police refused to immediately release details of the 
crash Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Shoen founded Phoenix-based U-Haul in 1945 and built it into the  
most recognized self-moving company in the nation with its 
signature orange and white trucks. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Francis Turner    	
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Francis Turner, a one-time federal highway  
administrator who advised President Eisenhower on the national 
interstate system and was considered its chief architect, died 
Saturday. He was 90 and had cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Turner, a highway engineer in Arkansas who did road surveys that  
built support for a system of superhighways, started working for 
the federal Bureau of Roads in 1929. In World War II, he worked as 
an engineer in Alaska to help build the Alaska Highway, and after 
the war he coordinated the rebuilding of damaged roads in the 
Philippines. 
</P>
<P>
	Eisenhower named Turner executive secretary of the highway  
advisory committee in 1954, which led to recommendations for a 
system of interstate and defense-oriented highways that were 
financed by both state and federal governments. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Edwin Warfield III    	
</P>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Edwin Warfield III, former chairman and chief  
executive officer of The Daily Record Co. and a former state 
legislator, died Monday at the age of 75. 
</P>
<P>
	Warfield represented Howard County in the state House of  
Delegates from 1963 to 1970 and resigned the office in 1970 after 
he was appointed adjutant general of the Maryland National Guard. 
</P>
<P>
	He commanded National Guard troops in the early 1970s during  
student disturbances at the University of Maryland's College Park 
campus following the bombing of Cambodia by U.S. aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	A World War II pilot, he was once shot down while strafing a  
Japanese airfield and had to parachute into the Pacific Ocean, 
where he spent four days in a raft before being rescued by a U.S. 
submarine. 
</P>
<P>
	Warfield is survived by his wife, Ellen; two sons; two  
daughters; a stepdaughter; two sisters; and nine grandchildren. 

