<P>
                          *Bernard Buffet    	
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Bernard Buffet, one of France's major contemporary  
painters, killed himself Monday at his home in southern France, 
police said. He was 71. 
</P>
<P>
	Buffet was found dead by his wife with a plastic bag over his  
head, police sources said, speaking on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Gallery owner Maurice Garnier, who had worked with Buffet for 51  
years, said the artist was suffering from Parkinson's disease and 
had been unable to work for some time. 
</P>
<P>
	Buffet, a millionaire who basked in fame since he was 20, was an  
outspoken advocate of figurative painting at a time when 
abstraction was the rage. He remained faithful to the distinctive, 
black vertical brushstroke he used to recreate emaciated faces, 
imperial Russian palaces and sad-faced clowns. 
</P>
<P>
	Buffet was roundly ignored by the French art establishment. The  
Georges Pompidou Center, France's most prestigious collection of 
modern and contemporary art, never purchased any of his work. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Buffet was a superstar abroad, His work was the subject  
of two separate museums in Japan, one featuring more than 600 of 
his works. 

</P>
<P>
                            *J. John Fox    	
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- J. John Fox, a retired judge and one of the  
leaders in the growth and development of the University of 
Massachusetts, died Monday. He was 95. 
</P>
<P>
	Fox is widely considered the father of the University of  
Massachusetts Medical School in Worcester. 
</P>
<P>
	He was named to the Norfolk Probate Court in 1960 by Gov. Foster  
Furcolo after serving in the Boston Municipal Bench as an associate 
justice for eight years. He retired from the bench in 1973. 
</P>
<P>
	A close confidant to Democratic governors Paul Dever, Endicott  
Peabody and Furcolo, he joined House Speaker David Bartley in 1974 
in filing a bill that provided a one-year mandatory prison sentence 
for people convicted of illegally carrying a gun. The measure was 
known as the Bartley-Fox bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Fox served in the U.S. Navy during World War II, rising to the  
rank of lieutenant commander in navel intelligence. He was awarded 
the Bronze Star for his work in the invasion of the Marshall 
Islands and the Marianas. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Bill Hustead    	
</P>
<P>
	PIERRE, S.D. (AP) -- Bill Hustead, who helped make Wall Drug a  
well-known tourist stop, died Monday. He was 72. 
</P>
<P>
	Hustead, who suffered from Lou Gehrig's disease, served as  
president of the internationally known business from 1972-97. His 
father, Ted E. Hustead, founded the store in 1931. He died Jan. 12 
at age 96. 
</P>
<P>
	The store, located in Wall on a major route between the Black  
Hills and Badlands, first started drawing customers by offering 
free ice water and 5-cent coffee. 
</P>
<P>
	The store has grown from the original 24-foot by 60-foot wooden  
building into an emporium of 77,000 square feet that features 
souvenirs, western art, clothing, a chapel, jewelry, veterinary 
supplies and more. Buffalo burgers and homemade doughnuts are 
especially popular food items. Coffee is still a nickel. 

</P>
