<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Drift Lower / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices were lower in  
early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures fell as prices continue to be pressured by large  
supplies and a lack of new export business. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures were lower as the market reacted to news the  
harvesting of the crop continues without being hampered by adverse 
weather. The quiet export market also is pulling corn lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean futures prices were lower on indications the soybean  
crop this year could reach 2.75 million bushels. 
</P>
<P>
	National Weather Service forecasts call for mostly dry  
conditions in the soybean belt over the next six to 10 days. That 
is expected to help the harvest, which the U.S. Agriculture 
Department reports is 32 percent completed as of Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	In early trading, December wheat was 1 1/4 cents lower at $2.67 1/2 a  
bushel; December corn was a 1/4 cent lower at $2.04 a bushel; 
December oats were a 1/2 cent lower at $1.11 1/2 a bushel; November 
soybeans were 1 1/4 cents lower at $4.82 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Cattle and hog futures prices were lower in early trading today  
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	October live cattle were .22 cent lower at 68.95 cents a pound;  
October feeder cattle were .50 cent lower at 81.50 cents a pound; 
October lean hogs were 1.30 cents lower at 48.90 cents a pound; 
February pork bellies were 1.27 cents lower at 62.50 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
