<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Camp Victims Threaten To End Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Survivors of Nazi labor camps threatened today  
to walk out on negotiations with German companies, calling the 
companies' compensation offers ``peanuts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference a day before reopening of negotiations,  
slave labor victims and their attorneys urged the companies to 
finish the talks quickly and offer ``meaningful compensation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If they don't step up to the plate and start  
negotiating...with real money that is representative of their 
ability to pay, we are going to walk away from these meetings,'' 
said attorney Mel Weiss. 
</P>
<P>
	He said that in months of negotiations the German companies have  
never given a specific figure of how much money they would pay for 
an estimated 2.4 million persons forced to work in German industry 
during World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	But Weiss said attorneys have relied on newspaper reports and  
rumors for an idea of what the companies might offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Quoting such a report in Tuesday's edition of the Washington  
Post, he said compensation of $200 per slave labor survivor is 
being contemplated and he called that offer a ``paltry amount'' and 
``a disgrace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Post reported that lawyers for the German companies would go  
into meetings with officials from the U.S. and other governments 
starting Wednesday offering $3.8 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Weiss declined to say how much survivors are demanding but said  
it was ``far in excess'' of the $20 billion that has been reported 
elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	A State Department official said Monday it was premature to  
comment on any anticipated offers. 
</P>
<P>
	The meetings will bring together representatives from countries  
where former slave laborers live such as Poland, Russia, Ukraine 
and Israel as well as leaders of Jewish groups and plaintiffs' 
lawyers. 
</P>
<P>
	German participants include top government officials and  
executives from leading German companies. 
</P>
<P>
	One Jewish group, B'nai B'Rith International, took out a full  
page ad in the New York Times that named Bayer, a German 
pharmaceutical company, accusing it of ``human experiments and 
slave labor'' during World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	The ad said ``Bayer executives explicitly directed Nazi doctors  
to perform specific experiments with their products.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas Reinert, a spokesman at Bayer headquarters in Leverkusen,  
Germany, said Bayer was absorbed during the Nazi era into the IG 
Farben pharmaceutical and chemical conglomerate. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no connection between (Nazi doctor Joseph) Mengele  
and the Bayer company,'' Reinard said. ``We know of no evidence 
that he ever worked for IG Farben.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the wider issue of Bayer's role in the Third Reich, including  
slave labor, Reinert said: 
</P>
<P>
	``Bayer rejects legal responsibility for whatever may have  
happened under the Nazi dictatorship and at IG Farben. However, 
Bayer is aware of a humanitarian responsibility and therefore is 
taking part in negotiations aimed at creating a foundation for the 
victims.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
