<HEADLINE> Waco Evidence Granted to Counsel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WACO, Texas (AP) -- A federal judge on Tuesday allowed Special  
Counsel John Danforth access to the trove of documents being shared 
by the government and plaintiffs' attorneys in the Branch 
Davidians' civil suit. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Walter Smith broadened the protective order  
governing the evidence to let Danforth see deposition testimony, 
exhibits and other information gathered by both sides in the 
lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney General Janet Reno appointed Danforth, a former  
Republican senator from Missouri, to investigate whether there was 
a cover-up or other wrongdoing in the government's handling of the 
51-day Branch Davidian siege, which ended in a fire at the sect's 
compound in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Branch Davidian leader David Koresh and about 80 followers died.  
Survivors of the siege and relatives of the dead have filed a 
wrongful death lawsuit, challenging the government's assertion that 
the Davidians set the fire. 
</P>
<P>
	Trial was to begin this month, but Smith delayed it to give  
federal officials time to produce evidence he has requested. A new 
date has not been set. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
