<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sales Strong for Reagan 'Memoir' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Sales remain strong days after the publication  
of ``Dutch: A Memoir of Ronald Reagan,'' but reviews of Edmund 
Morris' controversial book have turned increasingly sour. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's flying off the shelves,'' Barnes &AMP; Noble spokeswoman Mary  
Ellen Keating said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dutch'' has dropped from No. 4 to No. 20 on Amazon.com's  
best-seller list, but Internet purchases comprise only 2 percent of 
the market, according to the Book Industry Study Group. In chain 
bookstores, which account for 25 percent of sales, Morris' 
``memoir'' is still a big favorite. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sales have been very good and we expect the book to stay  
strong through the holidays,'' said Ann Binkley, a spokeswoman for 
Borders Books &AMP; Music. 
</P>
<P>
	Random House paid a reported $3 million to Morris, winner of the  
Pulitzer Prize for his biography of Theodore Roosevelt, and gave 
``Dutch'' a first printing of more than 300,000. 
</P>
<P>
	But Morris has been attacked by critics for inserting himself  
into the book as a fictional character and by Reagan supporters for 
writing that the president was an ``apparent airhead'' and 
``possessed of no inner warmth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since receiving favorable reviews last week from The New York  
Times and USA Today, ``Dutch'' has been panned several times. 
Joseph Ellis, author of an award-winning biography of Thomas 
Jefferson, called Morris' book ``a scandal and a tragedy.'' 
Reviewing for The Washington Post, Ellis wrote that ``editorial 
integrity has lost another battle to the proverbial bottom line.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reagan historian Lou Cannon, reviewing ``Dutch'' for the Los  
Angeles Times, criticized Morris' tendency ``to rework familiar 
material and present it as original.'' Stanley I. Kutler, author of 
``The Wars of Watergate,'' complained in the Chicago Tribune that 
Morris' ``intrusiveness is self-indulgent, irrelevant and, most of 
all, confusing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A notable review came Saturday from The New York Times, in which  
daily book critic Michiko Kakutani contradicted the positive 
assessment given by colleague Christopher Lehmann-Haupt earlier in 
the week. Kakutani described ``Dutch'' as a ``cloying, egocentric 
novel'' and accused Morris of wasting ``a rare opportunity to 
chronicle a sitting president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Presidential biographer Roger Morris, no relation to Edmund  
Morris, said Tuesday that he found the use of a fictional narrator 
``juvenile'' and that the author of ``Dutch'' had let down his 
readers. 
</P>
<P>
	``My quarrel with the book is its shallowness as history. We  
depend on our biographers, especially our presidential biographers, 
to give us the larger historical context,'' said Morris, author of 
works on Presidents Clinton and Nixon. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt betrayed. I might have expected this from the dozens of  
lightweights out there who write puff stuff, but Edmund Morris is 
not in that category. He's earned the right to be taken 
seriously.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
