<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Health Care Problems Said Y2K Risk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Medicare is warning doctors, hospitals and  
other health-care providers about possible financial consequences 
if the Y2K computer bug catches them unprepared. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they can't get their bills to us, they just won't get  
paid,'' Dr. Robert A. Berenson, director of Medicare's center for 
health plans and providers, said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors, hospitals and others are barred by law from upfront  
billing of the 39 million elderly and disabled Americans covered by 
Medicare for medical services. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, providers finding they must switch from filing electronic  
Medicare claims to paper claims because they are unprepared will 
have to wait longer for payment. By law, Medicare must pay bills 
submitted electronically within 14 days, but has 27 days to process 
old-fashioned paper invoices. 
</P>
<P>
	The Medicare warning was prompted by new surveys of health-care  
providers that government investigators say suggest many aren't 
ready for the so-called Year 2000 computer problem. That is the 
possibility that when the clock turns to midnight New Year's Eve, 
some older computers, built to recognize only the last two numbers 
in a year number, may mistake the 2000 for 1900 and malfunction or 
shut down. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are some significant gaps that have to be bridged yet,''  
George Grob, the Health and Human Services Department's deputy 
inspector general, said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The inspector general mailed surveys June 30 to 5,000 providers  
of health care for elderly and disabled Americans covered by 
Medicare, including doctors, hospitals, nursing homes, home-care 
agencies and medical equipment suppliers. 
</P>
<P>
	Fewer than half of the 1,924 caregivers responding said all of  
their biomedical equipment, such as X-ray machines and respirators, 
is Y2K ready. About two-thirds said their billing and 
record-keeping systems are ready. 
</P>
<P>
	One-third said, however, they had not tested information  
exchanges with vendors or bill-processing contractors. 
</P>
<P>
	``We find a great lack of testing, and, in the computer world in  
particular, if you haven't tested, you don't know,'' Grob said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate IG survey of 161 HMOs participating in Medicare,  
85 percent said they are prepared for Y2K. 
</P>
<P>
	The health department, the Clinton administration's Y2K task  
force and congressional auditors previously have raised alarms that 
the medical industry may not be doing enough to address the 
computer glitch. 
</P>
<P>
	Industry groups such as the American Hospital Association insist  
providers are making progress and will be ready. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991005.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-05 21:50:08 </DATE_TIME>
