<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Key Dates in MCI, Sprint History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	--1899: Brown Telephone Co., founded in Abilene, Kan.; later  
known as Sprint. 
</P>
<P>
	-- 1950s: Now known as United Utilities Inc., the company expands  
and modernizes telephone service to 40,000 customers in Missouri 
and Kansas. 
</P>
<P>
	-- 1960s: United purchases other companies and emerges as the  
third largest telephone system in the country, moves headquarters 
to suburban Westwood, Kan. 
</P>
<P>
	-- 1968: William G. McGowan, takes over Microwave Communications  
Inc., forerunner to MCI. 
</P>
<P>
	-- 1969: MCI gets license to operate long-distance service from  
St. Louis to Chicago using microwave-radio transmission technology 
instead of underground cables. 
</P>
<P>
	-- 1974: MCI and Justice Department sue AT&AMP;T on antitrust  
grounds. 
</P>
<P>
	-- 1980: MCI victorious in antitrust case; is awarded damages.  
AT&AMP;T continues to challenge the government's antitrust suit in 
court. 
</P>
<P>
	-- 1982: The Justice Department and AT&AMP;T settlement breaks up the  
Bell system. AT&AMP;T split into regional companies that become known 
as the ``Baby Bells.'' 
</P>
<P>
	-- 1983: MCI becomes first U.S. competitor to AT&AMP;T  
internationally, establishing service between the United States and 
Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	-- 1983: Long Distance Discount Services (LDDS) founded as a long  
distance reseller in Mississippi; later known as WorldCom. 
</P>
<P>
	-- 1985: Bernard J. Ebbers, becomes LDDS president and chief  
executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	-- 1986: United and GTE agree to merge long-distance subsidiaries  
into US Sprint. 
</P>
<P>
	-- 1988: United announces it will buy controlling interest in  
Sprint from GTE. 
</P>
<P>
	-- 1990: William T. Esrey takes over as chairman of United.  
</P>
<P>
	-- 1991: MCI introduces the ``Friends &AMP; Family'' program,  
entitling users to 20 percent savings, to stimulate long-distance 
calling and lure customers from AT&AMP;T. 
</P>
<P>
	-- 1992: United changes name to Sprint Corp.  
</P>
<P>
	-- 1993: British Telecommunications PLC purchases 20 percent of  
MCI Communications Corp. for $ 4.3 billion to provide global 
communications services. 
</P>
<P>
	-- 1993: Sprint becomes the only major U.S. telecommunications  
company providing long distance, local and wireless services after 
merger with Centel Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	-- 1994: Sprint announces plan to join a global partnership with  
Deutsche Telekom and France Telecom, which begins doing business in 
1996 as Global One. 
</P>
<P>
	-- 1994: LDDS acquires IDB WorldCom, the fourth ranked carrier of  
international long distance calls: Company renamed itself WorldCom 
Inc. in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	-- 1996: WorldCom buys MFS Communications for $12 billion.  
bringing its WorldCom local telephone network newly acquired UUNet 
Technologies Inc., an Internet network. 
</P>
<P>
	-- 1996: British Telecommunications PLC agrees to buy remaining  
80 percent of MCI for $ 20.8 billion the biggest foreign takeover 
of a U.S. company. 
</P>
<P>
	-- 1997: Sprint acquires PCS wireless licenses.  
</P>
<P>
	-- 1998: WorldCom Inc. acquires MCI Communications Inc. to form  
MCI WorldCom for $34.7 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	-- 1999: Sprint dedicates its $920 million corporate campus in  
Overland Park on Oct. 1; takeover by MCI WorldCom Inc. announced on 
Oct. 5. 
</P>
<P>
	-- 1999: In the largest corporate takeover in history, MCI  
WorldCom Inc. announces a $115 billion acquisition of Sprint Corp. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991005.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-05 07:40:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets closed generally higher  
Tuesday following overnight gains on Wall Street as fears eased of 
a possible rise in U.S. interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed up  
20.44 points, or 0.12 percent, to 17,784.15. The average closed up 
51.15 points, or 0.29 percent, the previous day. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo stocks rose moderately as investors awaited the U.S.  
Federal Reserve's policy meeting later in the day. 
</P>
<P>
	Although many expect the Federal Reserve to leave key rates  
unchanged, investors will be looking for any indication of bias in 
favor of future tightening of monetary policy, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Share prices were also supported by the announcement of a new  
Cabinet in Tokyo on Tuesday, marking the beginning of Japan's new 
three-party governing coalition. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 106.60 yen,  
up 0.49 yen from late Monday in Tokyo and also above its level of 
106.30 yen overnight in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, the blue-chip Hang Seng Index rose 123.03 points,  
or 1 percent, closing at 12,998.89. On Monday, the index had gained 
142.62 points, or 1.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers said share prices opened higher on the back of a rally  
overnight on Wall Street, where the Dow Jones industrial average 
gained 128.23, or 1.25 percent, to 10,401.23. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong investors also believe a U.S. interest rate hike is  
unlikely, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	Malaysian shares surged on a combination of factors, including a  
technical rebound from weeks of decline and on overnight gains on 
Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange's Composite Index, which tracks  
100 blue-chip stocks, rose 4 percent, or 27.37 points, to 710.23. 
</P>
<P>
	However, South Korean share prices slumped, with the benchmark  
index shedding 3.3 percent on rumors there will be more 
investigation of allegations of tax evasion and illegal fundraising 
by a major conglomerate. 
</P>
<P>
	The Korea Composite Stock Price Index fell 26.82 points to  
791.55. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Share prices closed higher as investors shrugged off  
concerns of a possible U.S. interest rate hike. The benchmark 
Straits Times Index rose 26.85 points, or 1.3 percent, to 2,064.72. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian shares closed higher on continued positive  
sentiment over the smooth progress of the country's electoral 
assembly, tasked with electing the next president. The Composite 
Index rose 10.947 points, or 2 percent, to 566.251. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Taiwan shares closed lower amid concerns over corporate  
earnings after the island's devastating Sept. 21 earthquake, 
analysts said. The market's key Weighted Stock Price Index fell 
128.47 points, or 1.67 percent, to 7,557.01. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed lower. The benchmark  
NZSE-40 Capital Index fell 9.46 points, or 0.4 percent, to 
2,036.16. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine shares closed lower as foreigners unloaded  
their holdings ahead of the U.S. Federal Open Market Committee 
meeting on interest rates. The 30-company Philippine Stock Exchange 
Index fell 39.52 points, or 1.9 percent, to 2,064.76. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: The Australian share market closed higher, with higher  
gold prices boosting gold stocks, offsetting weakness among the 
major banking stocks. The All Ordinaries index rose 21.7 points, or 
0.7 percent, to 2,917.2. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai share prices closed slightly higher. The Stock  
Exchange of Thailand index rose 2.81 points, or 0.7 percent, to 
398.94. 
  	   	
</P>
