<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Charlotte WNBA Seeks Extension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- The WNBA is close to completing talks  
aimed at locking the Charlotte Sting into a long-term relationship 
to stay in the city, officials said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're in the midst of negotiating a new deal for the Sting. It  
will be for more than one year,'' Sam Russo, the team's executive 
vice president of business, said in an interview with The 
Associated Press. ``We will have the Sting in Charlotte for an 
extended period of time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some media reports over the summer questioned whether the  
franchise, a charter member of the WNBA, had a future in Charlotte 
because of sagging attendance. WNBA commissioner Val Ackerman said 
in late July that such reports were premature and that the league 
preferred to keep a team in Charlotte. 
</P>
<P>
	``As far as Charlotte goes, the WNBA operating committees are  
having discussions and working out the specifics of the agreement 
right now,'' league spokesman Mark Pray said Monday. He said there 
was no specific timetable established to conclude talks that would 
set up the Sting to play in the WNBA for a fourth year and beyond. 
</P>
<P>
	Charlotte was among the league leaders in attendance its first  
two seasons, but the Sting got off to a slow start this year, 
struggling to stay near the .500 mark. Charlotte rallied in the 
final half of the season, made the playoffs for the third time in 
as many years and wound up averaging 7,081 fans. 
</P>
<P>
	Russo said the WNBA would work with the Sting to try to devise  
marketing strategies to increase crowds at the Charlotte Coliseum. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our organization has put in a lot of hours and effort to make  
this successful,'' Russo said. ``So having the opportunity to 
continue down the road with it is gratifying. It would have been a 
shame if we could not go down the road.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sting have traditionally been strong at attracting family  
crowds -- one or two parents taking their children to games. Where 
the Sting want to improve is in drawing more support from 
Charlotte's substantial corporate community, Russo said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every market has its little nuances that we still have to work  
on in Charlotte. We haven't gotten there yet,'' he said. ``But I 
don't believe it's a reason to give up on the market, and I think 
the WNBA realizes that this is a good market. And once we work 
together to find out what the real problems are and how we can 
rectify them, I think we'll be able to turn this market around.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 12-team WNBA, which is to add expansion franchises next  
season in Indianapolis, Miami, Portland and Seattle, has focused on 
marketing the overall league in its first three seasons. The league 
plans to expand its marketing approach to concentrate on helping 
individual franchises address local attendance issues. 
</P>
<P>
	``We expect to have all the same teams,'' Pray said. ``We don't  
have any plans to relocate any teams.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
