<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Agriculture Trying To Lure Students / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DECATUR, Ill. (AP) -- When the agriculture instructor at Richland  
Community College asked 2,000 high school students on a field day 
who was interested in a career in agriculture, only one raised his 
hand. 
</P>
<P>
	``They say, 'Well, that's driving a tractor,''' instructor Dan  
Dunphy said. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. employers seek to fill about 48,000 jobs each year in food  
and agricultural sciences, but only 46,000 graduates have training 
or education specifically in those areas, according to a U.S. 
Agriculture Department study. 
</P>
<P>
	In Illinois, agriculture and closely related jobs employ 1.5  
million people. 
</P>
<P>
	But fewer students have been entering agriculture as a career  
because they view it as a dying or backward occupation, according 
to farm agencies and educators like Dunphy. 
</P>
<P>
	In response, a growing number of programs are directed at  
showing students that agriculture is more than just driving a 
tractor. 
</P>
<P>
	``Agriculture is chemistry, satellite communications, marketing  
and economics, in addition to traditional farming,'' Dunphy said. 
``There is still a big demand for ag jobs, and the variety is so 
vast.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fewer children grow up on farms today, leading to a decline in  
interest in agricultural careers, according to Jay Runner, 
coordinator of a state program called Facilitating Coordination in 
Agriculture Education. 
</P>
<P>
	``The declining agricultural population base has left most  
people ignorant about where their food and fiber comes from,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Runner's program has a $2 million state-funded budget, five  
field advisers and partnerships with the Illinois Farm Bureau, 
University of Illinois Extension and Soil and Water Conservation 
districts throughout the state. 
</P>
<P>
	Runner said 17,000 students are now in high school agriculture  
programs, a 46 percent increase from seven years ago. Most are 
urban residents, and 30 percent are female. 
</P>
<P>
	The new agriculture curriculum has a heavy emphasis on science,  
horticulture, finance and computer technology -- the more modern 
applications of the field. 
</P>
<P>
	The Macon County Farm Bureau recently stepped up its ``Ag in the  
Classroom'' program to expose grade school students to 
opportunities in agriculture. 
</P>
<P>
	Information director Lisa Cobb, who has shown students how to  
make a plastic-like material out of corn starch and homemade ice 
cream, said even children in traditional farming communities seem 
to be out of touch with the importance of agriculture. 
</P>
<P>
	``They know crops are used for food, but they don't realize all  
the different products that are made,'' Cobb said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson Naylor, 22, graduated in May from the business  
administration program at Millikin University. As an intern, he 
handled high-tech equipment and computer accounting programs for 
the Macon office of Corn Belt FS, a farm supply company. He was 
hired immediately upon graduation. 
</P>
<P>
	Naylor said his fellow students understood why he wanted to go  
into agriculture, but only because they knew he grew up on a farm. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had an appreciation of farming,'' he said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
