<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bilingual Education Foe Wants Senate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Ron Unz, the software entrepreneur who  
helped pay for the campaign that ended most bilingual education in 
California, will seek the Republican nomination for Democratic Sen. 
Dianne Feinstein's seat. 
</P>
<P>
	Unz, 38, said Tuesday that he will focus on dismantling  
bilingual education nationally and reforming a campaign finance 
system he called corrupt. 
</P>
<P>
	His advantages include a personal fortune from the software  
industry and name recognition. Unz bankrolled a substantial part of 
the campaign last year for Proposition 227, which repealed 
bilingual education programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Unz is also sponsoring a campaign finance reform initiative on  
the March ballot. He financed his own unsuccessful campaign against 
incumbent Pete Wilson for the Republican nomination for governor in 
1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Feinstein so far has no opposition for the Democratic  
nomination in the March 7 primary. San Diego County Supervisor Bill 
Horn and state Sen. Ray Haynes of Riverside are also expected to 
run for the GOP nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1994, Unz opposed the anti-illegal immigrant measure  
Proposition 187, which most Republicans supported. But in 1996, he 
backed Proposition 209, which ended state-sponsored affirmative 
action. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
