<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mets Fly to Phoenix To Face D-Backs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- With the smell of champagne probably still in  
their hair, the New York Mets flew to Phoenix to face the Arizona 
Diamondbacks and one of the game's most intimidating pitchers, 
Randy Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets celebrated as if they'd won the World Series after  
their 5-0 victory over Cincinnati in Monday night's wild-card 
playoff game. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got a good, fun feeling on our flight to Phoenix,'' said  
Al Leiter, the Mets' hero. ``Hopefully we can do some damage down 
there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Manager Bobby Valentine, who will make his first postseason  
appearance, said that the way this team came back from the edge of 
oblivion, bouncing back to play tonight should be a piece of cake. 
</P>
<P>
	``If anyone questions what this team can do,'' he said, ``I'd  
like to hold you at bay. They've answered the bell. They've taken 
shots to the body and shots below the belt and come out swinging 
and won the title.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Well, at least they've won a spot in the postseason.  
</P>
<P>
	Now, reliever John Franco said, the pressure is gone.  
</P>
<P>
	``There's a weight off our shoulders,'' he said. ``Last week, we  
were at the bottom of the barrel, the bottom of the hill. Now we've 
got a second life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New York will start Masato Yoshii, who hopes things go a lot  
better against Johnson than they did when the two faced off on May 
26 in New York. In that game, Yoshii was shelled for seven runs in 
2 2-3 innings. Among the eight hits he surrendered were two by 
Johnson, including a two-out RBI single that knocked Yoshii out of 
the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, meanwhile, struck out 10 in eight innings in a 10-1  
victory. 
</P>
<P>
	But this is the playoffs, where Johnson has had more than his  
fair share of misfortune. His five consecutive postseason losses 
tie a major league record. 
</P>
<P>
	Those losses, like his 17-9 record this year, hardly reflect how  
well he's pitched. Johnson has a 3.41 ERA to go with his 2-5 
playoff record. So he sees no need to defend himself as he prepares 
to pitch in Arizona's opener. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you look at the postseason, I've pitched pretty well,''  
Johnson said. ``It's not like I've been a total flop. People just 
look at the numbers and they want wins, and that's all I want. 
</P>
<P>
	``More than probably anybody in the clubhouse on the day I  
pitch, that's all I want to do is win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The only other pitchers to lose five postseason games in a row  
are Joe Bush from 1914-23 and Doyle Alexander from 1973-87. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson seems poised to end his losing streak. He is coming off  
a season in which he struck out a career-best 364, fourth-most in 
baseball history. He pitched a career-high 271 2-3 innings and led 
the NL with a 2.48 ERA. Only the inability of his team to score 
runs for him, including an amazing four-game stretch when he was 
0-4 with a 1.41 ERA, but Arizona failed to score a single run, 
prevented him from amassing a Pedro Martinez-like win-loss record. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel I'm coming off the best year of my career, and I want  
to take that into the postseason and be extremely focused,'' 
Johnson said. ``Much like the regular season, I'll lay it all on 
the line.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, after his midseason trade from Seattle to Houston,  
Johnson was 0-2 in the divisional series against San Diego. In the 
opener, he pitched eight strong innings, but lost 2-1 to Kevin 
Brown. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot is riding on that first game,'' Johnson said. ``I can  
only go out and pitch as good as I can pitch. I've lost some close 
games. I feel I pitched extremely well last year in Game 1 and we 
lost. Did I choke? I don't think I did. I tip my hat to Kevin 
Brown. He pitched better than I did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Diamondbacks worked out Monday without knowing whether their  
first-round opponent would be the Mets or Houston Astros. Manager 
Buck Showalter was preparing extensive scouting reports on both 
potential foes. 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona was 7-2 against the Mets, including a three-game sweep  
in New York May 28-30, part of the slump that led to the firing of 
three Mets coaches. 
</P>
<P>
	Showalter shrugged off that long-ago sweep.  
</P>
<P>
	``With all the stuff they were going through at the time, that  
doesn't mean anything,'' he said. ``They're as talented a club as 
there is in our league.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Diamondbacks hit .316 against New York pitching. Luis  
Gonzalez hit .441, Jay Bell .375 and Tony Womack .364. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
