<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Strange May Be Next Ryder Cup Boss  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Curtis Strange, who hasn't won since his second straight U.S.  
Open in 1989, was the topic of conversation at the Buick Challenge 
-- before the tournament began, after his first-round 77 and even 
after missing the cut despite a 66. 
</P>
<P>
	Why?  
</P>
<P>
	All signs point toward him as the front-runner to be the next  
Ryder Cup captain. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody would be interested,'' Strange said. ``Everybody  
would treat it as a tremendous honor to go to the Belfry and be a 
captain. But I haven't talked to anybody, so I don't know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Strange fits the perfect profile to be the next captain. He will  
be 46 when the 2001 Ryder Cup is played, is still very involved 
with the current crop of stars and is not hurt by his work as a 
television analyst for ABC Sports. He also has player support. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Curtis would do a great job,'' Justin Leonard said.  
``I don't know who the PGA of America is thinking about, but he 
would be on my short list.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Strange also got a strong endorsement from Davis Love III, who  
described him as a ``co-captain'' with Lanny Wadkins at Oak Hill, 
where Strange was a captain's pick. 
</P>
<P>
	``He knew the things to do to pump you up and keep you lose,''  
Love said. ``I think he would be a great captain.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The PGA of America will announce the new captain before the end  
of this year. 
</P>
<P>
	One thing is clear -- the next U.S. captain could be saddled with  
additional responsibilities -- namely, damage control -- if the furor 
over this year's Ryder Cup doesn't calm. 
</P>
<P>
	After the last uproar at Kiawah Island in 1991 -- the ``War on  
the Shore'' -- the PGA of America sent five-time British Open 
champion Tom Watson to the Belfry as its captain. Clearly, a 
captain regarded as a great ambassador might not be a bad idea. 
</P>
<P>
	Where does that leave Strange?  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know how he's perceived over there,'' Love said. ``But  
I know he's tough enough to handle whatever happens.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *HALL HAPPENINGS:* For the second consecutive year, no player  
from the International ballot received enough votes to be elected 
into the World Golf Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	The PGA Tour ballot, featuring Greg Norman and Ben Crenshaw, has  
yet to be mailed. That means as of now, Juli Inkster and Beth 
Daniel will be the only inductees at the 2000 ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
	The question is when that ceremony will take place.  
</P>
<P>
	The World Golf Village at St. Augustine has decided to move the  
induction from the Monday of The Players Championship in late March 
until after the season in November. Executive director Ruffin 
Beckwith said one possibility is to hold the ceremony in 
conjunction with the PGA Tour awards luncheon. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials are hopeful a November induction would allow more  
players to watch their peers get inducted. The March date made it 
virtually impossible for LPGA Tour members to attend since that is 
the week of their first major, the Dinah Shore. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *DOWN THE ROAD:* Two weeks after their raucous Ryder Cup  
celebration before a rowdy hometown crowd at Brookline, Mass., Tom 
Lehman, Mark O'Meara and Payne Stewart could be in for a rude 
reception this week at St. Andrews. 
</P>
<P>
	The three Ryder Cup players comprise the U.S. team for the  
Dunhill Cup. The British gallery is expected to be quick to remind 
them what it's like on foreign soil. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm making my plans to fly over and secure a couple of big,  
burly guys for security,'' Lehman said. 
</P>
<P>
	And don't forget Valderrama, site of a raucous victory for  
Europe in the 1997 Ryder Cup, and the end-of-the-year World Golf 
Championship event. 
</P>
<P>
	Justin Leonard wonders how the Spanish gallery will treat U.S.  
Ryder Cup players, particularly since the 17th green celebration 
disrupted the chances of Jose Maria Olazabal. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I'll catch some flak,'' Leonard said. ``I'm hoping  
that people start to put that behind them, but I'm sure I'll 
encounter some things that we wouldn't have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Would it cause him to think about not going to Spain this year?  
</P>
<P>
	``I'll probably wait until the event,'' Leonard said. ``Right  
now, I have every intention of going.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *RYDER RINGS:* Davis Love III compares winning the Ryder Cup to  
any other team championship, such as a World Series or Super Bowl. 
The players can even dress the part, thanks to rings captain Ben 
Crenshaw gave them. 
</P>
<P>
	The only difference?  
</P>
<P>
	Crenshaw gave them rings BEFORE the matches.  
</P>
<P>
	``It was Monday night at the Oyster House,'' Love said. ``He  
said, 'Super Bowl teams get their rings after they win. I'm going 
to give you guys this Monday night. That's how good I feel about 
this.' `` 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SPLIT SERGIO:* Sergio Garcia plans to divide his time between  
the PGA Tour and the European tour next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Garcia, who finished third in the Nelson Classic and runner-up  
to Tiger Woods in the PGA Championship, is 49th on the PGA Tour 
money list and has secured his card. He also has his European card, 
having won twice in nine tournaments. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not sure where I'll play most, but I wanted to get both  
cards because I enjoy playing both tours,'' Garcia said after a 
playoff victory in Germany. ``I feel very comfortable in the United 
States, but I also want to play in Europe. It's my continent, it's 
where I grew up.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *STAT OF THE WEEK:* Greg Norman (No. 51) and Bernhard Langer  
(No. 54) have fallen out of the top 50 in the world rankings for 
the first time since its inception in 1986. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *FINAL WORD:* ``We were a half-point away from Europe not  
complaining about the crowd, and a half-point away from Justin 
(Leonard) getting hammered.'' -- Paul Azinger on the Ryder Cup. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
