<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Mostly Down But Up Vs. Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar rose against the Japanese yen Tuesday  
but fell against most other major currencies after the Federal 
Reserve brought down U.S. stocks and bonds with a hint of a future 
interest rate hike. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, dollar rose to 106.41 yen from 106.23  
yen Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	But other leading currencies gained against the dollar as U.S.  
financial markets stumbled. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro rose to $1.0743 from $1.0735 and the British pound  
edged up to $1.6565 from $1.6559. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Reserve, which has raised short-term interest rates  
twice since June in an attempt to keep the economy from 
overheating, left rates unchanged Tuesday. But it also warned it 
now is leaning toward raising rates in the future and would be 
especially watchful for signs of inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	In response, stock and bond markets -- spooked by the thought of  
higher interest rates -- turned lower, leading to a sympathetic 
selloff by currency traders. 
</P>
<P>
	``If our stock and bond markets aren't attractive to foreigners,  
they won't buy dollars,'' explained Grant Wilson, senior foreign 
exchange trader at Mellon Bank. ``There will be less of a demand 
for dollars to buy our assets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4815 Swiss francs, down from  
1.4829, and 1.4718 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4697. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on Tuesday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8206  
German marks, down from 1.8219; 6.1059 French francs, down from 
6.1105; and 1,802.36 Italian lire, down from 1,803.70. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
