<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rugby Officials Assail Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARDIFF, Wales (AP) -- Two players were suspended for the rest of  
group play at the Rugby World Cup, a move organizers hope sends a 
clear signal that ``gratuitous violence will not be tolerated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Colin Charvis of Wales and Roberto Grau of Argentina were cited  
following a fight during Wales' 23-18 victory in Friday's 
tournament opener. 
</P>
<P>
	A day later, Siua Taumalolo of Tonga was banned for 21 days for  
high tackling. Brendan Reilly of Samoa and Jose Miguel Villau of 
Spain escaped suspensions despite being cited for punching. 
</P>
<P>
	Tim Gresson, the International Rugby Board's chairman of  
referees and a member of the Rugby World Cup disciplinary 
committee, said Tuesday the IRB and the Rugby World Cup will not 
``tolerate wanton, unnecessary violence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Rugby is a tough, physical game but there's no reason it can't  
be played within the rules,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	IRB disciplinary officer Steve Griffiths said he hoped the  
suspensions acted as a deterrent. 
</P>
<P>
	Like hockey, rugby appears to accept that violence is inevitable  
in such a contact sport. But the rulemakers are trying to control 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a theory that the odd scrap is just part of rugby but  
the IRB is determined o get rid of gratuitous violence and foul 
play in rugby,'' Gresson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If anything is calculated to alienate people from the game,  
it's foul play. There is real potential for players to be turned 
off due to gratuitous violence.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
