<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> L.A. Makes Last Pitch for NFL Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Real estate mogul Ed Roski delivered a  
sealed, 11th-hour bid for an NFL team at the Coliseum, bolstered by 
letters of support from city and county leaders and a pledge of 
$100 million in public money, a city councilman said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal is the latest for an NFL team in Los Angeles and  
will compete with bids from Hollywood super agent Michael Ovitz, 
who hopes to build a stadium at Hollywood Park racetrack near Los 
Angeles, and Robert McNair on behalf of Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	Roski went to Atlanta on Tuesday to deliver the bid containing a  
proposal that will be ``far more competitive than anyone else in 
California,'' Councilman Mark Ridley-Thomas said. 
</P>
<P>
	A few hours later, NFL expansion committee members began meeting  
in Georgia, supposedly to make a recommendation for the NFL owners 
session Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ridley-Thomas said Roski carried letters of support from Mayor  
Richard Riordan and the chairman of the county Board of 
Supervisors, committing as much as $100 million in public money 
with no risk to the city or county's general fund. 
</P>
<P>
	He did not explain how the funding would work. The NFL's demand  
for public money has been a major stumbling block for Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Sources told the Houston Chronicle that McNair was prepared to  
offer $700 million for the franchise in what would be the most ever 
paid for any professional sports team. 
</P>
<P>
	Ovitz was expected to offer much less. Ridley-Thomas didn't  
reveal the total of Roski's offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Ridley-Thomas said he didn't expect a final decision on the  
NFL's 32nd franchise this week. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he had ``a very fruitful exchange'' during a 45-minute  
phone call with NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue earlier Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the most promising option that the NFL will find  
anywhere in Southern California,'' Ridley-Thomas said of the 
Coliseum. ``I think the commissioner got the message today, that it 
would be a huge mistake to miss this opportunity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The selection process has stretched over a year. Several  
promoters have vied for the franchise and the state appointed a 
representative to help, but he quit in frustration. The NFL set 
deadlines, then ignored them. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the NFL failed to place a person in Los Angeles to  
make this deal, a point person. They have never done that. They 
committed to setting a franchise fee and never did it. They said 
they were going to do it, they never did,'' Ridley-Thomas said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The larger issue is it's hard to get the league to play by one  
set of rules. It's hard to know what those rules are. It's like 
they're making up the rules as they go along.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
