<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Michigan Utilities To Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Two Michigan utilities are combining in a $2.6  
billion deal that will create the state's largest electric and gas 
company with more than 2 million customers. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the deal announced today, DTE Energy Co., parent of  
Detroit Edison Co., will buy MCN Energy Group, parent of Michigan 
Consolidated Gas Co., for $28.50 per share in cash and stock. 
</P>
<P>
	DTE will also be assuming about $2 billion in MCN debt in the  
deal. 
</P>
<P>
	The new company, based in Detroit, will be the largest electric  
and gas utility in Michigan with about 11,500 employees, 2.1 
million electric customers and 1.2 million natural gas customers. 
</P>
<P>
	The boards of both companies have approved the deal, which is  
subject to approval from shareholders and regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	When the transaction closes, expected in six to nine months, it  
will create DTE Energy Company, the utilities said. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined company will be able to market coal, gas and  
electricity in the region and to compete more effectively in the 
development of new power plants and distributed generation, the 
companies said. 
</P>
<P>
	DTE chairman Anthony F. Earley Jr. said the combined company  
will ``more effectively pursue growth and expansion opportunities 
available in the region spanning the corridor from the Great Lakes 
to the Northeast.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That corridor accounts for about half of the nation's total  
energy consumption, Earley said. 
</P>
<P>
	MichCon and Detroit Edison will retain their corporate  
identities and be operated as subsidiaries of DTE, the statement 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	No layoffs were planned, Detroit Edison spokesman Lew Layton  
said. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
