<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Sink on Interest Rate Worry / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Treasury bonds plummeted Tuesday after Federal  
Reserve policy-makers said they are leaning toward raising interest 
rates to hold down inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 1 7/32  
points, or $12.18 3/4 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves 
in the opposite direction, rose to 6.17 percent from 6.08 percent 
late Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The central bank's policy-setting Federal Reserve Open Market  
Committee left short-term interest rates unchanged Tuesday as 
expected by Wall Street economists and traders. But the Fed also 
said it was being extra vigilant about the risks of rising 
inflation and now is leaning toward raising rates in the future. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed already has raised short-term interest rates twice since  
June and many traders were hoping the central bank was through 
tightening credit for the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors who had been betting the Fed would keep a neutral  
stance toward interest rates started selling Treasurys after the 
central bank's midafternoon announcement. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said the Fed's decision likely will leave the market  
volatile in coming weeks as investors scour economic data in an 
attempt to predict how the Fed will act. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
fell 3/16 point to 1/4 point, while intermediate maturities fell 1/2 
point to 3/4 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information 
service. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading, the yield on three-month Treasury was 4.85  
percent, as the discount fell 0.01 point from Monday's auction to 
4.72 percent. The six-month yield was 5.11 percent as the discount 
rose 0.04 percentage point from the weekly auction to 4.91 percent. 
One-year yields rose to 5.31 percent as the discount rose 0.07 
percentage point from late Monday to 5.04 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, fell to 5 percent from 5.25 percent late Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 3/8 to 111 1/2. The average yield to 
maturity of the index was 5.93 percent, up from 5.91 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
