<HEADLINE> First Lady Offered Baseball Wager </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Majority Leader Dick Armey, whose  
relations with the White House have often been unfriendly, 
challenged first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton to a ``friendly 
wager'' Tuesday over the baseball playoff between the New York 
Yankees and the Texas Rangers. 
</P>
<P>
	Armey, R-Texas, who is fond of quoting from country-and-western  
songs, said he would sing Frank Sinatra's ``New York, New York'' if 
the Yankees win the American League playoff series. If the Rangers 
win, the first lady has to sing Sinatra's ``Chicago.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans have made much of the fact that Mrs. Clinton, who is  
considering a run for the Senate from New York, is an Illinois 
native who has not lived in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many wonder if she has actually ever read a Yankees box score.  
That's why I'm inviting the first lady to take up this wager,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Armey's frequent criticisms of Mrs. Clinton -- he once called her  
a Marxist -- led to a shouting match with President Clinton during 
the 1996 budget talks. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton is currently traveling in Poland and there was no  
immediate response to Armey's offer. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
