<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obuchi Announces New Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi named a new Cabinet  
today, inaugurating a coalition government that will have a 
commanding majority in both houses of Parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	The reshuffle, which was delayed while the government dealt with  
last week's nuclear accident, was aimed at both strengthening the 
position of Obuchi's Liberal Democratic Party in Parliament and 
bolstering his efforts to pull Japan out of its worst economic 
downturn in decades. 
</P>
<P>
	The new Cabinet was to be formally sworn in by Emperor Akihito  
later today. 
</P>
<P>
	Stressing the need for continuity, Obuchi retained his top  
economic advisors -- Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa and Economic 
Planning Agency head Taichi Sakaiya -- in the new 18-member Cabinet. 
</P>
<P>
	Miyazawa called today for more government spending to spur  
recovery from Japan's worst economic downturn in 50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``More pushes are needed,'' he told reporters at the prime  
minister's official residence. 
</P>
<P>
	He also described the current condition of Japan's economy as  
better overall than a year earlier, though he said corporate 
capital investment remains slow. 
</P>
<P>
	Hakuo Yanagisawa, head of the Financial Reconstruction  
Commission, a Japanese government body overseeing banking industry 
reform, will be replaced by the ruling Liberal Democratic Party's 
financial issues chief, Michio Ochi. 
</P>
<P>
	Ochi has served twice as minister for economic planning and is a  
former Finance Ministry bureaucrat. 
</P>
<P>
	Obuchi also named Yohei Kono to be the new foreign minister, and  
gave Takashi Fukaya the trade portfolio. Kono has previously held 
the post of foreign minister, and Fukaya was formerly minister of 
posts and telecommunications. 
</P>
<P>
	Obuchi is generally credited with sparking a glimmer of recovery  
with a bank bailout and public spending packages, and public 
opinion polls indicate he is one of the most popular prime 
ministers Japan has had in years. 
</P>
<P>
	He easily won re-election Sept. 21 as head of his party, taking  
about 70 percent of the votes in a three-way contest. 
</P>
<P>
	The approval rating for his Cabinet soared to a record 48  
percent in October, up 16 percent from last month, according to the 
Mainichi newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	But the poll also found that a majority were opposed to the  
three-party coalition involving Obuchi's Liberal Democratic Party, 
the Liberal Party and the New Komeito party. 
</P>
<P>
	The Liberals were already in the old coalition government, which  
only had a majority in the lower house. With the Komeito, the 
coalition controls the majority in the upper house as well. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-party ruling bloc will command over 350 seats in the  
500-seat House of Representatives, the lower house of Japan's 
parliament, and more than half of the 252-seat House of 
Councillors, the upper house. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
