<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fed Reserve Vice Chairman Sworn In </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Roger W. Ferguson, a Harvard-trained economist  
and lawyer, was sworn in Tuesday as vice chairman of the Federal 
Reserve. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan administered the oath to  
Ferguson, 47, who was nominated by President Clinton to fill a 
vacancy created by the departure of Alice Rivlin in July. 
</P>
<P>
	In making that announcement this summer, Clinton said Ferguson  
would be the first African American to hold the post of vice 
chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate confirmed Ferguson's nomination last Wednesday.  
</P>
<P>
	Clinton appointed Ferguson to the seven-member Fed board of  
governors two years ago. He has focused much of his attention on 
technical matters, including overseeing the Fed's plans to deal 
with the Year 2000 computer problem and heading a panel that is 
searching for ways to upgrade the central bank's check-clearing 
operations for commercial banks. 
</P>
<P>
	Ferguson is a former partner at the consulting firm of McKinsey  
&AMP; Co., where he specialized in the management of 
information-technology systems. 
</P>
<P>
	He is the third black to serve on the Fed board, following  
Andrew Brimmer, nominated by Lyndon Johnson in 1966, and Emmett 
Rice, nominated by Jimmy Carter in 1979. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
