<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-05 15:30:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stalled Steelers Plan No Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Kordell Stewart has led two touchdown drives  
in seven games against teams not named the Browns. His offensive 
line collapsed against Jacksonville, resulting in two safeties in 
five minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	Who said the Pittsburgh Steelers' offense couldn't score -- even  
if it is for the other team? 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart's confidence admittedly is fragile, his protection in  
the pocket even more so. Two home games into a new season that is 
fast resembling how last season ended, the Steelers' starting 
offense has yet to score a touchdown. For the most part, it hasn't 
come close. 
</P>
<P>
	It doesn't get much worse than this: the Steelers' offensive  
starters have been outscored two straight games by the opposing 
defense, which might be an NFL first. Seattle did so 7-3 in winning 
29-10 on Sept. 26; the Jaguars' defense outscored them 4-3 Sunday 
in a 17-3 victory. 
</P>
<P>
	So where does the Steelers' stationary offense go from here?  
</P>
<P>
	Coach Bill Cowher offered this suggestion Tuesday: How about the  
end zone? 
</P>
<P>
	Dismissing suggestions that big changes are in order, such as  
benching Stewart and playing backup quarterback Mike Tomczak, 
Cowher expects no substantive personnel moves. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked to envision a scenario in which Stewart would be benched  
sometime this season, Cowher said, ``I can't foresee that 
situation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If I thought it was one person, I'd make the change. I don't  
care who it is, because then you're not being fair to everybody,'' 
Cowher said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cowher denied the Steelers (2-2) are hesitant to bench Stewart  
after signing him to a $27 million contract extension only last 
spring. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has nothing to do with what a guy makes or who a guy is,''  
Cowher said. ``The fact that I haven't made a change ought to be 
indicative of the fact that it's not one person.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The offensive line play, among the best in the NFL for years,  
has been substandard. All-Pro center Dermontti Dawson said he has 
never played worse than he did against Seattle. Both tackles, Wayne 
Gandy and Anthony Brown, were beaten on the fourth-quarter safeties 
against Jacksonville. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Stewart's inability to throw downfield, either because  
his receivers aren't open or his protection breaks down, is 
allowing defenses to gang up against the run. Jerome Bettis, the 
No. 2 rusher in team history to Franco Harris, still hasn't had a 
100-yard game, gaining 97 yards on 31 carries the last two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	In his last eight starts, Stewart has one touchdown pass -- in  
the opener against Cleveland -- and 11 interceptions. 
</P>
<P>
	The Steelers' inability to move the ball consistently led Cowher  
to gamble twice Sunday on fourth-and-1 situations. Stewart was 
sacked for a big loss on one play and threw incomplete into the end 
zone on the other. 
</P>
<P>
	``But you still have to be aggressive in thought and action,''  
Cowher said. ``If you lose your aggressiveness, you lose your 
confidence and ability to execute. I didn't lose my aggressiveness 
on fourth-and-1. It might not have been smart, but ...'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991005.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-05 21:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arizona Embraces First Playoffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Like tens of thousands of other fans, Brian  
Landreville dutifully stood for the national anthem before Tuesday 
night's playoff opener between the New York Mets and Arizona 
Diamondbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike the rest, however, he was standing in chlorinated water.  
And wearing just purple swim trunks. 
</P>
<P>
	Playoff baseball, welcome to the desert.  
</P>
<P>
	In a state where folks defy the heat, fans celebrated in a  
ballpark featuring a retractable roof, a mammoth cooling system 
and, to Landreville's delight, a swimming pool just behind the 
right-field fence. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's definitely no better way to watch the game,''  
Landreville said, wading with a view of the field at Bank One 
Ballpark. 
</P>
<P>
	Well, no better way for people able to afford the $4,500 price  
tag to rent the pool area, which also includes a hot tub. 
</P>
<P>
	It actually was around 90 degrees outside -- positively mild by  
Phoenix standards -- and those in the stands 15 minutes before 
gametime marveled at the $354 million stadium's roof opening to a 
flourish of new age music. The game was played under a clear sky. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just incredible,'' said Lori Crawford, who watched the  
roof open from the upper deck. ``The newness hasn't worn off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last season, the five-minute roof opening often was the only  
highlight as the expansion team struggled mightily. Things were 
different the second time around, thanks at least in part to some 
jaw-dropping free agent signings. 
</P>
<P>
	The high price of success wasn't lost on Dan Bleasdale, a season  
ticket holder. 
</P>
<P>
	``We paid a lot of money,'' he said. ``We took a pay increase in  
tickets to get here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Diamondbacks created more than a little ill will late last  
season when they announced a 12 percent average ticket price 
increase during Fan Appreciation Weekend. The team then proceeded 
to shell out big bucks for free agents, including pitchers Randy 
Johnson and Todd Stottlemyre. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, Beth Dodaro was more concerned with the end than the  
means. 
</P>
<P>
	``As soon as we brought in Randy Johnson, we started thinking we  
could go all the way with this,'' Dodaro said. ``We're praying 
every night we're going all the way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson started the best-of-5 series against the Mets.  
</P>
<P>
	``Here we are,'' Chris Peddie said. ``People can say we've  
bought our way into this, but we're here. That's all that matters 
to me.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
