<HEADLINE> Honeywell-Allied Signal Plans Grow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Honeywell Inc. and AlliedSignal Inc. have  
agreed to divest some of their aviation electronics businesses in 
order to win the U.S. Justice Department's clearance of their 
planned merger. 
</P>
<P>
	Honeywell will divest its traffic alert and collision avoidance  
system business, and AlliedSignal will divest its search and 
surveillance weather radar product lines; space and navigation 
business; operations in Cheshire, Conn.; and MEMS microSCIRAS 
guidance technology. The areas accounted for about $250 million in 
1998 revenues. 
</P>
<P>
	The divestitures would represent only about 1 percent of overall  
revenues of the combined company and would not affect future 
earnings significantly, both companies said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement in principle with U.S. regulators leaves only one  
regulatory approval to be cleared before the merger can be 
completed. The companies are still working with the European Union 
Commission to obtain clearance. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today's agreement with the U.S. Department of Justice brings  
us to the final stage for completion of this important merger,'' 
said Michael Bonsignore, Honeywell's chairman and chief executive, 
who will head the merged company. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the European Union Commission has until late December  
to decide whether it will require changes in the alliance, the 
companies said they expect to receive clearance in time to complete 
the merger this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	The merged company will be known as Honeywell International and  
will be headquartered in Morristown, N.J., where AlliedSignal is 
now based. Honeywell's Minneapolis headquarters will be shut down 
after the merger closes. The companies have said about 4,500 
employees will be laid off due to the merger. 
</P>
<P>
	Both companies also confirmed that their third-quarter earnings  
will be in line with expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	AlliedSignal is active in aerospace, automotive and engineered  
materials products. Honeywell specializes in controls and systems 
for homes and buildings, as well as industrial applications for the 
aerospace industry. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
