<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Airways Mechanics Vote on Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- US Airways mechanics voted Tuesday on whether  
to approve a tentative contract agreement with the airline after 
months of contentious negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	Officers of the International Association of Machinists and  
Aerospace Workers endorsed the agreement but said approval of the 
rank and file is uncertain. They warned that the union would strike 
if the contract is defeated. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the contract is rejected and the strike vote is reaffirmed,  
it's not a threat, we will withdraw services within 48 hours,'' 
said the union's lead negotiator, Bill Freiberger. 
</P>
<P>
	The count of ballots cast at union offices across the country  
was not expected until midday Wednesday. Union members were asked 
to vote on two questions: whether to approve the 5-year contract 
agreement, and whether to authorize a strike in case it is not 
approved. 
</P>
<P>
	A strike could hobble the nation's sixth largest airline.  
</P>
<P>
	About 7,500 mechanics, airplane cleaners and other maintenance  
workers for US Airways, based in Arlington, Va., would be covered 
by the contract. 
</P>
<P>
	They already have voted down one potential agreement this year,  
in July, and a strike deadline was averted by just four days when 
federally mediated talks reached the current tentative deal Sept. 
21. 
</P>
<P>
	The use of part-time workers has been among the most contentious  
issues in the dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	Language in the new agreement would allow US Airways to use  
part-time workers to clean aircraft between flights but limit those 
workers to no more than a third of the full-time cleaning work 
force, down from 50 percent in the first agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	The contract also promises immediate bonuses and raises for all  
covered workers. Experienced US Airways mechanics currently earn 
about $23 an hour. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
