<DOCNO> APW19991005.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-05 00:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Riggleman Fired As Cubs Manager </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Jim Riggleman finished third in manager of the  
year balloting a year ago, so successful and popular after taking 
the Chicago Cubs to the playoffs that his contract was extended. 
</P>
<P>
	How quickly it all went away.  
</P>
<P>
	Now, he's without a job, fired after one of the Cubs' worst  
seasons in nearly two decades. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody involved felt that changes were needed, and maybe  
they were right,'' Riggleman said Monday after his dismissal by 
general manager Ed Lynch . 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel badly more than anything for my coaches. They were  
loyal and I'm going down with them. That's one silver lining. We 
will walk out together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Riggleman, coming off a 67-95 season on the heels of a 90-73  
mark and wild-card berth the year before, could never have 
predicted such a collapse. 
</P>
<P>
	He could have blamed the many injuries that ravaged the pitching  
staff, the poor performances of veterans who played so well in 
1998, a farm system that wasn't ready, a few players who were 
unhappy with playing time, or a front office that didn't compensate 
when the season began to crumble. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the 46-year-old Riggleman stood at the end of the Cubs'  
clubhouse, in the same spot where he held postgame news conferences 
for most of his five seasons, and took the blame himself. 
</P>
<P>
	He hinted that, in some areas, he should have been tougher.  
</P>
<P>
	``I know there were some things I probably should have done  
differently during the course of the season, and I didn't do 
them,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just little things that just get away from you. You become  
indebted to what players have done for you and you start letting 
things go when you know in your heart you shouldn't be. The next 
thing you know, it festers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not even Sammy Sosa's 63 homers could save the Cubs, who had the  
second-worst record in the National League and the team's worst 
since 1980, not counting the strike years of 1981 and 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Riggleman had a 374-419 record with the Cubs, including two  
90-game losers and one 90-game winner in the last three seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``It comes down to you got to win ballgames, and we didn't win  
enough,'' Riggleman said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got nobody to blame. I think everybody has to be  
accountable. I'm accountable and this is the result of wins and 
losses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Riggleman, who managed two seasons in San Diego before coming to  
Chicago, couldn't stop a slide that began in early June when the 
Cubs were nine games over .500 and in second place in the NL 
Central. Chicago won only 26 of 77 games after the All-Star break. 
</P>
<P>
	``We underachieved as a team. The numbers don't lie,'' said  
Lynch, who decided to fire Riggleman about a week ago and promised 
the Cubs would be in a ``retooling'' mode next season 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes it is necessary to change the perception or attitude  
or the direction of the club down in the clubhouse, and that's what 
I'm trying to do,'' Lynch added. 
</P>
<P>
	``I deserve a lot of the blame for what has happened here, and I  
accept that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubs offered Riggleman the chance to work in their minor  
league operations. He said he would consider it, but hopes to 
manage again. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd love to manage,'' he said. ``If a good opportunity comes  
up, I would jump at it. I had a good opportunity here, and it 
didn't work out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	First baseman Mark Grace came to Wrigley Field on Monday to say  
goodbye to Riggleman. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not his fault or the staff's. It's the guys between the  
lines, from Sammy to myself to the 25th guy,'' Grace said. ``We 
failed him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The team also fired four coaches and said Cubs Hall of Famer  
Billy Williams, the bench coach with Riggleman, will be interviewed 
for the manager's job. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whoever comes in here will have some work to do,'' Grace  
predicted. ``We have some quality players, but we have some spots 
that need to be filled.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chicago's starting rotation that was a big part of the success a  
year ago fell apart in 1999, starting in spring training when 
Rookie of the Year Kerry Wood blew out his elbow. Steve Trachsel, a 
15-game winner, became an 18-game loser in 1999; and staff ace 
Kevin Tapani, who won 19 games a year ago, was hit by injuries, 
finishing the season on the disabled list with a 6-12 record. 
</P>
<P>
	And veteran players who helped the Cubs to the playoffs in 1998  
couldn't match their performances of a season ago -- namely Lance 
Johnson, Mickey Morandini and Gary Gaetti. For the second straight 
season, Jeff Blauser was a non-factor. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubs ended up with rookie Chad Meyers at second and Jose  
Nieves at short. 
</P>
<P>
	Also fired were pitching coach Marty DeMerritt, third base coach  
Tom Gamboa and first base coach Dan Radison, although the Cubs said 
they would be considered for positions after a new manager is 
hired. Bullpen coach Dave Bialas also was fired but will be offered 
another position. Hitting coach Jeff Pentland will be retained. 
</P>
<P>
	Counting Joe Altobelli, who managed one game, Riggleman was the  
Cubs' sixth manager in the 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	Lynch said Williams is the only person on his list to be  
interviewed and said there was no timetable, but that he wouldn't 
drag out the process for three months. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
