<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hutu Rebels Kill 12 in Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUJUMBURA, Burundi (AP) -- Hutu rebels attacked two neighborhoods  
north of the capital and killed 12 civilians, a local official said 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The rebels, some of whom spoke Kinyarwanda, the language of  
neighboring Rwanda, attacked the Bubanza and Kanga neighborhoods in 
the Kinama district on Monday night, said district chief Idi 
Viragucumura. 
</P>
<P>
	Viragucumura identified the attackers as members of the armed  
wing of Palipehutu, an extremist Hutu party. Various reports 
indicate these rebels occasionally carry out joint raids with 
Rwandan Hutu rebels. 
</P>
<P>
	The attack followed another over the weekend in which five  
people were reported killed, although it was not clear whether they 
were civilians, rebels or Burundian army troops. 
</P>
<P>
	The majority of Burundi's 6.5 million people are Hutus, but the  
minority Tutsis have dominated the army and the administration 
since before the tiny Central African nation gained independence 
from Belgium in 1962. 
</P>
<P>
	Since Tutsi paratroopers in 1993 assassinated the country's  
first democratically elected president, a Hutu, more than 200,000 
people, mainly Hutu civilians, have been killed in fighting between 
the Tutsi-dominated army and Hutu rebels. 
</P>
<P>
	The United Nations Security Council expressed concern Tuesday  
about the recent spate of attacks and the forced relocation of 
about 75 percent of Bujumbura Rural province's population. 
</P>
<P>
	The 15 council members called for and end to the killings,  
looting and destruction and the peace process be revived, council 
president Sergey Lavrov of Russia said. 
</P>
<P>
	The final round of the yearlong peace talks, being held in  
neighboring Tanzania under the mediation of former Tanzanian 
President Julius Nyerere, were postponed for several weeks when 
Nyerere, 78, was hospitalized in London for leukemia. They were 
scheduled to resume this month. 
</P>
<P>
	In the mean time, Burundi's army said last week it had killed 30  
Hutu rebels in cleanup operations in and around the capital, after 
rebels killed at least seven people last week. 
</P>
<P>
	The army has forced more than 200,000 villagers into makeshift  
camps both to deprive rebels of possible support and to clear the 
way for counter attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	World Food Program spokeswoman Christiane Berthiaume said there  
were 267,000 displaced people in the Rural Bujumbura province 
alone, where the agency began distributing food in the camps on 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	In a visit to several camps on Friday, President Pierre Buyoya  
acknowledged that life there was not comfortable. But he said the 
camps were created for people's own protection ``during the current 
exercises to restore security in Bujumbura Rural.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, nine political parties in Burundi announced on Monday  
the establishment of a new political group called National 
Convergence for Peace and Reconciliation. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
